  // --- AGRA TOUR FAQS ---

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-tour-with-female-guide') {
    return [
      { question: "Is a licensed female guide available for the Taj Mahal?", answer: "Yes — this tour is specifically designed to provide a Ministry of Tourism-certified female guide for your [Taj Mahal visit](/india/agra/taj-mahal-ticket-price-2026). Female guides at the Taj Mahal are ASI-licensed professionals who undergo the same rigorous examination and certification as male guides. They carry official government photo ID and are authorized to provide historical commentary inside all federally protected monuments in Agra, including the Taj Mahal and [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort). Booking a dedicated female guide is strongly recommended for solo female travellers, families with young children, and anyone who prefers a more personal, comfortable dynamic." },
      { question: "Is this tour suitable for solo female travellers?", answer: "This tour is specifically optimized for solo female travellers visiting Agra. Having a female local guide creates an immediate sense of safety and comfort — she understands the local environment, knows which areas to avoid, and provides a reassuring presence throughout the visit. The Taj Mahal itself is a well-managed, internationally attended site that is generally safe, but navigating the surrounding streets, touts, and crowded entry areas can feel overwhelming alone. Your female guide handles all logistics, escorts you through security, and ensures you experience the monument without any unwanted interactions. Our [Agra travel guide](/india/agra/things-to-do-in-agra) has more solo travel tips." },
      { question: "What does the female guide cover at the Taj Mahal?", answer: "Your licensed female guide provides a comprehensive historical and architectural narrative covering the complete Taj Mahal complex. The tour begins in the forecourt with the architectural overview — the four minarets, the perfect Persian garden (charbagh), and the optical illusion of the monument appearing larger as you approach. Inside the mausoleum, she explains the Pietra Dura marble inlay technique (semi-precious stones embedded in white marble), the Quranic calligraphy panels, and the cenotaphs of Mumtaz Mahal and Shah Jahan. The love story of Shah Jahan is told with particular depth and emotion. She also explains the astronomical engineering — how the Taj Mahal is aligned to reflect sunrise and sunset light in specific ways." },
      { question: "What should female visitors wear at the Taj Mahal?", answer: "The Taj Mahal is an active Islamic mausoleum and modest dress is strongly recommended. For female visitors: cover shoulders, avoid sleeveless tops or very short skirts, and wear comfortable closed-toe shoes (you must remove footwear before entering the inner mausoleum — overshoes are provided but bare feet on the marble is unavoidable). Loose, breathable cotton is ideal given Agra's heat. Headscarves are not required but are respectful and useful for sun protection on the open terrace. Your female guide will brief you on dress expectations before entry. See our full [Taj Mahal visit tips](/india/agra/taj-mahal-opening-time) for packing recommendations." },
      { question: "Are there separate female entry queues at the Taj Mahal?", answer: "Yes — the Taj Mahal has dedicated separate security queues for female visitors, which are typically significantly shorter than the general queues. Your female guide knows exactly which security lanes are designated for women and leads you directly there, often reducing entry wait times considerably compared to entering without local guidance. The security check involves a bag X-ray and a brief pat-down by female security officers. Items not permitted include food, tobacco, tripods, and selfie sticks. Your guide will advise you what to leave at the security deposit facility to avoid delays." },
      { question: "Is this a private tour or a group tour?", answer: "This is a fully private tour — your female guide works exclusively for you and your companions throughout the visit. There is no shared group, no fixed pace imposed by others, and no compromise on how much time you spend at each viewpoint. This private format is particularly valuable for female travellers who prefer a curated, personal experience rather than moving in a large, impersonal group. The guide tailors the narrative depth, the photography stops, and the pacing entirely to your interests and questions." },
      { question: "Can the female guide also cover Agra Fort?", answer: "Yes — after the Taj Mahal, your female guide can escort you to [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort), the 16th-century Mughal red sandstone fortress that served as the seat of the Mughal Empire. The Agra Fort is approximately 2.5 km from the Taj Mahal and most visitors combine both sites in a single day. From certain towers inside Agra Fort, you can see the Taj Mahal in the distance across the Yamuna river — exactly where Shah Jahan was imprisoned by his son Aurangzeb in the final years of his life, with only a window view of the monument he built for his wife. Combined Taj Mahal + Agra Fort tours typically take 5–6 hours total." },
      { question: "How long does the Taj Mahal tour with a female guide last?", answer: "A standard Taj Mahal tour with your female guide takes approximately 2–3 hours inside the complex. This includes the complete guided walk through the forecourt, the garden, the main platform, and the interior mausoleum. If you add Agra Fort, allow 1.5 additional hours. If you include Mehtab Bagh (the moonlit garden opposite the Taj with perfect rear-view reflections), add another 45 minutes. Total day tour duration depends on your itinerary, but the Taj Mahal alone should never be rushed — the guide will ensure you have sufficient time at each area rather than moving at a speed dictated by group schedules." },
      { question: "What is the best time to visit the Taj Mahal with a female guide?", answer: "**Sunrise** (30 minutes before the 6 AM opening) is the single best time — lower crowds, soft golden light on the white marble, and cooler temperatures. This is especially recommended for female solo travellers as the monument is quieter and more serene. Mid-morning (7–9 AM) is excellent. Midday heat in Agra can be intense from March to June. Late afternoon light (4–6 PM) creates beautiful orange tones on the marble but the monument closes one hour before sunset. Friday is closed entirely. For a complete [Taj Mahal visit planning guide](/india/agra/taj-mahal-opening-time) including seasonal advice, see our dedicated resource." },
      { question: "Is hotel pickup in Agra included?", answer: "Yes — complimentary hotel pickup from your accommodation in Agra is included. Your female guide (or a driver coordinating with her) will collect you from your hotel lobby at the agreed time. For Delhi-based travellers doing a same-day trip, the pickup from your Delhi hotel is also arranged. Simply provide your hotel name and address when booking and the logistics are handled completely. The guide typically confirms pickup details via WhatsApp the evening before your tour, ensuring there is zero ambiguity on the morning of your visit." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-same-day-tour-from-delhi') {
    return [
      { question: "How long does it take to drive from Delhi to Agra?", answer: "The drive from Delhi to Agra takes approximately **3 to 3.5 hours** via the Yamuna Expressway (165 km), a smooth 6-lane highway with minimal traffic compared to older routes. Departure from Delhi hotels is typically at **5:30–6:00 AM** to arrive in Agra by 9 AM — the optimal time for the Taj Mahal visit before midday heat and crowds build. The total same-day round trip (Delhi → Taj Mahal → Agra Fort → Delhi) covers approximately 330 km. An air-conditioned private vehicle makes this journey comfortable. See our full [Delhi to Agra travel guide](/india/agra) for route and timing details." },
      { question: "What time does the same-day tour from Delhi depart and return?", answer: "Departure from Delhi hotels is at **5:30–6:00 AM** to maximise time in Agra. The Taj Mahal is visited from approximately 9:00 AM, followed by Agra Fort (11:30 AM–1:00 PM), and a sit-down lunch at a local restaurant (1:00–2:00 PM). The return drive to Delhi departs Agra at approximately 2:30–3:00 PM, arriving back in Delhi by **6:00–7:00 PM** depending on traffic. This is a long but fully manageable day trip. Most travellers find it rewarding — seeing the Taj Mahal and returning the same day is one of India's classic experiences." },
      { question: "What sites are visited on the same-day Taj Mahal tour from Delhi?", answer: "The standard same-day tour from Delhi covers three sites: (1) **Taj Mahal** — a 2–2.5 hour guided walk through the complete complex, including the interior mausoleum, the Pietra Dura inlay work, and the perfect garden views; (2) **Agra Fort** — the UNESCO-listed 16th-century Mughal fortress where Shah Jahan was imprisoned, with direct views of the Taj Mahal from the Musamman Burj tower; and (3) **Mehtab Bagh** (optional) — the moonlit garden on the opposite bank of the Yamuna with a unique rear-view perspective of the Taj. Lunch at a quality local restaurant is included between Agra Fort and departure." },
      { question: "Are Taj Mahal entry tickets included in the same-day tour from Delhi?", answer: "Entry tickets to the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort are included in this tour package. The Taj Mahal entry fee for foreign nationals is ₹1,300 (approximately $16) plus a separate ₹200 mausoleum fee to enter the inner chamber. Agra Fort entry is ₹650 for foreign nationals. By including these in your tour price, you avoid managing rupee currency, queueing at ticket windows, and the complexity of the online booking system. Your guide handles all ticket logistics on arrival, ensuring you enter without delays." },
      { question: "What vehicle is used for the Delhi to Agra same-day tour?", answer: "An air-conditioned private vehicle is used for all Delhi–Agra same-day tours — typically a Toyota Innova (SUV, seats 6-7) or similar comfortable sedan depending on group size. The vehicle is exclusively yours for the entire day, meaning departure times, lunch duration, and return timing are all flexible to your preferences. The driver is experienced on the Yamuna Expressway route. Wi-Fi is available in most vehicles. For groups of 7 or more, a larger tempo traveller vehicle is provided. Confirm vehicle type when booking based on your group size and comfort requirements." },
      { question: "Is lunch included in the same-day tour from Delhi?", answer: "Yes — a sit-down lunch at a quality restaurant in Agra is included in the same-day tour price. Restaurants are selected for hygiene standards, variety of cuisine (North Indian, continental), and location (typically between Agra Fort and the departure point to minimise travel time). Vegetarian, vegan, Jain, and halal options are available. Inform your guide of any dietary restrictions or allergies at booking so the restaurant can be briefed. The lunch break is approximately 45 minutes–1 hour, timed to avoid the midday heat during the main sightseeing hours." },
      { question: "Is a guide included in the same-day Taj Mahal tour from Delhi?", answer: "Yes — a Ministry of Tourism-licensed professional guide is included and accompanies you throughout the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort. The guide is the most valuable element of this tour — they transform what would otherwise be a simple monument walk into a deep historical and architectural experience. The guide covers the love story of Shah Jahan and Mumtaz Mahal, the 22-year construction timeline, the 20,000 craftsmen involved, the Pietra Dura inlay technique, and the engineering genius of Mughal architecture. Guide commentary is in English as standard; other languages are available on request at booking." },
      { question: "Can I do the same-day tour from Delhi as a solo traveller?", answer: "Yes — solo travellers frequently book this same-day tour from Delhi. The private vehicle and guide format means you are not sharing with strangers (unlike group tours). The pricing for solo travellers is higher per person than groups, but the private experience — flexible timing, direct guide attention, and no waiting for others — is significantly superior. If budget is a priority, we can arrange shared group tours from Delhi with other travellers for a reduced per-person rate. Contact us when booking to discuss the best option for your situation and budget." },
      { question: "Is the Yamuna Expressway safe for the Delhi-Agra drive?", answer: "Yes — the Yamuna Expressway is one of India's safest and best-maintained highways. It is a 165 km, 6-lane divided expressway with no intersections, modern crash barriers, and regular police patrols. All vehicles on the tour are comprehensively insured and driven by experienced, vetted drivers who make this route regularly. Early morning departures (5:30–6 AM) mean the expressway is lightly trafficked, and the drive is smooth and fast. Fog in winter months (December–January) can occasionally slow traffic; your driver monitors conditions and adjusts timing accordingly." },
      { question: "What is the difference between a same-day Delhi-Agra tour by car vs. by train?", answer: "**By car (private vehicle):** Maximum flexibility — depart when you want, stop for photos, adjust timing at each site. No fixed schedule. Door-to-door service from your hotel. Takes 3–3.5 hours each way. **By Gatimaan Express train:** India's fastest train (160 km/h), covers Delhi–Agra in just 1 hour 40 minutes. More comfortable than driving, scenic, and a unique experience. Fixed departure times (departing Hazrat Nizamuddin ~8 AM, returning ~9 PM). See our [Delhi-Agra Gatimaan train tour](/india/agra/delhi-agra-round-trip-gatimaan-train) for train-specific details. For most travellers, the private car offers better overall flexibility; the Gatimaan Express is ideal for train enthusiasts and those short on time." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'same-day-delhi-to-agra-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "Is a same-day trip from Delhi to Agra worth it?", answer: "Yes — the Delhi to Agra same-day trip is one of India's most classic and rewarding day trips. The Taj Mahal is approximately 200 km from Delhi (3–3.5 hours by car on the Yamuna Expressway), and a well-planned day allows you to visit both the Taj Mahal and [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort) comfortably before returning to Delhi by evening. The key to success is an early departure (5:30–6 AM from Delhi) to arrive before crowds build and before the midday heat intensifies. Most travellers returning from a same-day Agra trip describe it as one of the highlights of their India journey." },
      { question: "How long is the drive from Delhi to Agra?", answer: "The drive from Delhi to Agra takes **3 to 3.5 hours** via the Yamuna Expressway — a modern, 6-lane divided highway covering 165 km with virtually no traffic signals or intersections. The NH19 (old highway) takes 4–5 hours due to truck traffic and towns; the expressway is significantly faster and smoother. An early morning departure avoids Delhi city traffic entirely. The return journey to Delhi in the afternoon takes approximately the same time but can vary with expressway traffic volumes. Total round trip driving time: approximately 6–7 hours, leaving 5–6 hours in Agra for sightseeing." },
      { question: "What is the itinerary for the same-day Delhi to Agra tour?", answer: "**5:30–6:00 AM** — Pickup from Delhi hotel. **9:00–11:30 AM** — Taj Mahal visit with licensed guide (full 2.5-hour guided tour). **11:30 AM–1:00 PM** — [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort) visit. **1:00–2:00 PM** — Sit-down lunch at a quality restaurant in Agra. **2:30–3:00 PM** — Departure from Agra. **6:00–7:00 PM** — Arrival back in Delhi. Optional: Mehtab Bagh (baby Taj rear-view garden, 45 min) can be added between Agra Fort and lunch. Optional: Itmad-ud-Daula (Baby Taj) can replace Mehtab Bagh for repeat visitors who prefer a different monument experience." },
      { question: "What is included in the same-day Delhi to Agra tour?", answer: "Included: air-conditioned private vehicle for the full day (Delhi–Agra–Delhi), Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide in Agra, all entry tickets (Taj Mahal + Agra Fort for foreign nationals), and sit-down lunch at a quality restaurant. Not included: personal expenses, tips for the guide and driver, camera fees inside monuments (tripod/video camera require separate permits), or any optional site additions. The all-inclusive pricing removes the complexity of managing local payments, tickets, and logistics — everything is handled by your guide and driver." },
      { question: "What is the best time of year to do the Delhi-Agra day trip?", answer: "**October to March** is the ideal season for the Delhi–Agra day trip. Temperatures are pleasant (15–28°C), skies are clear, and the white marble of the Taj Mahal appears at its most luminous. **November and February** are arguably the best months — post-monsoon clarity combined with comfortable temperatures. **Avoid April–June** if possible: Agra temperatures regularly reach 42–46°C and outdoor sightseeing is genuinely uncomfortable. **July–September** (monsoon) brings humidity but also a dramatic atmosphere with dark clouds behind the white Taj — some photographers specifically seek this. The Taj Mahal is open year-round (closed Fridays)." },
      { question: "Are entry tickets to the Taj Mahal included in the tour?", answer: "Yes — entry tickets for the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort are included in this tour for all participants. Foreign national ticket pricing is ₹1,300 for the Taj Mahal main complex plus ₹200 for the inner mausoleum entry (the chamber containing the cenotaphs). Agra Fort is ₹650. By including all tickets in your tour price, you avoid queueing at ticket windows and the complexity of the online booking system. Your guide purchases or pre-books tickets and escorts you directly through the priority entry process." },
      { question: "Can we visit Baby Taj (Itmad-ud-Daula) on the same day?", answer: "Yes — Itmad-ud-Daula, often called the 'Baby Taj,' can be added to the same-day Delhi–Agra itinerary. Built in 1628, Itmad-ud-Daula is the tomb of Mirza Ghiyas Beg and is architecturally significant as one of the first Mughal structures built entirely in white marble with Pietra Dura inlay — predating the Taj Mahal and serving as its inspiration. It is quieter and less crowded than the Taj Mahal, making it a great add-on for those interested in Mughal architecture. Adding it requires approximately 45–60 minutes and is best visited after Agra Fort, before lunch." },
      { question: "Is it possible to take the Gatimaan Express instead of driving?", answer: "Yes — the Gatimaan Express (India's fastest train, 160 km/h) covers Delhi to Agra in just **1 hour 40 minutes**, departing from Hazrat Nizamuddin station and arriving at Agra Cantonment. For travellers who prefer trains or want to experience Indian rail, the Gatimaan option is excellent. Our [Delhi-Agra Gatimaan train tour](/india/agra/delhi-agra-round-trip-gatimaan-train) includes train tickets, guide, all entry fees, and AC vehicle in Agra between sites. The train departs approximately 8 AM and returns around 9 PM. The car option offers more flexibility; the train is faster and more scenic." },
      { question: "What vehicle is used for the Delhi to Agra day trip?", answer: "A modern, air-conditioned private vehicle is used — typically a Toyota Innova (6–7 seats) for groups of up to 6, or a sedan for couples/solo travellers. The vehicle is exclusively yours for the entire day, giving complete flexibility over timing and stops. Vehicles are GPS-tracked, insured, and driven by experienced drivers who regularly make the Delhi–Agra route. USB charging ports and Wi-Fi are available in most vehicles. For groups larger than 7, a tempo traveller or minibus is arranged." },
      { question: "Can we do the same-day trip in reverse — Agra to Delhi?", answer: "Yes — the tour can operate in either direction. If you are starting your trip in Agra (arriving from another city) and ending in Delhi, the vehicle can collect you from your Agra hotel, cover the sightseeing in Agra, and then drive you to Delhi for hotel drop-off. This is a popular itinerary for travellers arriving in Agra from Jaipur (completing the Golden Triangle circuit). The same sites, guide, and inclusions apply regardless of direction. Simply specify your pickup and drop-off locations when booking." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'private-sunrise-taj-mahal-agra-fort-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What time does the private sunrise Taj Mahal tour begin?", answer: "The Taj Mahal opens **30 minutes before sunrise**, and your guide meets you at the gate at this exact time — typically around **5:30–6:00 AM** depending on the season (sunrise time varies from 5:30 AM in June to 7:00 AM in December). Being at the gates when they open means you experience the Taj Mahal in near-solitude, with soft golden light on the white marble before tour groups and day-trippers arrive. This is the most photographically spectacular and emotionally profound time to visit the monument. Pickup from your Agra hotel is arranged at approximately 5:00 AM to ensure punctual arrival." },
      { question: "Why is sunrise the best time to visit the Taj Mahal?", answer: "Sunrise is universally agreed to be the best time to visit the Taj Mahal for three reasons: (1) **Light** — the rising sun casts warm gold and pink tones on the white marble, creating a photographic effect impossible at any other time; (2) **Crowds** — the monument receives up to 70,000 visitors per day, and sunrise means you may have entire sections nearly to yourself for the first 30–60 minutes; (3) **Temperature** — Agra can reach extreme heat by mid-morning (40°C+ in summer), and sunrise visits are significantly more comfortable. The [Taj Mahal ticket price](/india/agra/taj-mahal-ticket-price-2026) and opening hours are the same for all visitors." },
      { question: "Does the sunrise tour also include Agra Fort?", answer: "Yes — after the Taj Mahal (approximately 2–2.5 hours sunrise visit), the tour moves to [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort), which opens at 6 AM and is typically quiet in the early morning. Visiting Agra Fort immediately after sunrise at the Taj Mahal is the ideal combination: both sites when they are least crowded. Agra Fort is a UNESCO World Heritage Site — a massive 16th-century red sandstone Mughal fortress containing palaces, audience halls, and the Musamman Burj tower where Shah Jahan was imprisoned and from which he gazed at the Taj Mahal in his final years. The Agra Fort visit takes approximately 1.5 hours with a guide." },
      { question: "Are entry tickets included in the sunrise Taj Mahal tour?", answer: "Yes — entry tickets for both the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort are included for all participants. The Taj Mahal entry for foreign nationals is ₹1,300 (main complex) plus ₹200 for the inner mausoleum chamber. Agra Fort is ₹650. All tickets are purchased or pre-booked by your guide, eliminating the need to queue at ticket counters in the early morning. Note: the ₹200 mausoleum entry (to see the cenotaphs of Mumtaz and Shah Jahan inside the inner chamber) is specifically included — some lower-cost tours omit this." },
      { question: "Is this tour truly private with no other groups?", answer: "Yes — this is a 100% private tour. Your guide and vehicle are exclusively assigned to your group for the entire experience. You will not be combined with other travellers, families, or groups at any point. This means the guide's full attention is on your questions, the pace is entirely controlled by you, and photography stops are as long or as brief as you wish. Private tours at sunrise are particularly valuable because the monument is already at its quietest — combining privacy with off-peak timing makes this the most premium Taj Mahal experience available." },
      { question: "What should we bring for the sunrise Taj Mahal tour?", answer: "**Essential:** A warm layer (Agra mornings can be surprisingly cool, especially November–February, with temperatures dropping to 8–12°C at dawn), comfortable walking shoes with easy removal (shoes must be removed at the inner mausoleum platform), and your passport or ID (required for ticket purchase). **Recommended:** A camera or phone with a good low-light mode for the pre-sunrise golden hour, a reusable water bottle (the heat intensifies quickly after 8 AM), and reef-safe or mineral sunscreen for the walk back. **Not permitted:** Food and drinks (other than sealed water), tripods without permits, selfie sticks, and tobacco." },
      { question: "How long does the complete sunrise Taj Mahal and Agra Fort tour take?", answer: "The complete private sunrise tour typically runs **5–6 hours**: approximately 30 minutes of transit from hotel to Taj Mahal (5:00 AM pickup), 2–2.5 hours at the Taj Mahal (sunrise visit + full guided tour), 15-minute transit to Agra Fort, 1.5 hours at Agra Fort, and return to hotel by approximately 11:00–11:30 AM. This timing is excellent — you complete both UNESCO World Heritage sites before the main tourist crowds arrive and before Agra's notorious midday heat becomes uncomfortable. Breakfast is often included at a local café after the Taj Mahal visit before heading to Agra Fort." },
      { question: "Is the sunrise tour available in all seasons?", answer: "Yes — the sunrise tour operates year-round. The optimal season is **October to March** when temperatures at dawn are comfortable and visibility is clear. In **December–January**, winter mornings can be misty — fog sometimes settles over the Yamuna river, creating an ethereal atmosphere around the Taj Mahal that photographers specifically travel for. In **April–June** (summer), sunrise starts earlier (~5:30 AM) so the visit is completed before the worst heat. During **monsoon (July–September)**, rain at dawn is possible but not common at 6 AM — dark skies create a dramatic backdrop. The Taj Mahal is closed on Fridays." },
      { question: "Can the tour be extended to include Mehtab Bagh?", answer: "Yes — Mehtab Bagh (the 'Moonlit Garden') can be added after Agra Fort and is one of the most rewarding extensions for photographers. Located on the opposite bank of the Yamuna river directly behind the Taj Mahal, Mehtab Bagh provides a unique north-facing view across the river to the rear of the Taj Mahal — a perspective that is completely different from the main complex and far less crowded. This was originally a Mughal garden designed to be the mirror image of the Taj Mahal gardens. Entry is approximately ₹300. Adding Mehtab Bagh extends the tour by 45–60 minutes." },
      { question: "What is included in the private sunrise Taj Mahal and Agra Fort tour?", answer: "Included: hotel pickup and drop-off in Agra, private air-conditioned vehicle for the full tour, Ministry of Tourism-licensed English-speaking guide, all entry tickets (Taj Mahal complex + inner mausoleum + Agra Fort), and overshoe covers for the inner mausoleum platform. Not included: personal expenses, tips (recommended for excellent service), optional camera/video permits inside monuments, and meals (breakfast can be added at an optional café stop). The price is transparent and all-inclusive of the major costs — no hidden fees or surprise charges at the gates." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'delhi-agra-round-trip-gatimaan-train') {
    return [
      { question: "What is the Gatimaan Express and how fast does it travel?", answer: "The Gatimaan Express is **India's fastest train**, operating at up to 160 km/h (100 mph). It covers the 188 km journey between Delhi's Hazrat Nizamuddin station and Agra Cantonment station in just **1 hour 40 minutes** — dramatically faster than the 3–3.5 hour drive by road. The train is operated by Indian Railways and was launched in 2016. It is a premium semi-high-speed service with comfortable air-conditioned coaches, clean interiors, and reserved seating. For travellers who want to experience the best of Indian Railways while also visiting the Taj Mahal, the Gatimaan Express day trip is the definitive combination." },
      { question: "What time does the Gatimaan Express depart from Delhi?", answer: "The Gatimaan Express (train number 12049) departs **Hazrat Nizamuddin station in Delhi at 8:10 AM** and arrives at **Agra Cantonment at 9:50 AM**. The return train (12050) departs **Agra Cantonment at 8:05 PM** and arrives back at Hazrat Nizamuddin at **9:45 PM**. This schedule provides approximately 10 hours in Agra — more than sufficient for the Taj Mahal, Agra Fort, and lunch. Your tour package includes airport/hotel transfers to Hazrat Nizamuddin station and assistance through the ticketing and boarding process, which can be confusing for first-time Indian Railways travellers." },
      { question: "Are train tickets included in the Gatimaan Express tour package?", answer: "Yes — round-trip Gatimaan Express train tickets (Executive Chair Car class — the premium class with the most comfortable seating, wider seats, and complimentary breakfast/evening snack served on board) are included in the tour package price. Standard AC Chair Car tickets are available at a lower price if preferred. Tickets are booked in advance and assigned seat numbers provided before travel. In-train breakfast on the morning journey and an evening snack on the return are served by Indian Railways staff as part of the Executive class service." },
      { question: "Which station does the Gatimaan Express use in Delhi?", answer: "The Gatimaan Express departs from and arrives at **Hazrat Nizamuddin Railway Station** (station code NZM) in Delhi — not New Delhi Railway Station or Old Delhi Railway Station. Hazrat Nizamuddin is located in south-central Delhi, approximately 20–30 minutes from most central and south Delhi hotels. Your tour package includes a private vehicle pickup from your Delhi hotel to Hazrat Nizamuddin station, with sufficient time before departure. In Agra, the train arrives at **Agra Cantonment station** (AGC), where an air-conditioned vehicle and guide will be waiting to collect your group." },
      { question: "What sites are visited in Agra on the Gatimaan Express tour?", answer: "With 10 hours in Agra (9:50 AM arrival, 8:05 PM departure), the Gatimaan Express day tour comfortably covers: (1) **Taj Mahal** — 2.5-hour guided visit with licensed guide; (2) **Agra Fort** — 1.5-hour guided visit to the UNESCO World Heritage fortress; and (3) **Mehtab Bagh or Itmad-ud-Daula** (optional) — additional monument visits for those interested in more architectural history. A sit-down lunch at a quality restaurant is included between monument visits. The generous time in Agra (compared to a car-based same-day tour) means you are never rushed and can linger as long as you wish at the Taj Mahal." },
      { question: "Is a guide included in Agra for the Gatimaan Express tour?", answer: "Yes — a Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide meets your group at Agra Cantonment station upon arrival and accompanies you throughout the day in Agra. The guide provides historical commentary at the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort, manages all ticket logistics, and coordinates timing with the driver to ensure you are at Agra Cantonment station well before the 8:05 PM return train. The guide is a local Agra expert who has guided the Taj Mahal hundreds of times and can answer any historical, architectural, or practical question about the monument and the Mughal era." },
      { question: "Is lunch included on the Gatimaan Express Agra day tour?", answer: "Yes — a sit-down lunch at a quality restaurant in Agra is included. The restaurant is selected for hygiene, taste, and location (between Agra Fort and the optional afternoon site). Lunch typically takes place around 1:00–2:00 PM and includes a choice of North Indian and continental dishes. Vegetarian, vegan, Jain, and halal options are always available. In-train breakfast (morning journey) and an evening snack (return journey) are provided by Indian Railways as part of the Executive Chair Car class — so all main meals during the day are covered." },
      { question: "What class of train travel is included in the tour?", answer: "The standard tour package includes **Executive Chair Car (EC)** class — the premium Gatimaan Express class with wider reclining seats, extra legroom, complimentary meals served at seat, and cleaner, quieter coaches. EC class is equivalent to business class on a short-haul flight. If budget is a consideration, **AC Chair Car (CC)** is available at a lower price — comfortable, air-conditioned, reserved seating, but without in-seat meal service. Both classes arrive at the same time. We recommend EC class for the full Gatimaan experience — the on-board breakfast with a hot beverage as the train passes through the Yamuna plains is a genuine travel memory." },
      { question: "How does the Gatimaan Express compare to driving Delhi to Agra by car?", answer: "**Gatimaan Express advantages:** Much faster journey (1h40m vs 3h30m by road), more comfortable seated journey with meals served, a unique Indian railway experience, and no road traffic stress. **Private car advantages:** Door-to-door hotel pickup, flexible departure time (can leave before 8:10 AM for sunrise Taj Mahal visit), ability to stop en route, and the car waits for you throughout the day. **Best choice:** The Gatimaan Express is ideal for train enthusiasts, travellers with limited time in Delhi (later hotel checkout), and those who want to minimize road travel. The private car is better for early sunrise departures, families with young children, or travellers who prefer maximum flexibility." },
      { question: "What is the cancellation policy for the Gatimaan Express tour?", answer: "Free cancellation is available up to **48 hours** before the scheduled train departure for a full refund. Cancellations within 48 hours are subject to Indian Railways ticket cancellation charges (typically 25–50% depending on timing). In the rare event of train delays or cancellations by Indian Railways, we arrange an alternative private vehicle transfer at no extra cost so your Agra visit proceeds as planned. Train delays of 15–30 minutes occasionally occur; the day itinerary is designed with sufficient buffer to absorb minor delays without impacting the return train timing." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'hidden-gems-of-agra-heritage-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What hidden gems does this Agra heritage tour visit?", answer: "This heritage tour goes beyond the standard Taj Mahal and Agra Fort circuit to reveal Agra's lesser-known architectural treasures: **Itmad-ud-Daula** (the 'Baby Taj' — the first all-marble Mughal tomb, predating the Taj and considered its architectural prototype), **Mehtab Bagh** (the moonlit garden across the Yamuna with rare north-facing views of the Taj Mahal's rear facade), **Akbar's Tomb at Sikandra** (the magnificent mausoleum of the greatest Mughal emperor, just 10 km from Agra), **Mariam's Tomb** (the tomb of Akbar's Christian wife, rarely visited), and the **Agra bazaar lanes** (historic commercial streets used by Mughal craftsmen). These are the sites where serious history and architecture enthusiasts lose themselves for hours." },
      { question: "Does the hidden gems tour include the Taj Mahal?", answer: "The primary focus of the hidden gems heritage tour is the **lesser-known monuments of Agra** that most tourists miss. However, the Taj Mahal can be included as a starting or ending point if you haven't visited it yet, or if you want to combine the classic monument with the off-the-beaten-path sites. For repeat visitors to Agra who have already seen the Taj Mahal, the pure hidden gems tour (without the Taj) is highly recommended — it reveals a completely different dimension of Mughal Agra that is architecturally fascinating and free of the large tourist crowds. Discuss your preference when booking." },
      { question: "What is Itmad-ud-Daula and why is it worth visiting?", answer: "Itmad-ud-Daula (also called the 'Baby Taj') is the 1628 tomb of Mirza Ghiyas Beg — the grandfather of Mumtaz Mahal — and is historically significant as the **first Mughal monument built entirely of white marble** (preceding the Taj Mahal by 4 years). It was built by Nur Jahan, the powerful Mughal empress, and is an architectural jewel: small in scale but exquisite in detail, covered in Pietra Dura semi-precious stone inlay work that became the template for the Taj Mahal's decoration. The monument is located on the opposite bank of the Yamuna from the Taj Mahal and sees perhaps 5% of the Taj's visitor numbers — you often have entire sections to yourself, which is increasingly rare in Agra." },
      { question: "What is Mehtab Bagh and why is it a hidden gem?", answer: "Mehtab Bagh ('Moonlit Garden') is a Mughal-era garden complex on the north bank of the Yamuna river, directly opposite and behind the Taj Mahal. Built by Emperor Babur and later restored by Shah Jahan, it was originally designed to be viewed by moonlight — Shah Jahan reportedly planned a mirror-image Black Taj Mahal for himself here, though historians debate this. The garden provides the **only direct north-facing view of the rear facade of the Taj Mahal**, a perspective virtually unknown to most visitors. Sunrise photographers specifically seek this angle. Entry costs approximately ₹300, visitor numbers are tiny, and the garden's reflection pool perfectly frames the Taj Mahal in the background." },
      { question: "What is Akbar's Tomb at Sikandra and is it on this tour?", answer: "Akbar's Tomb at Sikandra is one of Agra's most important but most overlooked monuments. Emperor Akbar the Great (r. 1556–1605) is widely considered the greatest of the Mughal emperors — he built the largest empire in Indian history, championed religious tolerance, and patronised extraordinary art and architecture. His tomb at Sikandra, 10 km northwest of Agra, is a magnificent 5-storey sandstone and marble structure set in a vast garden approached through four ornate gateways. Unlike the Taj Mahal (which gets 70,000 daily visitors), Sikandra rarely exceeds 1,000 visitors on a busy day. The peaceful atmosphere allows genuine contemplation of one of history's most extraordinary rulers." },
      { question: "How is this heritage tour different from the standard Taj Mahal tour?", answer: "The standard Taj Mahal tour visits two UNESCO sites (Taj Mahal + Agra Fort) in 5–6 hours. The hidden gems heritage tour deliberately avoids the most-visited monuments in favour of sites with higher architectural significance-to-crowd ratios. The experience is quieter, more contemplative, and allows for detailed study of each site without jostling with thousands of other visitors. Your guide — a specialist in Mughal architectural history — provides commentary at a depth rarely possible in crowded monument settings. This tour is specifically designed for travellers who are passionate about history, architecture, or photography, and who want to leave Agra with knowledge that goes beyond what 99% of visitors take home." },
      { question: "How long is the hidden gems of Agra heritage tour?", answer: "The full hidden gems heritage tour runs approximately **7–8 hours** and covers 4–5 sites depending on your chosen itinerary: Itmad-ud-Daula (1 hour), Mehtab Bagh (45 min), Akbar's Tomb at Sikandra (1.5 hours), the Agra bazaar heritage walk (1 hour), and lunch at a local restaurant (1 hour). If combined with the Taj Mahal, the full day extends to 9–10 hours. An air-conditioned private vehicle connects all sites efficiently. The itinerary is flexible — if you find yourself particularly captivated by one site, the guide will adjust the schedule rather than rushing you." },
      { question: "Is a licensed guide included in the Agra heritage tour?", answer: "Yes — a Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide specialising in Mughal architectural history is included throughout the tour. The guide's expertise is what transforms this from a monument-hopping exercise into a genuine educational experience. They connect the sites chronologically — explaining how Itmad-ud-Daula influenced the Taj Mahal's design, how Akbar's architectural choices at Sikandra differed from his son Jahangir's at Itmad-ud-Daula, and how the entire Yamuna riverfront was originally conceived by Shah Jahan as a unified architectural landscape. This interconnected narrative is only possible with a specialist guide who has studied these sites in depth." },
      { question: "Is this tour suitable for repeat visitors to Agra?", answer: "This tour is **specifically designed** for repeat visitors to Agra. If you have already seen the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort on a previous trip, the hidden gems heritage tour gives you a completely fresh architectural and historical perspective on the same city. Many travellers who visit Agra a second time specifically book this tour to fill in the gaps from their first visit. Itmad-ud-Daula, Mehtab Bagh at sunrise, and Akbar's Tomb at Sikandra are all sites that serious India travellers repeatedly rank among their most memorable — precisely because they saw them without crowds and with a specialist guide." },
      { question: "What are the entry fees for the hidden gems Agra heritage tour sites?", answer: "Entry fees for the hidden gems sites are significantly lower than the Taj Mahal: **Itmad-ud-Daula** — ₹310 (foreign nationals); **Mehtab Bagh** — ₹300 (foreign nationals); **Akbar's Tomb at Sikandra** — ₹310 (foreign nationals). These are included in your tour price. The [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort) entry (₹650) and [Taj Mahal](/india/agra/taj-mahal-ticket-price-2026) entry (₹1,300 + ₹200 mausoleum) are additional if included in the itinerary. The total entry costs for the hidden gems sites are a fraction of the Taj Mahal, but the architectural and historical value is arguably equal — particularly at Itmad-ud-Daula and Akbar's Tomb." }
    ];
  }

  // --- AGRA TOUR FAQS BATCH 2 ---

  if (slug === 'agra-photography-tour-with-guide') {
    return [
      { question: "What locations does the Agra photography tour visit?", answer: "The Agra photography tour is specifically designed around the city's most photogenic locations at the optimal time of day for each: **Taj Mahal at sunrise** (the iconic reflection pool shot, the central mausoleum from the garden axis, and the ornate gateway arch framing); **Mehtab Bagh at dawn** (the rare north-facing view across the Yamuna — opposite bank to the Taj, a perspective that 95% of visitors never see); **Agra Fort's Musamman Burj tower** (the imprisoned Shah Jahan's viewpoint of the Taj, with the Yamuna in the foreground); and the **Agra bazaar lanes** (craft workshops, chai stalls, cycle-rickshaws). Each location is timed to the light rather than to monument opening hours — a photography-first approach." },
      { question: "Is the photography guide a professional photographer?", answer: "Yes — your guide on the Agra photography tour is both a Ministry of Tourism-certified historical guide and an experienced local photographer who has shot the Taj Mahal in every light condition across all seasons. They know exactly which angles, focal lengths, and times of day produce the most powerful images at each site. At the Taj Mahal specifically, they know: the precise position on the central axis where the reflection pool creates a perfect symmetrical composition; the optimal time after sunrise when direct light hits the south face; and the lesser-used western garden angle that most tourists miss. They can also operate your camera if you prefer to be in the frame." },
      { question: "What is the best time for photography at the Taj Mahal?", answer: "**30 minutes before and 60 minutes after sunrise** — this is the golden window for Taj Mahal photography. During this period: the light is warm and directional (not flat overhead), crowd density is at its daily minimum (often just dozens of people in the entire complex), and the marble picks up orange, gold, and pink tones that are impossible to replicate at any other time. The famous 'reflection pool' shot (Taj Mahal perfectly reflected in the long central channel) is most achievable in this window before the light becomes harsh. Our photography guide is already at the Taj Mahal gate before it opens at sunrise — your group enters in the first wave of visitors." },
      { question: "What camera equipment should I bring on the photography tour?", answer: "**Recommended:** A camera with manual controls (DSLR or mirrorless) for full control over long-exposure shots in pre-dawn light; a wide-angle lens (16–35mm equivalent) for the full Taj Mahal facade and garden; a short telephoto (85–135mm) for detail shots of the Pietra Dura inlay work and calligraphy; a polarising filter for cutting haze during later morning light. A lightweight travel tripod is highly recommended for the pre-sunrise shots — the guide knows which security staff permit discreet tripod use. **Important:** Full-size tripods require a separate camera permit inside the Taj Mahal complex (approximately ₹25); your guide handles this. Phone cameras with night/portrait mode produce excellent results and have no restrictions." },
      { question: "Is the photography tour suitable for smartphone photographers?", answer: "Absolutely. Modern smartphones produce outstanding results at the Taj Mahal, especially in the golden hour light of sunrise. iPhone 15 Pro, Samsung Galaxy S24 Ultra, and Pixel 8 Pro all perform exceptionally well in the soft morning light. Your photography guide tailors advice to your specific equipment — for smartphone users, they focus on composition, positioning, and timing rather than technical camera settings. They know the exact spot to stand for the 'classic postcard' composition, when to switch to portrait mode for closeups, and how to use the reflection pool as a natural mirror. Some of the most striking Taj Mahal photography shared on social media is shot on phones by guests on this exact tour." },
      { question: "What is included in the Agra photography tour?", answer: "Included: hotel pickup and drop-off in Agra, private air-conditioned vehicle for the day, professional photography guide (licensed historical guide + experienced local photographer), all monument entry tickets (Taj Mahal, Mehtab Bagh, Agra Fort), and camera/tripod permits where applicable. Not included: personal meals (a brief chai stop is usually included at a local stall), tips for the guide and driver, and professional post-processing of your images. The guide is available throughout the day to review your shots, suggest re-takes, and adapt the itinerary around the best available light rather than a fixed schedule." },
      { question: "Can the photography tour be customized for specific shots or themes?", answer: "Yes — the photography tour is highly customizable. If you are interested in: **architectural abstract photography** (extreme close-ups of the Pietra Dura inlay), **portrait photography** (photographing Agra residents in the bazaar lanes with their permission), **dawn landscape photography** (Yamuna river reflections), or **street documentary photography** (the working life of the monuments' surrounding communities), your guide can orient the entire day around your specific interest. Share your photography goals and a link to your portfolio or Instagram when booking — this allows the guide to prepare location-specific advice before the tour begins." },
      { question: "What time does the Agra photography tour start and finish?", answer: "The photography tour starts before dawn — pickup from your Agra hotel at approximately **5:00–5:15 AM** to arrive at the Taj Mahal gates 15–20 minutes before opening (approximately 5:30–6:00 AM depending on season). The sunrise session at the Taj Mahal runs until approximately 8:30 AM. Transit to Mehtab Bagh and the Yamuna river bank for rear-view Taj photography: 8:30–10:00 AM. Agra Fort (Shah Jahan's viewpoint and architectural photography): 10:00–11:30 AM. Optional bazaar walk: 11:30 AM–12:30 PM. Return to hotel by approximately 1:00 PM. The tour ends by early afternoon, leaving the rest of the day free." },
      { question: "Are drone flights permitted at the Taj Mahal for photography?", answer: "No — drone flights are **strictly prohibited** within a designated no-fly zone around the Taj Mahal, enforced by both the Archaeological Survey of India (ASI) and the Indian Air Force. Violations carry heavy fines and possible confiscation of the drone. The no-fly zone extends for several kilometres around the monument. Mehtab Bagh (across the Yamuna) is also within this zone. If you travel to India with a drone, it must be declared and registered with DGCA (India's aviation authority) prior to any flight — and the Taj Mahal area remains permanently restricted regardless of registration. Your photography guide will advise on all permitted locations for drone use during your broader India trip." },
      { question: "How does the photography tour differ from a standard guided tour?", answer: "A standard guided tour is designed around historical narrative and monument coverage. The photography tour is designed around **light, composition, and timing**. The guide makes all decisions — which gate to enter, which path to walk first, which areas to revisit — based on light conditions on the day rather than a standard itinerary. This means on a misty winter morning, the guide prioritises the ethereal fog shots; on a clear sunrise day, the reflection pool comes first. The historical commentary is still present and detailed, but the pace and sequence are driven by photography conditions. The result is a day that produces images you will actually want to display and share — not just documentary snapshots." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-sunrise-skip-the-line-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What does 'skip the line' mean at the Taj Mahal?", answer: "'Skip the line' at the Taj Mahal means your tickets are pre-purchased and your guide leads you through the **priority entry process**, bypassing the general ticket purchase queues which can run 30–90 minutes on busy days. The Taj Mahal receives up to 70,000 visitors daily, and weekend mornings see the longest queues. With this tour, you arrive at the gate with tickets already in hand, walk directly to the security check, and enter the complex within minutes of arrival. This is particularly valuable at sunrise — the priority entry means you are inside the complex in the first group of visitors, maximising your time in the quietest, most photogenic period of the day." },
      { question: "What time do the Taj Mahal gates open at sunrise?", answer: "The Taj Mahal opens **30 minutes before official sunrise** year-round. This means opening time varies seasonally: approximately **5:30 AM in June** (earliest sunrise) to **6:30–7:00 AM in December** (latest sunrise). The official closing time is 30 minutes before sunset. The monument is **closed every Friday** for prayers. For exact sunrise times by month, check our [Taj Mahal opening hours guide](/india/agra/taj-mahal-opening-time). Your tour guide will specify the exact gate opening time based on your visit date and ensures your group arrives at the gate 10–15 minutes before opening to be among the first visitors inside." },
      { question: "Which gate does the sunrise skip-the-line tour use?", answer: "The sunrise skip-the-line tour uses the **South Gate** (also called the Main Gate or Western Gate) — the principal ceremonial entrance that leads directly to the famous garden axis with the central reflecting pool and the first full view of the Taj Mahal facade. This is the most architecturally significant entry point. The East Gate is also available and is sometimes faster during peak times. Your guide selects the optimal gate based on current queue conditions on the morning of your visit. The South Gate's first view of the Taj Mahal through the ornate sandstone gateway arch (the Great Gate) is one of the most dramatic architectural reveals in the world — worth experiencing at the primary entrance." },
      { question: "Are tickets truly pre-booked in advance with this tour?", answer: "Yes — tickets are pre-purchased before your tour date. For foreign nationals, this means tickets are secured via the official ASI (Archaeological Survey of India) online ticketing system in advance. The Taj Mahal does not have a strict capacity cap that causes sell-outs, but pre-purchasing eliminates the ticket queue entirely. Your guide will have physical or digital tickets ready on the morning of the tour. The foreign national entry fee (₹1,300 for main complex + ₹200 for inner mausoleum) is included in your tour price — no additional payment required at the gate." },
      { question: "How many people are inside the Taj Mahal at sunrise?", answer: "At the moment the gates open at sunrise, visitor numbers inside the complex are at their absolute minimum — often just a few hundred people compared to the 20,000+ who visit between 9 AM and 1 PM on a busy day. The first 30–60 minutes after opening are the most tranquil of the entire day. During winter months (December–February), mist or fog frequently reduces visibility of other visitors and creates an extraordinary atmosphere. By 8:00–8:30 AM, group tours and day-trippers begin to arrive in significant numbers. The quality of the sunrise experience is therefore heavily dependent on punctual arrival at opening time — which this skip-the-line tour is specifically designed to achieve." },
      { question: "Is a guide included in the sunrise skip-the-line tour?", answer: "Yes — a Ministry of Tourism-licensed professional guide accompanies you throughout the sunrise visit. The guide provides complete historical and architectural commentary: the 22-year construction story (1631–1653), the 20,000 workers involved, the Pietra Dura marble inlay technique (over 28 varieties of semi-precious stones), the Quranic calligraphy that covers every archway, and the optical illusion engineering that makes the minarets appear to lean outward (to fall away from the tomb in case of earthquake). The guide also identifies the best photography positions and angles, acting as a photography guide as well as a history guide. The combination of expert commentary and sunrise light makes this the definitive Taj Mahal experience." },
      { question: "Is the Taj Mahal inner chamber included in the skip-the-line tour?", answer: "Yes — the inner mausoleum entry (₹200 additional fee for foreign nationals on top of the main complex entry) is included in your tour price. The inner chamber contains the marble cenotaphs (ornamental tombs) of Mumtaz Mahal and Shah Jahan, surrounded by an ornate marble screen carved in a jali lattice pattern with Pietra Dura floral inlays. Entry to the inner chamber is often the most moving part of a Taj Mahal visit — the scale, craftsmanship, and acoustics inside the marble dome are extraordinary. Photography inside the inner chamber is restricted (no flash permitted), but your guide will advise on the best approach for capturing the experience." },
      { question: "What happens if it is foggy or raining on the morning of my sunrise tour?", answer: "The Taj Mahal tour proceeds in all weather conditions — the monument is open unless there is an official government closure (extremely rare). Fog is common in December–January and creates a uniquely atmospheric experience: the Taj Mahal emerging from morning mist is one of the most beautiful sights in India. Rain at sunrise is uncommon but occasional during the monsoon transition months. In heavy rain, the guide shifts the itinerary to prioritize covered areas and the forecourt views. Partial refunds are not provided for weather conditions, but the guide adapts the experience to maximize what is possible. Sunrise visits are specifically chosen because even on overcast days, the early morning quiet and cooler temperatures make it the best time of day." },
      { question: "Can we combine the sunrise skip-the-line tour with Agra Fort?", answer: "Yes — combining the sunrise Taj Mahal visit with Agra Fort in a single day is the most common and recommended itinerary. After the sunrise visit (typically 5:30–8:30 AM), your guide and driver take you to Agra Fort (15 minutes away), which opens at 6 AM. Agra Fort in the early morning is almost as peaceful as the Taj Mahal at sunrise — the red sandstone Mughal fortress receives a fraction of the Taj's visitor numbers even at peak hours. The combined tour (Taj Mahal sunrise + Agra Fort) takes approximately 5–6 hours total and is completed by mid-morning, leaving the afternoon free for other activities or your onward journey." },
      { question: "What should I bring for the sunrise Taj Mahal visit?", answer: "**Essential:** Warm layers (Agra mornings drop to 8–12°C in winter; even summer dawns can be cool at 5:30 AM), comfortable walking shoes you can remove easily (mandatory at the inner mausoleum), and a valid passport or national ID for ticket verification. **Recommended:** Camera or smartphone with night/portrait mode, a light jacket or stole (also useful as a head covering for female visitors), and a reusable water bottle (no food or drinks beyond sealed water are permitted inside). **Not permitted:** Tripods without permits (guide arranges permit), selfie sticks (banned), tobacco, food, and knives. Overshoes for the marble platform are provided free by the monument." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-guided-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What is included in the Taj Mahal guided tour?", answer: "The Taj Mahal guided tour includes: hotel pickup and drop-off in Agra, private air-conditioned vehicle, Ministry of Tourism-licensed English-speaking guide, all entry tickets (Taj Mahal complex + ₹200 inner mausoleum entry), and overshoes for the marble platform. The guide covers the complete complex — the Great Gate (Darwaza-i-Rauza), the Persian charbagh garden, the main terrace, the mausoleum exterior and interior, and the mosque and guest house flanking the tomb. Duration is approximately 2–2.5 hours inside the complex. Additional sites (Agra Fort, Mehtab Bagh) can be added to create a full-day itinerary." },
      { question: "Is this a private tour or a shared group tour?", answer: "This is a 100% private guided tour — your guide and vehicle are exclusively assigned to your group with no shared participants. The private format means the guide adapts to your pace, interests, and question depth rather than managing a group of 20+ people with different needs. At the Taj Mahal, this makes a significant difference: you can linger at the reflection pool as long as you wish, request the guide to revisit sections, and ask questions without feeling you are holding up others. Private tours are the standard format for quality Taj Mahal experiences — avoid shared group tours which typically rush through in 45–60 minutes." },
      { question: "How long does the Taj Mahal guided tour take?", answer: "The guided tour of the Taj Mahal complex takes approximately **2 to 2.5 hours** at a comfortable pace with full commentary. This covers: the Great Gate and forecourt (15 minutes), the charbagh garden and approach (20 minutes), the main terrace and exterior of the mausoleum (30 minutes), the inner mausoleum chamber (20 minutes), the mosque and guest house (15 minutes), and photography time at the key reflection pool viewpoint (20 minutes). Faster visits (1.5 hours) are possible but do not allow sufficient time for the guide to provide full depth of commentary. Allow 3 hours if you want a completely unhurried experience." },
      { question: "Who are the guides and what are their qualifications?", answer: "All guides on this tour are Ministry of Tourism-certified and carry ASI (Archaeological Survey of India) authorization to guide inside federally protected monuments including the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort. Certification requires passing a rigorous government examination covering Mughal architectural history, Indian national history, and tour management. Guides are re-certified periodically. Our guides are senior professionals who have guided the Taj Mahal hundreds of times and possess deep expertise in the monument's history, construction, and architectural significance. At booking, you can request guides with specific language fluency (Spanish, French, German, Italian, Japanese, Chinese are available in addition to English)." },
      { question: "What does the guide cover inside the Taj Mahal?", answer: "Your guide covers the complete architectural and historical narrative: (1) **The Great Gate** — 11 domed towers, Quranic calligraphy growing optically larger toward the top, and the famous first framed view of the Taj Mahal through the archway; (2) **The charbagh garden** — Persian four-quartered garden design, the central water channel representing the rivers of paradise in Islamic cosmology; (3) **The main platform** — the four minarets (each 40 metres, tilted slightly outward for earthquake safety), the mosque and jawab; (4) **Exterior marble work** — Pietra Dura inlay with 28 varieties of semi-precious stone including lapis lazuli, carnelian, malachite, and mother-of-pearl; (5) **Interior** — the marble jali screen, the cenotaphs, and the acoustics of the dome." },
      { question: "What is the best time of day for the Taj Mahal guided tour?", answer: "**Sunrise** is the optimal time: first entry into the complex (30 minutes before official sunrise), minimum crowds, and the most beautiful directional light on the white marble. **Early morning (7–9 AM)** is excellent and only marginally more crowded than sunrise. **Midday (11 AM–2 PM)** is the most crowded, hottest, and worst-lit period — avoid if possible. **Late afternoon (3–5 PM)** is good in winter months when the sun is low and golden — the marble takes on a warm amber tone. The monument closes 30 minutes before sunset. For a complete [Taj Mahal visit planning guide](/india/agra/taj-mahal-opening-time) including seasonal recommendations, see our dedicated resource." },
      { question: "Is the Taj Mahal entry ticket included in the guided tour price?", answer: "Yes — the Taj Mahal entry ticket for foreign nationals (₹1,300 for the main complex and ₹200 for the inner mausoleum — both included) is part of the tour package price. No additional payment is required at the gate. Indian national tickets are ₹50 (significantly lower), and SAARC/BIMSTEC citizen tickets are ₹540. Children under 15 years are free for all nationalities. The guide manages the ticketing process entirely, including the identity verification requirement (passport or national ID). Keeping a digital copy of your passport on your phone is recommended for quick verification at the ticket counter." },
      { question: "Can I visit the Taj Mahal without a guide?", answer: "Yes — the Taj Mahal can be visited independently without a guide. However, the monument provides minimal on-site interpretation (a few small information boards), and without expert context, the visit becomes primarily a photo opportunity rather than a historically rich experience. The Pietra Dura inlay work, the Quranic calligraphy, the architectural engineering, the love story behind the construction, and the political history of Mughal decline are all complex subjects that transform the Taj Mahal from a 'pretty building' into one of humanity's most extraordinary artistic achievements. A good guide is the single most valuable investment in any visit to the Taj Mahal. See our [Agra travel guide](/india/agra/things-to-do-in-agra) for independent visitor tips." },
      { question: "Is the Taj Mahal guided tour suitable for elderly visitors?", answer: "Yes — the Taj Mahal guided tour is suitable for elderly visitors with appropriate planning. The complex involves approximately 1.5–2 km of walking on flat, paved surfaces, with the main mausoleum accessed via a short staircase (approximately 30 steps). The gardens are wheelchair accessible via ramp access for most areas. Electric buggies (golf carts) are available inside the complex for visitors with mobility limitations — your guide arranges this at the entry gate. The main challenge for elderly visitors is heat in summer months (April–June), when temperatures can reach 40–45°C by midday — sunrise visits are strongly recommended to complete the tour in cooler morning conditions." },
      { question: "What is the difference between the Taj Mahal east gate and west gate?", answer: "The **South/Western Gate** (Main Gate) is the primary ceremonial entrance — it aligns with the monument's central axis and provides the iconic first 'reveal' view of the Taj Mahal through the Great Gate archway as you walk through. This is the most dramatic entry experience. The **Eastern Gate** is the secondary entrance, slightly closer to most hotel areas and often has shorter queues. Both gates lead to the same complex. Your guide selects the appropriate gate based on your hotel location, current queue conditions, and time of day. Most first-time visitors are strongly recommended to use the South Gate for the architectural 'reveal' — this first view of the Taj Mahal through the gateway arch is one of travel's truly unmissable moments." }
    ];
  }

  // --- END AGRA TOUR FAQS BATCH 2 ---

  // --- AGRA TOUR FAQS BATCH 3 ---

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-sunrise-tour-from-agra') {
    return [
      { question: "What time does the sunrise tour of the Taj Mahal start from Agra?", answer: "Your guide collects you from your Agra hotel at approximately **5:00–5:15 AM** — roughly 30–45 minutes before the Taj Mahal gates open at sunrise. The exact pickup time depends on your hotel's distance from the South Gate and the season (sunrise varies from 5:30 AM in summer to 7:00 AM in winter). Arriving at the gate before opening ensures your group enters in the first wave of visitors, securing the reflection pool axis almost entirely for your photography before the main crowds arrive at 8–9 AM. This is the single most impactful thing you can do to transform a standard Taj Mahal visit into an extraordinary one." },
      { question: "Why should Agra hotel guests do a sunrise tour rather than visiting later?", answer: "Staying in Agra overnight specifically to do the sunrise tour is the gold standard Taj Mahal experience. By staying in Agra, you avoid the 3.5-hour drive from Delhi that forces same-day visitors to rush. You can be at the Taj Mahal gate precisely at opening, spend 2.5 unhurried hours in soft golden light with minimal crowds, and still be back at your hotel for breakfast by 9 AM. The contrast between a sunrise visit (serene, beautiful, uncrowded) and a midday visit (hot, noisy, 50,000 people) is stark. If you are staying in Agra for any length of time, the sunrise session is non-negotiable. Our [Agra travel guide](/india/agra/things-to-do-in-agra) recommends a minimum 2-night stay to include both sunrise and sunset visits." },
      { question: "What is the route from Agra hotels to the Taj Mahal?", answer: "Most Agra hotels are within 2–4 km of the Taj Mahal. The monument is located at the north end of the city on the banks of the Yamuna river. The South Gate (main entrance) is accessed via Taj Road. Importantly, a traffic-free zone surrounds the Taj Mahal for environmental protection — petrol and diesel vehicles are not permitted within 500 metres of the gates. Your tour vehicle drops you at the designated parking area (Shilpgram), from where electric buggies or cycle rickshaws (or a short 5-minute walk) take you to the entrance gates. Your guide manages this entire logistics chain smoothly so there is no confusion at 5 AM." },
      { question: "Is Agra Fort visited after the sunrise Taj Mahal tour?", answer: "Yes — the standard post-sunrise addition is [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort), a 2.5-km drive from the Taj Mahal and the second major site on every Agra itinerary. After the sunrise Taj Mahal session (typically complete by 8:30–9:00 AM), your guide takes you to Agra Fort, which is at its quietest in the early morning. The fort is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and contains the Musamman Burj — the octagonal tower where Shah Jahan was imprisoned by his son Aurangzeb from 1658 until his death in 1666, able only to see the distant white dome of the Taj Mahal across the Yamuna. This narrative is most poignant when the Taj Mahal is visible from the tower on a clear morning." },
      { question: "What is the light like at the Taj Mahal at different times of day?", answer: "The Taj Mahal's white Makrana marble changes colour dramatically across the day: **At sunrise** — warm orange and gold tones, directional shadows that define the carved relief work, the reflection pool perfectly still. **Mid-morning (8–10 AM)** — soft white, clear detail, pleasant and bright. **Midday (11 AM–2 PM)** — harsh, flat overhead light; marble appears bleached white; the worst time photographically. **Late afternoon (3–5 PM in winter)** — warm amber light returns, beautiful for the western facade. **Full moon nights** (5 days/month by special permit) — the marble glows blue-white in moonlight, an otherworldly experience. Sunrise is universally recommended as the single best light condition." },
      { question: "What is included in the sunrise Taj Mahal tour from Agra?", answer: "Included: hotel pickup in Agra at dawn, private air-conditioned vehicle for the morning, Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide throughout the visit, all entry tickets (Taj Mahal main complex + inner mausoleum chamber), and overshoes for the marble platform. The sunrise session typically ends by 8:30–9:00 AM. Agra Fort can be added to extend the tour to a half-day (returning to hotel by 11:30 AM). A brief breakfast stop at a local café is often included between the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort visits. The guide provides complete historical and architectural commentary and suggests optimal photography positions throughout." },
      { question: "Is a moonlight viewing of the Taj Mahal available?", answer: "Yes — the Taj Mahal offers special **moonlight viewing** on the night of the full moon and the two days before and after (5 nights per month). This is a separate ticketed experience from the sunrise visit and has strict visitor limits (maximum 400 visitors per session, in groups of 50). The moonlight permit costs ₹750 for foreign nationals and must be booked well in advance through the ASI ticketing system. The experience runs in 8 PM, 9 PM, and 10 PM sessions, each 30 minutes. The white marble glows an extraordinary blue-white in full moonlight. If your Agra dates coincide with a full moon, combining a sunrise morning visit with a moonlight evening visit makes for an incomparable day." },
      { question: "What are the rules for visiting the Taj Mahal at sunrise?", answer: "Key rules: **Shoes must be removed** at the marble terrace surrounding the mausoleum (overshoes are provided free). **No food, tobacco, or chewing tobacco** inside the complex — confiscated at security. **Tripods require a permit** (₹25, arranged by your guide). **Selfie sticks are banned**. **Camera bags** may be checked at security. **Drones are strictly prohibited** within the no-fly zone. **Fireworks, coloured powders** (Holi powder) are banned. **Modest dress** is respectful and recommended. The security check is thorough — your guide briefs you on what to leave in the vehicle to avoid delays at the gate at 5:30 AM when time is critical for the sunrise light." },
      { question: "How far is the Taj Mahal from Agra Fort?", answer: "The Taj Mahal and [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort) are approximately **2.5 km apart**, a 10–15 minute drive via the riverside road. The route passes through the old city area near the Yamuna. On the road between the two monuments, you also pass the access road to Mehtab Bagh (the moonlit garden). The physical proximity of Agra's three major sites (Taj Mahal, Agra Fort, and Mehtab Bagh) within a 3-km radius makes combining all three in a single morning very achievable when starting at sunrise. Your guide coordinates the vehicle and timing between sites efficiently." },
      { question: "Can solo travellers book the sunrise Taj Mahal tour from Agra?", answer: "Yes — solo travellers regularly book the sunrise Taj Mahal tour from Agra. The private format (dedicated guide and vehicle) means solo travellers receive the same level of personalized service as groups. The pricing for a solo traveller is higher per person than for a group (the vehicle and guide cost is shared across fewer people), but the one-on-one guide interaction — asking any question, moving at your own pace, and having the guide's full photographic assistance — is significantly more rewarding than a shared group experience. If cost is a concern, contact us to enquire about shared sunrise tours with other solo travellers." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-pickup-private-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What does 'pickup included' mean for this Taj Mahal private tour?", answer: "The private Taj Mahal tour with pickup means a dedicated air-conditioned vehicle and driver collect you from your hotel entrance at the arranged time and transport you door-to-door throughout the tour. There is no need to arrange your own transport, navigate to a meeting point, or deal with local auto-rickshaw drivers. For Delhi-based visitors, pickup is from your Delhi hotel, followed by the 3–3.5 hour drive to Agra. For Agra-based visitors, pickup is from your Agra hotel for the short trip to the monument. Drop-off after the tour returns you to the same hotel (or an alternative if you are continuing your journey onward to Jaipur, for example)." },
      { question: "Does the private tour include a guide at the Taj Mahal?", answer: "Yes — a Ministry of Tourism-licensed professional guide is included and meets your group at the Taj Mahal gate (or travels with you from Delhi if this is a day trip). The guide provides full historical and architectural commentary covering the complete complex: the Great Gate, the charbagh garden, the main mausoleum exterior and interior including the Pietra Dura inlay work, the cenotaphs of Mumtaz Mahal and Shah Jahan, and the mosque and guest house flanking the tomb. The entire visit is private — the guide works exclusively for your group with no other visitors sharing the experience." },
      { question: "Is this tour available for pickup from Delhi?", answer: "Yes — this tour is available with hotel pickup from Delhi for same-day visitors. Pickup from Delhi hotels is at approximately **5:30–6:00 AM** to allow arrival at the Taj Mahal by approximately 9:00 AM. The drive is 3–3.5 hours via the Yamuna Expressway. The complete day tour from Delhi includes the Taj Mahal, [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort), and lunch in Agra, returning to Delhi hotels by approximately 7:00 PM. If you are visiting from Agra directly (staying in Agra overnight), pickup is arranged from your Agra hotel for the short morning drive to the monument — typically 5:00–5:30 AM for a sunrise visit." },
      { question: "What is included in the private Taj Mahal tour with pickup?", answer: "Included: hotel pickup and drop-off by private air-conditioned vehicle (Delhi-Agra-Delhi for day trips, or Agra hotel to monument for local tours), Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide, all entry tickets (Taj Mahal complex + inner mausoleum), overshoes for the marble platform, and bottled water. Not included: tips for guide and driver, personal shopping, optional additional sites (Mehtab Bagh, Itmad-ud-Daula), and meals (Delhi day trips include lunch; Agra-only tours do not unless specified). The all-inclusive format eliminates the need to carry local currency for major costs during the tour." },
      { question: "How many people can the private vehicle accommodate?", answer: "Standard private vehicles accommodate groups of up to **6 passengers** comfortably (Toyota Innova or equivalent SUV). For 2–4 passengers, a sedan may be arranged. For 7–12 passengers, a tempo traveller minivan is provided at adjusted pricing. For larger groups (13+), multiple vehicles can be arranged. When booking, specify your exact group size so the appropriate vehicle is allocated. The vehicle is exclusively yours for the entire tour — you will not share with other tour groups. This exclusivity is what makes the 'private tour with pickup' format fundamentally different from shared shuttle or group bus services." },
      { question: "Can the tour be customized to include Agra Fort and other sites?", answer: "Yes — the private tour with pickup is fully customizable. The standard itinerary covers the Taj Mahal (2–2.5 hours with guide). Popular additions include: **Agra Fort** (1.5 hours, UNESCO Heritage Site, ₹650 entry included); **Mehtab Bagh** (45 minutes, moonlit garden with rear-view Taj photography, ₹300 entry); **Itmad-ud-Daula** (Baby Taj, 1 hour, ₹310 entry); and **Akbar's Tomb at Sikandra** (1.5 hours, 10 km from Agra, ₹310 entry). A full Agra day tour can visit all five sites. Share your interests when booking and the guide designs the ideal itinerary for your available time." },
      { question: "What is the cancellation policy for the private Taj Mahal tour with pickup?", answer: "Free cancellation is available up to **24 hours** before the scheduled pickup time for a full refund. Cancellations within 24 hours are subject to a partial cancellation fee (typically 25–50% of the tour price) to cover the driver's time and pre-purchased tickets. If you need to reschedule rather than cancel, we accommodate this at no charge with 24 hours notice. In the event of a monument closure (extremely rare — usually for government events or VIP visits), the tour is rescheduled or fully refunded. The Taj Mahal is closed every **Friday** — ensure your booking is not on a Friday before confirming." },
      { question: "What time should we plan to arrive back at our hotel?", answer: "For **Delhi-based day trips**: departure from Delhi ~5:30 AM, return to Delhi hotel ~6:30–7:00 PM (13-hour round trip). For **Agra hotel-based tours** (Taj Mahal + Agra Fort): pickup ~5:00 AM, return by ~11:30 AM. For Agra hotel-based tours adding Mehtab Bagh and lunch: return by ~2:00 PM. All timings are approximate and depend on traffic, time spent at each site, and your chosen itinerary. The private format means you control the pace — if you want to spend 3 hours at the Taj Mahal instead of 2, the driver waits and the schedule adjusts accordingly." },
      { question: "Is the Taj Mahal private tour suitable for a honeymoon visit?", answer: "The Taj Mahal is one of the world's most romantic monuments — built as an eternal expression of love by Emperor Shah Jahan for his wife Mumtaz Mahal, who died in childbirth. A private tour (versus a shared group) is the only appropriate format for a honeymoon visit: no strangers, no fixed group pace, and the guide can tailor the narrative to focus on the deeply romantic love story of Shah Jahan and Mumtaz. Sunrise is the most intimate time — in the early morning, you may have the reflection pool walkway almost entirely to yourselves. Couples frequently request the guide to take photographs using their phone or camera at the most romantic viewpoints. Our [Agra travel guide](/india/agra) has honeymooner-specific recommendations." },
      { question: "Are there any items that cannot be brought into the Taj Mahal?", answer: "Items **not permitted** inside the Taj Mahal complex: food and drinks (sealed water only), tobacco and chewing tobacco, selfie sticks, tripods without paid permits (₹25, guide arranges), professional video cameras without permits, fireworks, coloured powders, flowers, and any sharp objects. Mobile phones and standard cameras are freely permitted. Bags are X-rayed at security — keep your bag light and leave prohibited items in the vehicle. Shoes must be removed at the marble terrace surrounding the mausoleum; free overshoes are provided at the base. Your guide briefs you on all these rules before entry to ensure the security process is smooth and fast." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-half-day-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What does the Taj Mahal half-day tour cover?", answer: "The Taj Mahal half-day tour covers the complete Taj Mahal complex with a licensed guide, running approximately **4–5 hours total** (including pickup, monument visit, and drop-off). The guided visit itself is 2–2.5 hours inside the complex: the Great Gate, the charbagh garden, the main terrace, the mausoleum exterior and interior (including the inner chamber with the cenotaphs), and the mosque and guest house flanking the tomb. The half-day format is ideal for visitors with limited time in Agra or those combining the Taj Mahal with an onward journey (e.g., Agra to Jaipur on the same day). It covers the Taj Mahal comprehensively without the additional sites of a full-day tour." },
      { question: "How long is the Taj Mahal half-day tour?", answer: "The half-day tour typically runs **4 to 5 hours** from hotel pickup to hotel drop-off. This includes: 15 minutes pickup and transit to the monument, 2–2.5 hours guided visit inside the complex, 20–30 minutes transit via the parking/buggy area, and return to hotel. For Delhi-based visitors doing a half-day Taj Mahal tour, note that the drive alone is 3–3.5 hours each way — a same-day Delhi visit is therefore effectively a full day. The half-day format is most appropriate for Agra hotel guests or travellers arriving in Agra from another city for a brief visit." },
      { question: "Can I combine the half-day Taj Mahal tour with Agra Fort?", answer: "Adding [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort) converts the half-day tour to a full-day experience (approximately 7–8 hours). The fort is 2.5 km from the Taj Mahal and the two sites are routinely combined. If you are staying in Agra overnight, a common approach is to split: Taj Mahal in the morning (half-day tour, 5:30–9:30 AM) and Agra Fort in the late morning or afternoon (10:00 AM–12:00 PM). This avoids the exhaustion of visiting both back-to-back and allows you to visit the Taj Mahal at the optimal sunrise time without rushing. Discuss the optimal scheduling with your guide based on your Agra hotel check-in/check-out times." },
      { question: "What time does the Taj Mahal half-day tour start?", answer: "The ideal start time for the half-day Taj Mahal tour is **sunrise** — pickup at 5:00–5:30 AM from your Agra hotel, arrive at the gate at the moment it opens (5:30–6:30 AM depending on season), complete the 2.5-hour guided visit, and return to your hotel by 8:30–9:30 AM. This allows the rest of your morning for breakfast, check-out, or onward travel. Alternatively, the half-day tour can start at 7:00–8:00 AM (slightly more crowds but still a good experience) or late afternoon (3:30–5:30 PM, excellent in winter months for warm amber light). Avoid 10 AM–2 PM — this is the most crowded and hottest window." },
      { question: "Is a guide included in the half-day Taj Mahal tour?", answer: "Yes — a Ministry of Tourism-licensed professional guide is included for the full duration of the monument visit. The half-day format does not reduce the quality or depth of the guide's commentary — the 2–2.5 hour guided visit covers the complete architectural and historical narrative of the Taj Mahal. The guide also assists with photography, manages the ticketing process, and navigates the security and entry logistics so you spend your limited time experiencing the monument rather than managing logistics." },
      { question: "Are entry tickets included in the half-day Taj Mahal tour?", answer: "Yes — all entry tickets are included: the main Taj Mahal complex (₹1,300 for foreign nationals) and the inner mausoleum chamber entry (₹200 additional). Both are included in the tour price — no additional payment is needed at the gate. The inner mausoleum entry (the chamber containing the cenotaphs of Mumtaz Mahal and Shah Jahan) is specifically worth including — some budget tours omit this ₹200 fee, which means visitors do not enter the most historically significant part of the monument. Confirm that both fees are included when comparing tour prices." },
      { question: "Is the half-day Taj Mahal tour suitable for children?", answer: "Yes — the half-day format is particularly well-suited for families with young children. The 2–2.5 hour visit duration is manageable for children without becoming exhausting. The private tour format allows you to take breaks, visit the shaded garden areas, and adjust the pace based on your children's energy. Your guide is experienced with families and adapts the narrative to engage younger visitors (the love story of Shah Jahan, the construction facts like 22 years and 20,000 workers, and the size comparisons are naturally fascinating to children). Shoes must be removed at the marble platform — bring socks for comfort. Entry for children under 15 is free." },
      { question: "What happens if I arrive late for my half-day tour pickup?", answer: "Your driver will wait at your hotel for up to 15–20 minutes beyond the agreed pickup time. If you anticipate a later start, contact the driver or guide via the WhatsApp number provided at booking — they can adjust the pickup time with sufficient notice. A late start compresses the time at the monument and can push your visit into the more crowded and hotter mid-morning period. For sunrise half-day tours specifically, punctuality at pickup is critical — even a 20-minute delay at 5 AM means entering the complex 20 minutes later, with noticeably different light conditions and beginning crowd buildup." },
      { question: "Can the half-day tour start from New Delhi, Jaipur, or another city?", answer: "The half-day format (4–5 hours total) is only practical for visitors who are **already staying in Agra**. For visitors coming from Delhi, the drive alone is 3–3.5 hours each way, making the total trip 10+ hours — this is a same-day tour format, not a half-day. For Jaipur-based visitors, the drive is 4–5 hours each way. If you are coming from outside Agra, we recommend the [same-day Delhi to Agra tour](/india/agra/same-day-delhi-to-agra-tour) or an overnight Agra stay combined with this half-day sunrise tour for the best experience." },
      { question: "Is the half-day Taj Mahal tour suitable for elderly visitors or those with mobility issues?", answer: "Yes — the half-day Taj Mahal tour is well-suited for elderly visitors and those with mobility challenges. The Taj Mahal complex features **flat marble surfaces** across the main platform and garden pathways, making navigation relatively smooth. **Wheelchair accessibility** is available via ramps on the eastern side of the main platform, and **electric golf carts** can be arranged at the gate to transport visitors from the entry point to the base of the mausoleum, eliminating the 300-metre garden walk. The main physical requirement is approximately **30 steps** up to the marble terrace, but the ramp alternative bypasses this entirely. As a private tour, the pace is entirely flexible — your guide adjusts the walking speed, incorporates rest breaks in shaded areas of the garden and mosque, and ensures the experience is comfortable rather than rushed. For visitors who need additional assistance, consider booking the [Taj Mahal entry ticket](/india/agra/taj-mahal-entry-ticket) separately to allow unlimited time at your own pace." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'mysteries-of-agra-local-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What mysteries and secrets does this Agra local tour reveal?", answer: "The 'Mysteries of Agra' tour explores the city's hidden historical narratives that standard monument tours never cover: **The 'Black Taj Mahal' legend** — did Shah Jahan plan a dark mirror-image tomb for himself across the Yamuna (where Mehtab Bagh stands)? Archaeological evidence and historical debate examined on location. **The 57 craftsmen mystery** — legend says Shah Jahan cut off the hands of the Taj Mahal's craftsmen to prevent them from building anything more beautiful; historically questionable but fascinating to explore at the monument where it allegedly occurred. **The Taj Mahal's 22 years of construction** — why did it take so long, what engineering challenges arose? **The Taj Mahal's secret chambers** below the mausoleum — reportedly sealed rooms that ASI has never fully excavated. Your guide separates myth from documented history throughout." },
      { question: "Is this a walking tour or does it use a vehicle?", answer: "The Mysteries of Agra tour uses a combination of a private vehicle (for transit between sites) and guided walks within each location. The Taj Mahal complex, Agra Fort, and the old bazaar areas involve significant walking on flat surfaces (3–5 km total across the day). Wear comfortable walking shoes. The vehicle is available throughout for anyone who needs to rest or if the heat becomes uncomfortable. The bazaar walk sections are the most immersive part of the local tour — your guide introduces you to craftsmen still using Mughal-era Pietra Dura stone inlay techniques in their workshops, providing a living connection to the monument's construction methods." },
      { question: "Does the mysteries tour include the Taj Mahal?", answer: "Yes — the Taj Mahal is the centrepiece of the mysteries tour. Unlike a standard Taj Mahal visit focused primarily on beauty and romance, the mysteries tour approaches the monument from an analytical and investigative angle: the engineering questions (how were the 74 semi-precious stone types sourced and transported?), the mathematical mysteries (is there a hidden geometric code in the design?), and the historical controversies (was the Taj Mahal built on the site of a pre-existing Hindu palace?). These alternative perspectives are examined with evidence at the monument itself, making even a repeat visit completely fresh and intellectually engaging." },
      { question: "What Agra sites beyond the Taj Mahal are on this tour?", answer: "Beyond the Taj Mahal, the mysteries tour visits: **Mehtab Bagh** (the alleged 'Black Taj' site — examined for archaeological evidence on location), **Agra Fort's sealed chambers and underground passages** (areas of the fort not on standard tours), **The Agra bazaar craftsmen lanes** (Kinari Bazaar and surrounding streets where Mughal-era crafts — Pietra Dura, marble carving, dhurrie weaving — are still produced using traditional methods), and optionally **Fatehpur Sikri** (Akbar's abandoned city, 40 km from Agra — why was it completely abandoned just 14 years after completion? Another Mughal mystery examined in person)." },
      { question: "How long is the mysteries of Agra local tour?", answer: "The standard mysteries tour runs **6–8 hours** and covers the Taj Mahal, Mehtab Bagh, Agra Fort, and the bazaar walk. Adding Fatehpur Sikri extends the tour to a full day (9–10 hours). A half-day mysteries option (4 hours) focuses exclusively on the Taj Mahal and Mehtab Bagh with the mystery-focused narrative. All tours use a private vehicle and licensed guide. Lunch at a local restaurant is included in full-day versions. The tour is designed for curious, intellectually engaged travellers rather than those wanting a purely photographic or romantic experience." },
      { question: "Is the mysteries tour suitable for history enthusiasts?", answer: "The Mysteries of Agra tour is specifically designed for history enthusiasts, architecture researchers, and intellectually curious travellers. The guide — a specialist in Mughal architectural and political history — engages with the academic debates surrounding Agra's monuments rather than just presenting accepted narratives. If you have read Mughal history (Bamber Gascoigne's 'The Great Moghuls', Abraham Eraly's 'The Mughal Throne', or William Dalrymple's Mughal accounts), you will find the guide's commentary deeply complementary to your existing knowledge. This tour is explicitly not for visitors who want a quick photographic overview — it is for those who want to understand Agra at a depth impossible in a standard 2-hour tour." },
      { question: "Are children suited to the mysteries of Agra tour?", answer: "The mysteries format works surprisingly well for children aged 10 and above — the story elements (cut-off hands, secret underground chambers, the ghost of Mumtaz Mahal reportedly seen in the moonlight, why an entire city was abandoned overnight) are genuinely engaging for younger visitors in a way that straight architectural history sometimes is not. The guide calibrates the depth of analysis to suit mixed-age groups. For very young children (under 8), the full 6–8 hour tour may be long — a shorter 3–4 hour version focusing on the Taj Mahal and one mystery site is recommended for young families." },
      { question: "What makes this different from a standard Agra guided tour?", answer: "Standard Agra tours follow a fixed narrative: love story, construction facts, architectural beauty, photographic highlights. The mysteries tour is specifically designed for travellers who have already done (or want more than) the standard tour. It layers the standard history with: contested interpretations that are debated among historians, physical evidence at the sites that supports or refutes popular legends, the perspective of local craftsmen whose families have worked in Agra's stone-carving industry for generations, and the political intrigue of the Mughal court that contextualizes why the Taj Mahal was built in the way it was. The result is an Agra experience that generates conversations and questions for weeks after the visit." },
      { question: "Is the Agra mysteries tour available in languages other than English?", answer: "The mysteries tour is available in English (standard), and can be arranged in Spanish, French, German, Italian, Russian, and Japanese with advance notice. The mystery-focused narrative requires a guide with both deep historical knowledge and strong language fluency — language-specific guides are pre-vetted for both qualities. When booking, specify your preferred language. Last-minute language requests (less than 48 hours notice) may not always be possible for less common languages. English-language mysteries tours can be arranged with as little as 24 hours notice." },
      { question: "Can we visit Fatehpur Sikri on the mysteries tour?", answer: "Yes — Fatehpur Sikri is the perfect addition to the mysteries tour and one of India's greatest unsolved historical puzzles. Emperor Akbar built this entire city as his new imperial capital in 1569 and then completely abandoned it just 14 years later in 1585 — the reason given (water shortage) is disputed by historians. The city was never destroyed or rebuilt — it stands exactly as Akbar left it, 40 km from Agra. Entry to Fatehpur Sikri (₹610 for foreign nationals, included) adds approximately 2.5 hours to the tour. The guide examines the abandonment mystery on location, with evidence visible in the city's infrastructure that standard tour guides rarely discuss." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-agra-private-day-tour-with-lunch') {
    return [
      { question: "What is included in the Agra private day tour with lunch?", answer: "This comprehensive private day tour includes: hotel pickup and drop-off (Delhi or Agra), private air-conditioned vehicle for the full day, Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide, all entry tickets (Taj Mahal main complex + inner mausoleum + Agra Fort), a sit-down lunch at a quality restaurant in Agra, and overshoes for the Taj Mahal marble platform. The lunch is a full meal at a restaurant selected for hygiene, variety, and location. All major costs for the day are covered — no hidden charges at monument gates or restaurants. Bring only pocket money for personal purchases and the recommended guide tip." },
      { question: "What type of restaurant is used for lunch on the Agra day tour?", answer: "Lunch is served at a quality sit-down restaurant near Agra Fort — typically a well-established establishment that has served international visitors for many years. The menu includes: North Indian dishes (dal makhani, paneer tikka, naan, biryani), Mughlai cuisine (murgh makhani, shahi paneer, kebabs), continental options, and a selection of fresh salads and desserts. The restaurant is verified for food hygiene standards, international-style washrooms, and reliable vegetarian labelling. All dietary requirements are accommodated — vegetarian, vegan, Jain (no root vegetables), gluten-free, halal, and allergy-specific requests. Inform your guide at booking for the restaurant to prepare appropriately." },
      { question: "What sites are visited on the private Agra day tour?", answer: "The standard private day tour with lunch covers: (1) **Taj Mahal** — 2–2.5 hour guided visit covering the complete complex including the inner mausoleum; (2) **Agra Fort** — 1.5 hour guided visit to the UNESCO World Heritage Mughal fortress with views of the Taj Mahal from the Musamman Burj; (3) **Lunch** — 45–60 minutes at a quality restaurant. Optional additions available: **Mehtab Bagh** (moonlit garden, rear Taj view, 45 minutes), **Itmad-ud-Daula/Baby Taj** (first marble Mughal tomb, 1 hour), and a **Marble inlay craft workshop** (see Pietra Dura craftsmen at work, 30 minutes). The guide designs the itinerary around your interests and available time." },
      { question: "What time does the private Agra day tour from Delhi start and end?", answer: "For Delhi-based visitors: **Pickup from Delhi hotels at 5:30–6:00 AM** (early departure is essential to reach Agra for the best morning experience at the Taj Mahal). **Arrival in Agra: ~9:00 AM**. **Taj Mahal visit: 9:00–11:30 AM**. **Agra Fort: 11:30 AM–1:00 PM**. **Lunch: 1:00–2:00 PM**. **Departure from Agra: 2:30–3:00 PM**. **Return to Delhi hotels: ~6:00–7:00 PM**. Total day: approximately 13 hours. For Agra hotel guests, the tour typically runs 5:00 AM–2:00 PM (including a sunrise start). The early departure from Delhi is not optional if you want morning quality at the Taj Mahal." },
      { question: "Is the lunch suitable for vegetarians and vegans?", answer: "Yes — the lunch restaurant offers extensive vegetarian and vegan options. North Indian vegetarian cuisine is among the world's richest: dal makhani (lentil curry with butter and cream), paneer dishes (fresh Indian cheese in various preparations), various vegetable curries, stuffed parathas, biryanis, and fresh salads. Vegan options (all dishes prepared without dairy) are available on request. Jain vegetarian (no root vegetables, onions, or garlic) is accommodated with advance notice. Inform your guide about any dietary requirement at booking so the restaurant receives specific preparation instructions before your arrival." },
      { question: "Is the private day tour suitable for first-time visitors to India?", answer: "This private day tour is specifically designed to be the ideal first India experience. Everything is handled for you — transport, ticketing, guide, security navigation, and food. First-time India visitors often find Agra overwhelming independently: the crowd management, the persistent touts outside monuments, the complexity of buying the right tickets, and the navigation inside large complex sites can be stressful. A private guide immediately creates a protective bubble — you have a knowledgeable local professional managing all interactions, translating the experience, and ensuring you have a stress-free, enriching day. The lunch at a verified restaurant also removes any anxiety about food safety that many first-time India visitors experience." },
      { question: "Can the private day tour be combined with the Agra Fort visit only (no Taj Mahal)?", answer: "Yes — the private day tour can be customized to focus on any combination of Agra sites. If you have already visited the Taj Mahal on a previous trip (or on a separate day), the vehicle and guide can focus entirely on [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort), Itmad-ud-Daula (Baby Taj), Akbar's Tomb at Sikandra, and Mehtab Bagh. This alternative Agra tour covers sites that most visitors miss entirely and is highly recommended for repeat visitors. Lunch is included regardless of which sites are chosen. Share your previous Agra experience when booking so the guide prepares an itinerary that avoids duplication." },
      { question: "What is the best time of year for the private Agra day tour?", answer: "**October to March** is the optimal season for any Agra visit, and particularly for the private day tour from Delhi. November and February are the most comfortable months: temperatures of 18–28°C, clear skies, and excellent visibility of the white Taj Mahal marble. **December–January** can bring morning fog (beautiful but reduces visibility in photos); temperatures can drop to 8–12°C at dawn. **April–June** is very hot (40–46°C) — if visiting in summer, a 5:30 AM departure from Delhi is essential to complete most sightseeing before 11 AM. **July–September** (monsoon): humidity is high but green surroundings and dramatic cloud formations create unusual photography conditions." },
      { question: "Is tipping expected for the guide and driver on the Agra day tour?", answer: "Tipping is not mandatory but is warmly appreciated in India's tourism industry and reflects your satisfaction with the service. A recommended guideline: **₹300–500 per person** for the guide (for an excellent day's guiding), and **₹200–300** for the driver. These amounts are suggestions only — tip based on your satisfaction. If your guide went above and beyond — adapting to your interests, taking excellent photographs, managing unexpected situations smoothly — a higher tip reflects that. Tips are given directly in cash to the guide and driver at the end of the tour. US dollars and Euros are also accepted (guide can exchange)." },
      { question: "What type of 5-star lunch is included in the Taj Mahal tour?", answer: "The private day tour with lunch offers a premium dining experience at one of Agra's finest **5-star hotel restaurants** — typically **The Oberoi Amarvilas**, **ITC Mughal**, or **Jaypee Palace Hotel**, depending on availability and group size. The meal features an extensive spread of **Mughlai cuisine** (slow-cooked kebabs, biryanis, rich curries descended from royal Mughal kitchen recipes) alongside **continental options** (pastas, grilled dishes, salads) for those who prefer familiar flavours. All dietary requirements are fully accommodated — **vegetarian, vegan, Jain, gluten-free, halal, and allergy-specific** meals are prepared on request with advance notice. The highlight for many visitors is the **rooftop dining with direct Taj Mahal views** available at select venues, where you enjoy your meal with the white marble dome as your backdrop. Beverages (soft drinks, lassi, fresh juice) are included; alcoholic beverages are available at additional cost. For more dining and activity recommendations in the city, explore our guide to [things to do in Agra](/india/agra/things-to-do-in-agra)." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'agra-royal-sunrise-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What makes this tour 'royal' compared to a standard Agra sunrise tour?", answer: "The 'Royal Sunrise Tour' of Agra delivers an elevated, luxury-focused experience across every element: premium air-conditioned vehicle (luxury sedan or SUV rather than standard vehicle), senior Ministry of Tourism guide with specialisation in Mughal royal history, priority entry into the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort, a royal Mughal-inspired breakfast served at a premium heritage hotel or rooftop restaurant overlooking the Taj Mahal, and optional access to the Taj Mahal's moonlit viewing permit. The tour is designed to replicate — as closely as modern tourism allows — the experience of a privileged visitor to the Mughal court. The guide's narrative specifically focuses on the royal dimensions of the monuments: the emperors, the harem, the court rituals, and the political power expressed through architecture." },
      { question: "What is included in the Agra Royal Sunrise Tour?", answer: "Included: luxury air-conditioned vehicle and driver, hotel pickup from your Agra hotel at dawn (~5:00 AM), senior Ministry of Tourism-certified guide throughout the tour, priority entry tickets for Taj Mahal (main complex + inner mausoleum) and Agra Fort, a sit-down royal Mughal-style breakfast at a premium rooftop venue, and a royal welcome/farewell amenity. The complete tour covers the Taj Mahal at sunrise, Agra Fort, and an optional visit to Mehtab Bagh. Return to hotel by approximately 1:00 PM. The breakfast element — overlooking the Taj Mahal from a rooftop as the morning light changes — is a genuinely special experience that standard tours do not include." },
      { question: "Where is the royal breakfast served during the Agra sunrise tour?", answer: "The royal breakfast is served at a premium rooftop restaurant in the Taj Ganj area — the historic neighbourhood immediately south of the Taj Mahal complex — that offers unobstructed direct views of the Taj Mahal's white marble dome and minarets. Several heritage properties in this area have maintained rooftop restaurants specifically for this purpose. Breakfast is typically served from approximately 8:00 AM (after the sunrise Taj Mahal session), and the combination of fresh North Indian and continental breakfast foods with the Taj Mahal in the background in morning light is one of Agra's most memorable experiences. The exact venue is confirmed based on availability and seasonal setup." },
      { question: "What royal Mughal history does the guide cover on this tour?", answer: "The senior guide on the Royal Sunrise Tour goes beyond standard architectural history to provide a royal court perspective: the daily life of Mughal emperors (Shah Jahan's 5,000-strong harem, the zenana quarters at Agra Fort, the architecture of female power in Mughal India), the succession wars that defined Mughal history (Aurangzeb's imprisonment of Shah Jahan, the brutal fratricidal conflicts among Mughal princes), the economics of empire (how was the Taj Mahal's construction financed?), and the gradual decline of Mughal power from Shah Jahan's era onward. This richer political and social context transforms the monuments from beautiful buildings into windows onto one of history's most extraordinary dynasties." },
      { question: "Can this tour be arranged for a special occasion (anniversary, honeymoon, proposal)?", answer: "The Royal Sunrise Tour is one of our most popular choices for romantic special occasions. For **proposals**: the guide can arrange a private moment on the Taj Mahal terrace or in Mehtab Bagh with the Taj Mahal as a backdrop — one of the world's most stunning proposal settings. For **honeymoons and anniversaries**: the royal breakfast with Taj views, private vehicle, and senior guide create an experience that feels genuinely exclusive. Special additions — flower arrangements, a bottle of champagne at the breakfast venue, or a handwritten parchment dedication — can be arranged on request. Inform us of the special occasion when booking and we will add personal touches." },
      { question: "What luxury vehicle is used for the Royal Sunrise Tour?", answer: "The Royal Sunrise Tour uses a premium luxury vehicle — options include the **Toyota Innova Crysta** (premium SUV, excellent road comfort), **Toyota Fortuner** (larger SUV with extra space), or **Mercedes E-Class / BMW 5 Series** (maximum luxury for couples or small groups). All vehicles are chauffeur-driven, spotlessly clean, air-conditioned, and equipped with USB charging, Wi-Fi, and a personal travel amenity bag (wet wipes, mineral water, breath mints). For the 5:00 AM pickup in Agra, the vehicle is pre-cooled or pre-heated depending on the season, and the driver is waiting at the hotel entrance before the agreed time." },
      { question: "Is the Royal Sunrise Tour available for groups?", answer: "Yes — the Royal Sunrise Tour is available for groups of any size, from couples to wedding parties or corporate groups. For groups larger than 6, multiple luxury vehicles are arranged to maintain the premium experience rather than using a large bus format. Corporate groups sometimes book the Royal Tour for client entertainment — the combination of one of the world's greatest monuments, a luxury vehicle, a senior guide, and a rooftop breakfast creates an impressive and memorable experience. All inclusions scale proportionally for larger groups. Contact us with your group size for specific pricing and vehicle configuration recommendations." },
      { question: "How does the Royal Sunrise Tour differ from the standard sunrise tour?", answer: "Standard sunrise tour elements: hotel pickup in a Toyota Innova or similar, mid-level guide, entry tickets, monument visit. **Royal Sunrise Tour adds:** luxury vehicle (premium sedan/SUV), senior specialist guide with royal history focus, priority processing at entry gates, Mughal royal breakfast at a rooftop Taj-view restaurant, personal travel amenity bag in the vehicle, and concierge-style attention to special requests. The price premium reflects the vehicle upgrade, senior guide fee, and the breakfast venue (which is not cheap). For travellers for whom this is a once-in-a-lifetime experience, the Royal Tour is the most complete way to experience Agra." },
      { question: "What time does the Agra Royal Sunrise Tour end?", answer: "The Royal Sunrise Tour follows this schedule: **5:00 AM** hotel pickup, **5:30–6:00 AM** Taj Mahal gate arrival, **5:30–8:00 AM** Taj Mahal sunrise guided visit, **8:00–9:00 AM** royal breakfast at rooftop venue, **9:30–11:00 AM** Agra Fort guided visit, **11:00–11:45 AM** optional Mehtab Bagh visit, **12:00–1:00 PM** return to hotel. The tour concludes by approximately **12:00–1:00 PM**, leaving the afternoon free for rest, additional exploration, shopping in Agra's famous marble-ware and leather craft markets, or your onward journey (Agra to Jaipur by car is 5–6 hours)." },
      { question: "What makes the sunrise Taj Mahal experience different from visiting later in the day?", answer: "The sunrise experience at the Taj Mahal is fundamentally different from a mid-morning or afternoon visit in several important ways. The **golden and pink light** of early dawn illuminates the white Makrana marble with warm hues that shift minute by minute — colours that are completely absent by 9:00 AM when the light turns flat and white. The gates open at approximately **6:00 AM** (varying slightly by season), and the first 30–45 minutes inside the complex offer **dramatically fewer crowds** — often just a few hundred visitors compared to the 20,000–40,000 who pass through on a busy midday. The **cooler temperatures** (especially October–March, when dawn temperatures are 8–18°C vs. 28–35°C by noon) make the walking experience far more comfortable. The **reflection pool photographs** — the Taj Mahal mirrored in the long central water channel — are at their most pristine in the windless early morning. On many mornings, a light **mist rising from the Yamuna River** behind the Taj creates an ethereal, dreamlike backdrop that vanishes by 8:00 AM. For photographers seeking the most dramatic conditions, consider the dedicated [Taj Mahal photography tour](/india/agra/taj-mahal-photography-tour) which is specifically designed around optimal light windows." }
    ];
  }

  // --- END AGRA TOUR FAQS BATCH 3 ---

  // --- AGRA TOUR FAQS BATCH 4 (FINAL AGRA) ---

  if (slug === 'same-day-taj-mahal-tour-by-car-from-delhi') {
    return [
      { question: "Is the same-day Taj Mahal tour from Delhi by car worth it?", answer: "Yes — a same-day Taj Mahal tour from Delhi by car is one of India's most popular day trips and is absolutely worth it for most visitors. The Taj Mahal is 200 km from Delhi (3–3.5 hours via the Yamuna Expressway), and a well-organized day allows for a comprehensive visit to the Taj Mahal and [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort) before returning to Delhi in the evening. The key success factor is an early departure (5:30–6:00 AM) to arrive at the Taj Mahal for the morning before crowds. By departing on the return at 2:30–3:00 PM, you avoid Agra midday heat and Delhi evening rush hour simultaneously." },
      { question: "Why go by car rather than by train for the Delhi-Agra day trip?", answer: "Going by **private car** offers several advantages over the train for a same-day Taj Mahal trip: complete flexibility on departure time (critical for sunrise visits), door-to-door hotel pickup and drop-off, ability to stop en route or adjust the itinerary mid-day, the vehicle waits throughout the day so you are never constrained by a train timetable, and easier logistics for families with luggage. The **Gatimaan Express train** is faster (1h40m vs 3h30m) and offers a unique Indian railway experience, but fixed departure times mean you typically arrive later than a car (train departs ~8 AM vs car ~5:30 AM), missing the best Taj Mahal sunrise window. For sunrise-focused visits, the private car is the better choice." },
      { question: "What is the exact route from Delhi to Agra by car?", answer: "The standard route uses the **Yamuna Expressway (NH19)**: Delhi (exit via DND Flyway or Noida Expressway) → Yamuna Expressway (165 km, 6-lane divided highway) → Agra Cantonment exit → city roads to Taj Mahal South Gate. Total distance: approximately 200 km. Journey time: 3–3.5 hours in normal conditions. The Yamuna Expressway is smooth, well-maintained, and largely traffic-free in the early morning. Toll charges (approximately ₹415 each way) are included in the tour price. Avoid the old NH2 highway through towns — it adds 45+ minutes and significant stress." },
      { question: "What sites does the same-day Taj Mahal car tour from Delhi cover?", answer: "The standard itinerary covers: (1) **Taj Mahal** — complete 2–2.5 hour guided visit including the inner mausoleum (entry tickets included); (2) **Agra Fort** — 1.5 hour guided visit to the UNESCO World Heritage fortress; (3) **Sit-down lunch** in Agra at a quality restaurant; and optionally (4) **Mehtab Bagh** or **Itmad-ud-Daula (Baby Taj)** for visitors interested in additional monuments. All entry tickets for these sites are included in the tour price. The guide manages all logistics so you experience the maximum amount in the available time without rushing." },
      { question: "What time will the car tour return to Delhi?", answer: "Departure from Agra is typically at **2:30–3:00 PM** after lunch, arriving back in Delhi by **6:00–7:00 PM** (total day: approximately 13 hours). The return timing can be adjusted — if you want to spend more time in Agra, a later return (4–5 PM departure from Agra) is possible, though this risks arriving in Delhi during rush hour (7–9 PM). Early departure from Agra (before 2 PM) can get you back in Delhi by 5:30 PM. Discuss your preferred timing with the driver when booking. The private car format means departure is whenever you decide, not a fixed coach departure time." },
      { question: "Is there a toilet stop on the Delhi-Agra highway?", answer: "Yes — the Yamuna Expressway has modern service plazas at regular intervals with clean, maintained restroom facilities, petrol stations, and cafes. Your driver typically stops at one service plaza en route to Agra (approximately 1.5 hours from Delhi) for a 10–15 minute comfort break. On the return journey, a similar stop is made. For families with young children, additional stops can be made at any service plaza — inform the driver of your preferences. The service plazas also sell bottled water, packaged snacks, and Indian fast food if needed between meals." },
      { question: "Is the same-day car tour suitable for elderly passengers?", answer: "Yes — the private car tour is the most comfortable format for elderly visitors. The vehicle is air-conditioned throughout, the driver maintains a smooth pace on the expressway, and departure and return are door-to-door from your hotel. Inside the Taj Mahal, electric golf buggies are available for mobility-impaired visitors (arranged by the guide at the gate). The main physical requirement is the short climb to the Taj Mahal marble terrace (approximately 30 steps). For visitors who cannot manage stairs, the terrace level is accessible by ramp for wheelchair users. The guide adapts the pace and duration at each site to suit the group's physical comfort." },
      { question: "Are tickets to the Taj Mahal included in the same-day car tour?", answer: "Yes — all entry tickets are included: Taj Mahal main complex (₹1,300 for foreign nationals), inner mausoleum (₹200), and Agra Fort (₹650). These are pre-purchased or purchased by your guide on arrival — no additional payment required at any gate. The total included ticket value is approximately ₹2,150 per foreign national. Children under 15 enter all ASI monuments for free. Indian nationals have significantly lower ticket prices; if your group includes both foreign and Indian nationals, inform us when booking for accurate pricing." },
      { question: "Can I book a same-day car tour from Delhi for just one person?", answer: "Yes — solo travellers can book the same-day Delhi-Agra car tour. The per-person price for a solo traveller is higher than for groups (the vehicle, guide, and driver costs are divided across fewer people), but the private experience — one-on-one guide interaction, flexible timing, and complete privacy — is worth the premium. If you prefer a more economical option, enquire about joining a shared group tour with other travellers. However, private is strongly recommended for anyone who values a personalized experience and does not want to be rushed by a group schedule." },
      { question: "What should I wear for the same-day Taj Mahal tour from Delhi?", answer: "Comfortable, breathable cotton clothing is ideal. Modest dress is recommended (cover shoulders, avoid very short shorts or skirts) out of respect at this active mausoleum. Comfortable walking shoes that are easy to remove are essential — shoes must be taken off at the marble terrace of the Taj Mahal. Closed shoes with socks are preferable to sandals (the marble can be hot in summer and the security process is smoother with proper shoes). A hat and sunscreen are important from March onwards. A light stole or scarf is useful for female visitors as an optional head covering and as a layer against early morning car AC." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-guided-tour-from-agra') {
    return [
      { question: "What does the guided tour of the Taj Mahal from Agra include?", answer: "This tour starts from your Agra hotel and includes: hotel pickup by private vehicle, a Ministry of Tourism-licensed professional guide for the complete Taj Mahal visit, all entry tickets (main complex + inner mausoleum), overshoes for the marble platform, and drop-off back at your hotel. The guide provides full architectural and historical commentary covering the complete complex — from the Great Gate through the charbagh garden to the main mausoleum exterior, interior, and flanking mosque and guest house. Duration is 2–2.5 hours inside the complex. Additional sites (Agra Fort, Mehtab Bagh) can be added to create a half-day or full-day tour." },
      { question: "What is the advantage of booking a guided tour vs. visiting independently?", answer: "Visiting the Taj Mahal with a licensed guide transforms the experience from a photo opportunity into a historically and architecturally profound journey. Without a guide, the monument provides minimal interpretation — a few small information boards. A licensed guide covers: the 22-year construction story (1631–1653), the 20,000 artisans, the 28 varieties of semi-precious stone in the Pietra Dura inlay, the Quranic calligraphy that frames every archway, the optical illusion of the minarets leaning outward for earthquake safety, and the deeply romantic history of Shah Jahan and Mumtaz Mahal. The guide also manages security entry, ticket logistics, and photography positioning — eliminating stress and allowing full focus on the experience." },
      { question: "How long is the guided tour of the Taj Mahal from Agra?", answer: "The guided tour of the Taj Mahal from your Agra hotel takes approximately **3.5–4 hours total**: 15–20 minutes vehicle transit from hotel to monument (plus buggy/walk from parking to gate), **2–2.5 hours** guided visit inside the complex, and 20–30 minutes return to hotel. If you start at sunrise (recommended), you are back at your hotel by 9:00–9:30 AM — leaving the rest of the morning free for Agra Fort, checkout, or onward travel. The guided visit itself is unhurried — if you want to spend 30 minutes at the reflection pool rather than 10, the guide accommodates." },
      { question: "Which entry gate does the Agra guided tour use?", answer: "Most guided tours from Agra hotels use the **South Gate** (Main Gate) — the principal ceremonial entrance that aligns with the monument's central axis, providing the famous first framed view of the Taj Mahal through the Great Gate archway. This is the most architecturally significant and visually dramatic entry. The East Gate is used when the South Gate has unusually long queues or for logistical reasons based on your hotel location. Both gates lead to the same complex. Your guide selects the optimal gate on the morning of the visit based on current conditions." },
      { question: "Can the guided tour from Agra include the moonlight visit?", answer: "Yes — if your Agra dates coincide with the 5-night moonlight viewing period (full moon ± 2 days), the moonlight permit can be added to your guided tour package. The moonlight visit is a separate experience from the daytime tour — it runs in 30-minute sessions from 8:30 PM to 12:30 AM, with maximum 400 visitors per session. Permits (₹750 for foreign nationals) must be booked in advance through the ASI system. Your guide arranges the permit and accompanies you for the moonlight session. Combining a sunrise morning visit with a moonlight evening visit on the same day in Agra is extraordinary — white marble in gold dawn light and then silver-blue moonlight." },
      { question: "Is the Taj Mahal guided tour from Agra suitable for a half-day itinerary?", answer: "Yes — the Taj Mahal guided tour from Agra is naturally a half-day activity (3.5–4 hours total from hotel). When combined with Agra Fort (15-minute drive away, 1.5 hours with guide), the combined tour runs approximately 5.5–6 hours — an excellent full morning itinerary that completes both UNESCO sites before lunch. This schedule works particularly well for visitors checking out of Agra at midday and continuing to Jaipur by car (5–6 hour drive) or Delhi (3.5 hours). The guide can advise on the optimal timing sequence based on your departure time." },
      { question: "What is the Taj Mahal inner mausoleum and is it included?", answer: "The inner mausoleum (known as the 'main chamber') is the central domed interior of the Taj Mahal containing the marble cenotaphs (decorative tombs) of Mumtaz Mahal and Shah Jahan, surrounded by an ornate pierced marble screen (jali) with intricate Pietra Dura inlay work. Entering the inner chamber is the emotional and aesthetic climax of any Taj Mahal visit — the scale of the interior dome, the quality of the craftsmanship, and the knowledge that this is where Shah Jahan was buried alongside his beloved wife creates a genuinely moving experience. The inner mausoleum entry costs ₹200 additional for foreign nationals and **is included** in this guided tour price." },
      { question: "What happens at the Taj Mahal security check?", answer: "The Taj Mahal security process involves: (1) ticket verification and identity check (passport or national ID required for foreign nationals — carry a digital copy); (2) luggage X-ray; (3) brief physical security check (separate male/female lines). Items confiscated include: food, tobacco, selfie sticks, tripods (without paid permits), and sharp objects. The entire security process takes 5–15 minutes depending on crowd levels. With a guide, you know exactly what to leave in the vehicle beforehand, making security smooth and fast. Your guide queues alongside you and handles any questions from security staff. Be at the gate 10–15 minutes before the opening time to secure first-entry position." },
      { question: "Is the guide fee included or paid separately?", answer: "The Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide fee is fully included in the tour price — there is no additional payment required for guiding services. This is important to note because many budget operators claim to include a guide but provide only a vehicle and driver, expecting visitors to hire a guide at the gate (where unlicensed touts operate). This tour includes a certified, pre-vetted professional guide as a standard inclusion. The only optional additional payment is a voluntary tip for the guide and driver at the end of the tour (recommended ₹300–500 per person for excellent service)." },
      { question: "Can I combine the Taj Mahal guided tour with other Agra monuments on the same day?", answer: "Yes — the Taj Mahal guided tour from Agra is easily combined with other major monuments for a comprehensive full-day Agra experience. **Agra Fort** is just **3 km away** (10–15 minute drive) and pairs naturally with the Taj Mahal — the fort's Musamman Burj offers the famous view of the Taj that imprisoned Shah Jahan gazed upon for his final eight years. **Itmad-ud-Daulah** (the 'Baby Taj'), located **6 km** north across the Yamuna, is the exquisite marble tomb that served as a direct architectural precursor to the Taj Mahal and features even finer Pietra Dura inlay work. **Mehtab Bagh** (Moonlight Garden), directly across the river from the Taj, provides the iconic **sunset view** of the Taj Mahal reflected in the Yamuna — the perfect conclusion to a full day. A typical full-day combination runs 6–8 hours: sunrise Taj Mahal, mid-morning Agra Fort, lunch, afternoon Baby Taj, and sunset at Mehtab Bagh. For a structured combination that covers both UNESCO sites with a single guide, consider the [Taj Mahal & Agra Fort guided tour](/india/agra/taj-mahal-agra-fort-guided-tour)." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-vrindavan-full-day-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What is Vrindavan and why combine it with the Taj Mahal?", answer: "Vrindavan is one of Hinduism's most sacred pilgrimage cities — believed to be the birthplace and childhood home of Lord Krishna, revered as the site where the divine love of Radha and Krishna was enacted. The city is home to over 5,000 temples, thousands of sadhus (holy men), and a deeply devotional atmosphere unlike anywhere else in India. Combining Vrindavan with the Taj Mahal creates an extraordinary day that captures two completely different dimensions of the Yamuna river valley: the Mughal architectural expression of love (Taj Mahal) and the Hindu devotional expression of divine love (Vrindavan). Both sites sit on the same river; both are about love — but in profoundly different cultural traditions." },
      { question: "What is the itinerary for the full-day Taj Mahal and Vrindavan tour?", answer: "**5:30–6:00 AM** — Pickup from hotel (Delhi or Agra). **9:00–11:30 AM** — Taj Mahal visit with licensed guide (complete 2.5-hour guided tour including inner mausoleum). **12:00–1:00 PM** — Drive from Agra to Vrindavan (approximately 70 km, 1.5 hours). **1:00–1:30 PM** — Lunch at a local Vrindavan restaurant (pure vegetarian as per local tradition — no meat, eggs, or onions in many Vrindavan establishments). **1:30–4:00 PM** — Vrindavan tour: Banke Bihari Temple, ISKCON Vrindavan (largest in India), Prem Mandir, Govind Dev Temple, and a walk through the ghats. **4:30–5:00 PM** — Departure for Delhi or Agra. **7:30–9:00 PM** — Arrival (depending on destination)." },
      { question: "Is Vrindavan suitable for non-Hindu visitors?", answer: "Absolutely — Vrindavan is welcoming to visitors of all faiths and backgrounds. The temples, while deeply active religious sites, are generally open to international visitors with appropriate modest dress (covering shoulders and legs, removing shoes before temple entry). The atmosphere — thousands of flower petals, the sound of devotional music (bhajans), the smell of incense and prasad (offered sweets), the colourful temple facades — is a profoundly sensory and cultural experience regardless of religious belief. Your guide provides cultural context throughout, explaining Krishna mythology, temple architecture, and the significance of the rituals you observe." },
      { question: "What are the key temples to visit in Vrindavan?", answer: "The four most significant Vrindavan temples on this tour: (1) **Banke Bihari Temple** — the most important Vrindavan temple, famous for its unusual puja ritual where the deity's curtain is repeatedly opened and closed (to protect devotees from the intensity of the divine gaze); (2) **ISKCON Vrindavan** (Sri Krishna Balaram Mandir) — the international Krishna consciousness temple, architecturally spectacular and welcoming to international visitors; (3) **Prem Mandir** — a stunning modern white marble temple (completed 2012) with elaborate night illuminations and carvings depicting Krishna and Radha; (4) **Govind Dev Temple** (partially ruined) — a 1590 Mughal-era temple representing the fusion of Mughal and Hindu architectural styles." },
      { question: "What is the distance from Agra to Vrindavan?", answer: "Vrindavan is approximately **70 km from Agra** (1–1.5 hours by road), and approximately **145 km from Delhi** (2.5–3 hours). The full-day Taj Mahal + Vrindavan tour typically starts from Delhi or Agra and visits both sites in sequence: Taj Mahal first (arriving by 9 AM), then Vrindavan in the afternoon (arriving by noon–1 PM), with the return journey in the evening. The route between Agra and Vrindavan follows the NH19 northward — both cities are on the same stretch of the Yamuna river. If you are based in Delhi, the full round trip by car is approximately 320 km and makes for a long but rewarding day." },
      { question: "What is the dress code for visiting temples in Vrindavan?", answer: "Temple visits in Vrindavan require: **covered shoulders and legs** for all visitors (both male and female) — no sleeveless tops, shorts, or short skirts. A dupatta (scarf) is useful for women to drape over the head as a mark of respect inside certain temples. **Shoes must be removed** before entering any temple — wear footwear that is easy to slip on and off (sandals or easy-removal shoes are strongly recommended for Vrindavan). Some temples request that leather items (belts, bags) not be brought inside. **Non-vegetarian food** cannot be brought into the temple area. Your guide will brief you on specific requirements for each temple before entry." },
      { question: "Is lunch included in the Taj Mahal and Vrindavan full-day tour?", answer: "Yes — a vegetarian lunch is included at a quality restaurant in or near Vrindavan. Vrindavan is a strictly vegetarian city (reflecting its deep Krishna devotional tradition — no meat, eggs, or alcohol are sold or consumed in the temple areas). The lunch restaurant serves North Indian vegetarian cuisine: paneer dishes, dal, fresh rotis, sabzis, rice, and sweets. This is an opportunity to eat genuinely authentic Braj-region cuisine (the cultural region encompassing Mathura and Vrindavan), including dishes offered as prasad in temples. For non-vegetarians, Vrindavan's vegetarian food culture is typically surprising — the quality and variety of vegetarian dishes in this region is exceptional." },
      { question: "Can this tour be combined with a visit to Mathura (Krishna's birthplace)?", answer: "Yes — Mathura (Lord Krishna's actual birthplace city) is 12 km from Vrindavan and can easily be included in the full-day tour. The key site is the **Krishna Janmabhoomi complex** — the temple built over the spot where Krishna was born, adjacent to a mosque built by Aurangzeb on the same site (creating one of India's most politically sensitive religious locations). Adding Mathura extends the tour by approximately 1.5–2 hours. A combined Taj Mahal + Mathura + Vrindavan tour makes for an extraordinarily rich day covering Mughal architecture, Hindu pilgrimage, and the cultural landscape of the Yamuna river valley from three very different perspectives." },
      { question: "Is the full-day Taj Mahal Vrindavan tour available from Delhi?", answer: "Yes — the full-day tour operates from Delhi with hotel pickup at 5:30–6:00 AM. Visiting the Taj Mahal first (arriving Agra ~9 AM, completing by ~11:30 AM), then driving to Vrindavan (~1 hour), allows approximately 2.5–3 hours in Vrindavan before the return to Delhi. Drop-off in Delhi is typically by 8:00–9:00 PM. It is a long day (14–15 hours total) but combines three of India's most iconic sites (Taj Mahal, Vrindavan, and the Yamuna river landscape) in one comprehensive itinerary. For visitors with limited time in India who want maximum cultural breadth, this tour delivers extraordinary value." },
      { question: "Is the Mathura & Vrindavan portion of the tour suitable for non-Hindu visitors?", answer: "Absolutely — the Mathura and Vrindavan experience is a deeply enriching **cultural journey** that resonates with visitors of all faiths and backgrounds. The temples are architectural marvels in their own right: **Prem Mandir's** intricate white marble carvings rival any monument in India, while the **500-year-old Govind Dev Temple** showcases a fascinating fusion of Mughal and Hindu design. The **ISKCON temple** (International Society for Krishna Consciousness) explicitly welcomes visitors of every nationality and religion — it was founded to share Krishna philosophy with the world and conducts services in English. The vibrant street life — flower sellers, devotional music echoing through narrow lanes, colourful powder markets, and the riverside ghats — provides an immersive sensory experience that transcends religious boundaries. If you visit during **Holi festival** (February–March), Vrindavan hosts India's most famous celebrations with weeks of colour, music, and dance. The spiritual atmosphere of devotion, community, and joy is universally accessible and deeply moving regardless of personal belief. For more context on planning your Agra region visit, see our comprehensive [Agra travel guide](/india/agra/agra-travel-guide-2026)." }
    ];
  }

  // --- AGRA TOUR FAQS BATCH 5 ---

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-fort-guided-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "Is the guide for the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort tour government-certified?", answer: "Yes — your guide is a **Ministry of Tourism-licensed** professional, certified by the Archaeological Survey of India (ASI) to operate at all federally protected monuments in Agra. They carry an official government-issued photo ID card that you can verify at any monument entrance. Licensed guides undergo a rigorous 2-year training programme covering Mughal history, Islamic architecture, and heritage conservation. This certification matters because unlicensed touts at the gates often provide inaccurate information and lack depth. For a Taj-only option, see our [Taj Mahal Official Guided Tour](/india/agra/taj-mahal-official-guided-tour)." },
      { question: "How long does the combined Taj Mahal and Agra Fort guided tour take?", answer: "The combined tour takes approximately **4.5 to 5.5 hours** in total: **2 to 2.5 hours** at the Taj Mahal (including security entry, the full garden walk, main mausoleum interior, and the flanking mosque) and **1.5 to 2 hours** at Agra Fort (covering Diwan-i-Am, Diwan-i-Khas, Sheesh Mahal, Musamman Burj, and Jahangir Palace). Travel time between the two monuments is approximately **15 minutes** by car. Starting at sunrise is recommended so you complete both sites before the midday heat, which can exceed **45 degrees Celsius** from April through June." },
      { question: "Where is the meeting point for the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort tour?", answer: "Your guide meets you at your **Agra hotel lobby** at the pre-agreed time — typically **30 minutes before Taj Mahal opening** for sunrise visits. Hotel pickup is included in the tour price. If you are arriving from Delhi by car or train, the guide can meet you at the **Agra Cantt railway station** or at the Taj Mahal South Gate directly. The exact meeting point is confirmed via WhatsApp the evening before. For travellers coming from Delhi, consider our [Taj Mahal & Agra Overnight Tour from Delhi](/india/agra/taj-mahal-agra-overnight-tour-from-delhi) which includes all transfers." },
      { question: "Are entry tickets to the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort included in the tour price?", answer: "Yes — all entry tickets are **included in the tour price**. For foreign nationals, the Taj Mahal entry fee is **₹1,300** plus **₹200** for the inner mausoleum, and Agra Fort entry is **₹650** — a combined ticket value of approximately **₹2,150** per person. Indian nationals pay significantly less (₹50 for Taj Mahal, ₹35 for Agra Fort). Children under 15 enter free at both ASI monuments. Your guide handles all ticket purchases and queue management so you walk straight through without delays or confusion at the counters." },
      { question: "What languages are available for the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort guided tour?", answer: "The standard tour language is **English**. Additional languages available on request include **French, German, Spanish, Italian, Japanese, Korean, Mandarin Chinese, Russian, and Hindi**. Non-English language guides are subject to availability and should be requested at the time of booking — at least **48 hours in advance** is recommended for less common languages. All guides are government-certified in their respective languages. The guide's commentary covers the complete Mughal narrative connecting both monuments, including the love story of Shah Jahan and Mumtaz Mahal, architectural techniques, and the political history of the Mughal Empire." },
      { question: "What is the difference between booking a Taj Mahal-only guide and the combined Taj Mahal and Agra Fort tour?", answer: "The combined tour is strongly recommended over a Taj-only visit because the two monuments tell **one continuous story**. The Taj Mahal is where Shah Jahan's love for Mumtaz Mahal is expressed in architecture; Agra Fort is where Shah Jahan was **imprisoned by his son Aurangzeb** for 8 years until his death in 1666, with only a distant window view of the Taj from the Musamman Burj tower. Without visiting both, you miss the tragic conclusion of the story. The combined tour also saves money compared to booking two separate guided visits. For a Taj-only option, see our [Taj Mahal Entry Ticket tour](/india/agra/taj-mahal-entry-ticket)." },
      { question: "Can I add Fatehpur Sikri to the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort guided tour?", answer: "Yes — **Fatehpur Sikri** can be added as a half-day extension, turning this into a full-day Agra heritage tour. Fatehpur Sikri is **37 km from Agra** (approximately 45 minutes by car) and requires **1.5 to 2 hours** for a complete guided visit. The combined Taj Mahal + Agra Fort + Fatehpur Sikri tour typically runs **8 to 9 hours** total. Adding Fatehpur Sikri is highly recommended — it was Emperor Akbar's purpose-built capital city, abandoned after just 14 years due to water scarcity, and is one of India's best-preserved Mughal ghost cities. See our dedicated [Fatehpur Sikri Guided Tour](/india/agra/fatehpur-sikri-guided-tour) for details." },
      { question: "What is the best time to visit the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort together?", answer: "The best strategy is to visit the **Taj Mahal at sunrise** (gates open at **6:00 AM**) when crowds are minimal and the white marble glows in soft golden light, then proceed to **Agra Fort by 9:00–9:30 AM** when morning light illuminates the red sandstone beautifully. This sequence completes both monuments by **11:00–11:30 AM**, well before peak midday heat. The **October to March** season offers the most comfortable temperatures (**15–25 degrees Celsius**). Avoid Fridays — the Taj Mahal is closed every Friday for prayers. If your visit falls on a Friday, consider our [Agra Friday Tour](/india/agra/agra-friday-tour-taj-closed-alternative) instead." },
      { question: "What is the walking distance between the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort?", answer: "The Taj Mahal and Agra Fort are approximately **2.5 km apart** along the Yamuna River. While the two monuments are visible from each other (the famous view of the Taj from the Musamman Burj tower inside Agra Fort), walking between them is **not recommended** due to Agra's traffic, heat, and road conditions. Your tour includes a **private air-conditioned vehicle** that transfers you between the two sites in **10–15 minutes**. The vehicle waits at each monument while you visit, serving as a cool resting point between sites and a secure place to leave bags and water." },
      { question: "What monuments and structures are covered inside Agra Fort?", answer: "Agra Fort is a massive **94-acre UNESCO World Heritage** red sandstone fortress with over 20 significant structures. Your guide covers the key highlights: **Diwan-i-Am** (Hall of Public Audience where the emperor held court), **Diwan-i-Khas** (Hall of Private Audience with exquisite marble inlay), **Sheesh Mahal** (Mirror Palace with thousands of glass fragments), **Musamman Burj** (the octagonal tower where Shah Jahan was imprisoned with his view of the Taj Mahal), **Jahangir Palace** (the largest palace inside the fort), **Khas Mahal** (Shah Jahan's private marble palace), and the **Nagina Masjid** (Gem Mosque). The fort was the seat of the Mughal Empire for nearly a century." },
      { question: "Is the combined Taj Mahal and Agra Fort tour suitable for elderly visitors or children?", answer: "Yes — both monuments are manageable for elderly visitors and families with children. The Taj Mahal requires climbing approximately **30 steps** to the marble platform (wheelchair ramps are available), and the interior visit involves flat surfaces. Agra Fort has more uneven terrain and some steeper steps, but your guide selects a route that minimises difficult sections. **Electric buggies** are available at the Taj Mahal (₹300) for visitors who cannot walk the 500-metre path from the gate to the monument. The private vehicle between sites provides air-conditioned rest. Your guide adjusts the pace and duration based on the group's comfort level." },
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-agra-overnight-tour-from-delhi') {
    return [
      { question: "Is hotel accommodation included in the Taj Mahal overnight tour from Delhi?", answer: "Yes — one night's accommodation in a **4-star hotel** in Agra is included in the tour package. Standard hotels include properties like the Courtyard by Marriott Agra, Crystal Sarovar Premiere, or equivalent rated hotels located **3–5 km from the Taj Mahal**. The room includes breakfast, Wi-Fi, and air conditioning. Upgrades to **5-star luxury hotels** (The Oberoi Amarvilas with direct Taj Mahal views, ITC Mughal, or Trident Agra) are available at an additional cost. Hotel assignment is confirmed at booking — you can request a specific property or category based on your preferences and budget." },
      { question: "Can I see the Taj Mahal at both sunset and sunrise on the overnight tour?", answer: "Yes — this is the **primary advantage** of the overnight tour over a same-day trip. On **Day 1**, you visit the Taj Mahal in the late afternoon when the white marble turns golden-orange in the sunset light (entry until one hour before sunset). On **Day 2**, you return at **sunrise** (gates open at 6:00 AM) when the marble glows pink and gold in the early morning light with minimal crowds. Seeing the Taj Mahal in two completely different lighting conditions is an extraordinary experience that same-day visitors miss entirely. Between the two visits, you can also view the Taj from [Mehtab Bagh](/india/agra/things-to-do-in-agra) at sunset." },
      { question: "What is the drive time from Delhi to Agra for the overnight tour?", answer: "The drive from Delhi to Agra takes approximately **3 to 3.5 hours** via the Yamuna Expressway (NH19), a modern **6-lane divided highway** covering 200 km. Departure from your Delhi hotel is typically at **8:00–9:00 AM** (later than same-day tours since you have two full days). The expressway is smooth, well-maintained, and largely traffic-free outside rush hours. Toll charges (approximately **₹415 each way**) are included in the tour price. A comfort stop is made at a highway service plaza approximately 90 minutes into the journey. The return drive on Day 2 departs Agra after lunch." },
      { question: "What type of private car is used for the Delhi to Agra overnight tour?", answer: "A **private air-conditioned vehicle** is assigned exclusively to your group for the entire duration — both days and overnight. Vehicle types include: **Toyota Innova Crysta** (6-seat SUV, most popular for families and groups of 3–5), **sedan** (Toyota Etios or similar for couples/solo), or a **tempo traveller** (12-seat minibus for groups of 7+). The vehicle includes USB charging, bottled water, and tissue supplies. The same driver stays with you throughout, ensuring consistency and familiarity. All fuel, tolls, parking fees, and driver accommodation are included in the tour price." },
      { question: "Is a licensed guide included for the full overnight tour?", answer: "Yes — a **Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide** accompanies you for all monument visits across both days. The guide provides comprehensive historical commentary at the Taj Mahal (both sunset and sunrise visits), Agra Fort, and any additional monuments on your itinerary. Having the same guide for two days allows for much deeper engagement with Mughal history — Day 1 covers the Taj Mahal's construction story and architecture, while Day 2 explores the broader political narrative at Agra Fort. The guide is available in **English** as standard, with other languages on request. See our [Taj Mahal Official Guided Tour](/india/agra/taj-mahal-official-guided-tour) for guide details." },
      { question: "Are meals included in the overnight Taj Mahal tour from Delhi?", answer: "The tour includes **breakfast at your Agra hotel** on Day 2 and a **sit-down lunch** on both days at quality Agra restaurants. Dinner on Day 1 is at the hotel restaurant or a recommended local restaurant (cost included in the package). Restaurants serve North Indian, Mughlai, and continental cuisine with comprehensive vegetarian, vegan, Jain, and halal options. The lunch restaurants are selected for hygiene standards and proximity to the day's itinerary. Inform your guide of dietary requirements or allergies at booking so all restaurants can be briefed in advance." },
      { question: "What is the full 2-day itinerary for the Taj Mahal overnight tour?", answer: "**Day 1:** Depart Delhi hotel at 8:00–9:00 AM → drive to Agra (3–3.5 hours) → lunch in Agra → **Agra Fort** guided tour (1.5–2 hours) → **Taj Mahal** afternoon/sunset visit (2–2.5 hours) → optional Mehtab Bagh sunset viewpoint → hotel check-in → dinner. **Day 2:** Early morning **sunrise Taj Mahal** visit (2 hours) → return to hotel for breakfast → checkout → optional visit to **Itmad-ud-Daula (Baby Taj)** or local bazaars → lunch → depart Agra at 1:00–2:00 PM → arrive Delhi by 4:30–5:30 PM. The itinerary is flexible and can be customised to your interests." },
      { question: "What monuments besides the Taj Mahal are included in the overnight tour?", answer: "Beyond the Taj Mahal (visited twice — sunset and sunrise), the standard overnight itinerary includes: **Agra Fort** — the massive 94-acre UNESCO World Heritage Mughal fortress where Shah Jahan was imprisoned with a view of the Taj; **Itmad-ud-Daula** (Baby Taj) — the exquisite marble tomb often called the 'jewel box' and the first Mughal structure to use Pietra Dura marble inlay; and **Mehtab Bagh** — the Mughal garden directly across the Yamuna from the Taj Mahal offering the perfect rear-view reflection photograph. Optional additions include [Fatehpur Sikri](/india/agra/fatehpur-sikri-guided-tour) (37 km away) or the [Hidden Gems of Agra Heritage Tour](/india/agra/hidden-gems-of-agra-heritage-tour)." },
      { question: "Why should I choose the overnight tour instead of a same-day trip from Delhi?", answer: "The overnight tour is superior for four key reasons: (1) You see the Taj Mahal in **two lighting conditions** — sunset golden light and sunrise pink-gold glow — which same-day visitors cannot do; (2) The **sunrise visit** (Day 2) has the smallest crowds and best photography conditions of the entire day; (3) You have time for **additional monuments** (Agra Fort, Baby Taj, Mehtab Bagh) without rushing; and (4) The pace is relaxed rather than the 14-hour marathon of a same-day trip. The overnight format is especially recommended for photographers, honeymooners, and anyone who considers the Taj Mahal a once-in-a-lifetime experience worth experiencing properly." },
      { question: "What is the best season for the Taj Mahal overnight tour from Delhi?", answer: "The best season is **October through March** when temperatures are comfortable (**10–25 degrees Celsius**), skies are generally clear, and the Yamuna Expressway drive is pleasant. **November and February** offer the ideal balance of mild weather and clear visibility. **December–January** can have morning fog that occasionally obscures sunrise views but creates ethereal, atmospheric photographs. **April–June** is extremely hot (**40–47 degrees Celsius**) — the overnight format is still viable since you visit monuments in early morning and late afternoon, avoiding peak heat. The **monsoon season** (July–September) brings dramatic clouds that create stunning Taj Mahal backdrops but occasional rain. See our [Agra Travel Guide](/india/agra/agra-travel-guide-2026) for seasonal details." },
      { question: "Can the overnight tour be extended to include Fatehpur Sikri or Mathura?", answer: "Yes — both extensions are popular and highly recommended. **Fatehpur Sikri** (37 km from Agra, 45 minutes) adds approximately **2 hours** and is best visited on Day 2 morning before the return drive to Delhi. It is Emperor Akbar's magnificent abandoned capital city with the Buland Darwaza — the tallest gateway in the world at **54 metres**. **Mathura and Vrindavan** (55 km from Agra, 1 hour) add approximately **3–4 hours** and can be visited on Day 2 en route back to Delhi. Adding either extension converts the return to Delhi to a late-afternoon arrival instead of early afternoon. Both sites have separate entry fees (included if added to the package)." },
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'agra-mathura-full-day-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What do you see in Mathura on the Agra, Mathura, and Vrindavan day trip?", answer: "Mathura is the **birthplace of Lord Krishna** and one of Hinduism's seven sacred cities. Key sites include: **Krishna Janmabhoomi** — the temple complex built over the exact spot where Krishna was born, with an adjacent mosque creating one of India's most historically significant religious sites; **Dwarkadhish Temple** — a magnificent 19th-century temple with elaborate carvings; **Vishram Ghat** — the main bathing ghat on the Yamuna River where Krishna is believed to have rested after defeating the tyrant Kansa; and the **Mathura Museum** (optional) — housing one of India's finest collections of Kushan-period Buddhist and Hindu sculptures dating back **2,000 years**." },
      { question: "Which Krishna temples are visited in Vrindavan on this tour?", answer: "Vrindavan — the city where Lord Krishna spent his childhood — has over **5,000 temples**. This tour covers the most significant: (1) **Banke Bihari Temple** — Vrindavan's holiest shrine, famous for its unique curtain ceremony where the deity is repeatedly revealed and concealed; (2) **ISKCON Vrindavan** (Sri Krishna Balaram Mandir) — the stunning international Krishna consciousness temple welcoming to all visitors; (3) **Prem Mandir** — a modern white marble temple completed in 2012 with spectacular evening illuminations; and (4) **Govind Dev Temple** — a partially ruined 1590 Mughal-era temple showing Hindu-Mughal architectural fusion. Your guide explains the mythology and devotional significance at each site." },
      { question: "What is the distance from Agra to Mathura and how long is the drive?", answer: "Mathura is approximately **55 km from Agra** (1–1.5 hours by road via NH19). Vrindavan is a further **12 km from Mathura** (20 minutes). The full day trip route is: Agra → Taj Mahal → drive to Mathura (55 km, 1 hour) → drive to Vrindavan (12 km, 20 minutes) → return to Agra (70 km, 1.5 hours). Total driving distance for the day is approximately **190 km**. If starting from Delhi, add **150 km each way** for the Delhi–Agra segment. All driving is in a private air-conditioned vehicle with an experienced driver familiar with the route." },
      { question: "How long is the full-day Agra, Mathura, and Vrindavan tour?", answer: "The full-day tour runs approximately **12 to 14 hours** depending on your starting point. From Agra: depart at **6:00 AM** for sunrise Taj Mahal → complete Taj Mahal by 8:30 AM → drive to Mathura (arrive 10:00 AM) → Mathura temples 2 hours → drive to Vrindavan → Vrindavan temples 2.5 hours → lunch → return to Agra by **5:00–6:00 PM**. From Delhi: add 3.5 hours each way for the drive, making it a **16-hour** day with departure at 5:00 AM and return by 9:00 PM. The Agra-based itinerary is more comfortable and less rushed." },
      { question: "Is the Agra, Mathura, and Vrindavan tour too rushed to enjoy properly?", answer: "The tour covers a lot of ground but is **well-paced when starting from Agra**. The Taj Mahal visit (2–2.5 hours) is comprehensive and unhurried. Mathura receives 1.5–2 hours (sufficient for the key temples and ghats), and Vrindavan receives 2–2.5 hours (covering the four major temples). Lunch provides a natural rest break. The guide manages transitions efficiently so you spend time at sites rather than in transit. If starting from **Delhi**, the tour is more demanding due to 7 hours of total driving — consider our [Taj Mahal & Agra Overnight Tour](/india/agra/taj-mahal-agra-overnight-tour-from-delhi) to split the experience across two days." },
      { question: "Is the guide knowledgeable about all three cities — Agra, Mathura, and Vrindavan?", answer: "Yes — your guide is a **Ministry of Tourism-licensed professional** with expertise in both Mughal history (for the Taj Mahal and Agra) and Hindu pilgrimage traditions (for Mathura and Vrindavan). The Agra–Mathura–Vrindavan corridor represents one continuous cultural landscape along the Yamuna River, and your guide connects these sites into a coherent narrative spanning **Mughal royal architecture** and **Hindu devotional heritage**. The guide explains Krishna mythology in an accessible way for international visitors regardless of religious background, making the temple visits culturally enriching rather than confusing." },
      { question: "What type of vehicle is used for the Agra, Mathura, and Vrindavan day trip?", answer: "A **private air-conditioned vehicle** is assigned exclusively to your group for the full day. Vehicle types include: **Toyota Innova Crysta** (6-seat SUV) for groups of 3–5, **sedan** for couples or solo travellers, or a **tempo traveller** (12-seat minibus) for larger groups. The vehicle stays with you throughout and serves as a mobile base — essential for a multi-city day trip with **190 km of driving**. USB charging, bottled water, and Wi-Fi are available. The driver is experienced with Mathura and Vrindavan's narrow temple-district roads, which can be challenging for unfamiliar drivers." },
      { question: "Are entry tickets included for all monuments and temples?", answer: "**Taj Mahal entry tickets** are fully included (₹1,300 + ₹200 mausoleum fee for foreign nationals). Most temples in Mathura and Vrindavan are **free to enter** — Hindu temples generally do not charge admission fees. The **Krishna Janmabhoomi complex** in Mathura has a nominal entry fee of **₹25–50** which is included. Photography restrictions apply at certain temples (Banke Bihari Temple prohibits photography inside the sanctum). Your guide briefs you on specific rules before each temple. The only additional costs are optional donations (prasad offerings) at temples, which are entirely voluntary." },
      { question: "What is the best season to visit Agra, Mathura, and Vrindavan?", answer: "The best season is **October to March** when temperatures are comfortable (**12–28 degrees Celsius**). The most spectacular time to visit Mathura and Vrindavan is during **Holi** (March) — the festival of colours originated in this region and celebrations here are the most intense and famous in all of India. **Janmashtami** (August/September) — Lord Krishna's birthday — transforms Mathura and Vrindavan into an extraordinary celebration with midnight ceremonies and millions of devotees. For comfortable sightseeing without festival crowds, **November to February** is ideal. Avoid **April to June** when temperatures exceed **45 degrees Celsius**." },
      { question: "What is the spiritual significance of Mathura and Vrindavan?", answer: "Mathura and Vrindavan together form the sacred **Braj Bhoomi** region — the most important pilgrimage area in Vaishnavism (devotion to Lord Vishnu through his avatar Krishna). Mathura is where **Krishna was born** in a prison cell (his parents were imprisoned by the tyrant King Kansa), and Vrindavan is where he spent his **childhood and youth**, playing his flute, tending cows, and enacting the divine love play (Raas Leela) with Radha and the gopis. This region attracts over **15 million pilgrims annually**. Combining these sacred sites with the Taj Mahal creates an extraordinary day contrasting Mughal expressions of romantic love with Hindu celebrations of divine love." },
      { question: "Can this tour be combined with an Agra Fort visit?", answer: "Yes — **Agra Fort** can be added to the morning itinerary before departing for Mathura. The recommended sequence is: sunrise Taj Mahal (6:00–8:30 AM) → Agra Fort (9:00–10:30 AM) → drive to Mathura → Mathura and Vrindavan → return. Adding Agra Fort extends the tour by approximately **1.5 hours** but creates the most comprehensive single-day experience of the region. For a focused Taj Mahal and Agra Fort experience without the Mathura extension, see our [Taj Mahal & Agra Fort Guided Tour](/india/agra/taj-mahal-agra-fort-guided-tour). The combined itinerary is best suited for energetic travellers comfortable with a full 14-hour day." },
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'agra-fort-private-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What is the drive time from Delhi to Agra and then to Fatehpur Sikri?", answer: "The drive from Delhi to Agra takes approximately **3 to 3.5 hours** (200 km via the Yamuna Expressway). From Agra to Fatehpur Sikri is an additional **45 minutes to 1 hour** (37 km via NH21). The total round-trip driving distance for the day is approximately **500 km**: Delhi → Agra (200 km) → Fatehpur Sikri (37 km) → Delhi (237 km, returning via the expressway). Departure from Delhi is at **5:30–6:00 AM** to maximise sightseeing time, with return to Delhi by **7:00–8:00 PM**. All driving is in a private air-conditioned vehicle with an experienced driver." },
      { question: "What is Fatehpur Sikri and why should I visit it?", answer: "Fatehpur Sikri is a **UNESCO World Heritage Site** — a magnificent Mughal city built by Emperor Akbar in 1571 as his new imperial capital. Constructed entirely from red sandstone, it represents the pinnacle of Mughal architectural innovation, blending Hindu, Islamic, and Jain design elements reflecting Akbar's famous religious tolerance. The city was **abandoned after just 14 years** (1585) due to acute water scarcity, which paradoxically preserved it in near-perfect condition — making it one of the best-preserved 16th-century cities in the world. It is often called India's **ghost city** and is considered by many architectural historians to be more architecturally interesting than the Taj Mahal itself." },
      { question: "What is the Buland Darwaza and can I see it on this tour?", answer: "The **Buland Darwaza** (Gate of Magnificence) is the main entrance to Fatehpur Sikri's Jama Masjid and is the **tallest gateway in the world at 54 metres** (177 feet). Built by Akbar in 1601 to commemorate his military victory in Gujarat, it is constructed from red and buff sandstone with marble decorations and inscriptions. Climbing the **42 steps** to the gateway is one of the most dramatic architectural experiences in India — the sheer scale overwhelms visitors as they approach. Yes, the Buland Darwaza is a highlight of this tour. Your guide explains the inscriptions, including Akbar's famous words about the transience of the world carved above the entrance." },
      { question: "Why was Fatehpur Sikri abandoned and is it really a ghost city?", answer: "Emperor Akbar built Fatehpur Sikri as his imperial capital in 1571, choosing the location because a Sufi saint (Sheikh Salim Chishti) had correctly predicted the birth of Akbar's heir at this spot. After **14 years of occupation** (1571–1585), the city was abandoned — the most widely accepted reason being **chronic water shortage** from the area's inadequate water table. Other theories include strategic military concerns and disease outbreaks. Today, the term 'ghost city' is apt: the palaces, courtyards, and administrative buildings stand intact but **completely uninhabited**, preserved in time. Walking through the empty halls with your guide narrating the vibrant court life that once filled them is a haunting experience." },
      { question: "How long do you spend at each monument on the same-day Delhi tour?", answer: "Time allocation across the day: **Taj Mahal — 2 to 2.5 hours** (complete guided tour including interior mausoleum), **Agra Fort — 1.5 hours** (key highlights including Diwan-i-Am, Sheesh Mahal, and the Musamman Burj with its Taj view), and **Fatehpur Sikri — 1.5 to 2 hours** (Buland Darwaza, Jama Masjid, Panch Mahal, Diwan-i-Khas, and Sheikh Salim Chishti's tomb). Lunch takes approximately **45 minutes to 1 hour**. Driving accounts for approximately **5 hours** across the full day. The pace is structured but not rushed — each monument receives quality guided time." },
      { question: "Is a licensed guide included for all three monuments?", answer: "Yes — a **Ministry of Tourism-licensed professional guide** accompanies you throughout the entire day, covering all three monuments: the Taj Mahal, Agra Fort, and Fatehpur Sikri. Having one guide for all three sites is invaluable because the guide weaves a **continuous Mughal narrative** — the Taj Mahal (Shah Jahan's tribute to love), Agra Fort (the seat of Mughal power), and Fatehpur Sikri (Akbar's visionary capital) together span three generations of the same dynasty. The guide is certified for all three ASI-protected monuments. For a focused Fatehpur Sikri experience, see our dedicated [Fatehpur Sikri Guided Tour](/india/agra/fatehpur-sikri-guided-tour)." },
      { question: "Is lunch included in the same-day Delhi to Agra and Fatehpur Sikri tour?", answer: "Yes — a **sit-down lunch** at a quality restaurant is included, typically served between the Agra Fort visit and the drive to Fatehpur Sikri (approximately **1:00–2:00 PM**). The restaurant serves North Indian, Mughlai, and continental cuisine with vegetarian, vegan, Jain, and halal options. Agra is famous for its Mughlai cuisine — dishes like **petha** (Agra's signature sweet), **dal moth**, and **Mughlai biryani** originated here. Bottled water is available in the vehicle throughout the day. Inform your guide of dietary requirements at booking so the restaurant can prepare accordingly." },
      { question: "What time does the tour return to Delhi?", answer: "The tour typically departs Fatehpur Sikri at approximately **4:00–4:30 PM** and arrives back in Delhi by **7:00–8:00 PM** depending on traffic conditions on the Yamuna Expressway. The return drive from Fatehpur Sikri to Delhi is approximately **237 km** (3–3.5 hours). If you have an evening flight from Delhi, inform us at booking — the itinerary can be adjusted to ensure airport drop-off by a specific time. For late-evening flights (after 10:00 PM), the standard timing works comfortably. For earlier flights, the Fatehpur Sikri visit may be shortened or the lunch break adjusted." },
      { question: "What are the entry fees for the Taj Mahal, Agra Fort, and Fatehpur Sikri?", answer: "All entry fees are **included in the tour price**. Individual ticket costs for foreign nationals: **Taj Mahal — ₹1,300** (main complex) + **₹200** (inner mausoleum); **Agra Fort — ₹650**; **Fatehpur Sikri — ₹610**. The combined ticket value is approximately **₹2,760 per foreign national**. Indian nationals pay significantly less (₹50, ₹35, and ₹40 respectively). Children under 15 enter all three ASI monuments for free. Your guide pre-purchases or purchases tickets on arrival at each site, handling all logistics so you avoid queues and proceed directly through the entry gates." },
      { question: "Is Fatehpur Sikri worth adding to a same-day Agra tour from Delhi?", answer: "Absolutely — Fatehpur Sikri is one of India's most **underrated UNESCO World Heritage Sites** and is strongly recommended for anyone visiting Agra. While the Taj Mahal receives 7–8 million visitors annually, Fatehpur Sikri sees a fraction of that — meaning you explore a perfectly preserved Mughal city with **far fewer crowds**. The architecture is arguably more diverse and innovative than Agra Fort, and the 'ghost city' atmosphere is unlike anything else in India. Adding Fatehpur Sikri extends the day by approximately **3 hours** (including driving and visit time) but enriches the experience exponentially. For a complete [Agra sightseeing guide](/india/agra/things-to-do-in-agra), see our resource page." },
      { question: "What should I wear and bring for the same-day Taj Mahal and Fatehpur Sikri tour?", answer: "Wear **comfortable, breathable cotton clothing** and sturdy walking shoes that are easy to remove (shoes are removed at the Taj Mahal marble platform and at the mosque and tomb areas of Fatehpur Sikri). Modest dress is recommended — cover shoulders, avoid very short shorts. Bring **sunscreen and a hat** (the Taj Mahal marble terrace and Fatehpur Sikri's open courtyards have minimal shade). A light scarf is useful for women as a respectful head covering in mosque areas. The vehicle provides air-conditioned rest between sites. Carry a small daypack for essentials — large bags are restricted at the Taj Mahal security check." },
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-express-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What are the Gatimaan Express train details for the Delhi to Agra tour?", answer: "The **Gatimaan Express** is India's fastest operational train, running at speeds up to **160 km/h** on the Delhi–Agra route. It departs from **Hazrat Nizamuddin Railway Station** in South Delhi at approximately **8:10 AM** and arrives at **Agra Cantt Railway Station** at approximately **9:50 AM** — a journey time of just **1 hour 40 minutes** covering 188 km. The return train departs Agra Cantt at approximately **5:50 PM** and arrives back at Hazrat Nizamuddin by **7:30 PM**. The train operates daily **except Fridays** (when the Taj Mahal is closed), making it perfectly aligned for Taj Mahal day trips." },
      { question: "Are confirmed (CNF) train tickets guaranteed on this tour?", answer: "Yes — your Gatimaan Express tickets are **confirmed (CNF) reserved seats** in the Executive Chair Car (CC class), which is the premium class with airline-style reclining seats, individual reading lights, and charging points. Tickets are pre-booked by us when you confirm the tour, ensuring guaranteed confirmed seats. The Gatimaan Express is extremely popular and **sells out weeks in advance** — independent travellers often struggle to secure confirmed tickets. By booking this tour, your seats are secured from our advance allocation. You receive your ticket details (PNR number and seat assignment) **48 hours before departure**." },
      { question: "Which railway station does the Gatimaan Express depart from in Delhi?", answer: "The Gatimaan Express departs from **Hazrat Nizamuddin Railway Station**, located in South Delhi — approximately **15 km from Connaught Place** and **12 km from Delhi's major hotel districts** (Karol Bagh, Paharganj, Chanakyapuri). The station is well-connected by metro (Hazrat Nizamuddin metro station, Violet Line) and is a 25–40 minute drive from most Delhi hotels depending on traffic. Your tour includes **hotel pickup** at approximately **6:30–7:00 AM** to ensure comfortable arrival at the station 30–40 minutes before departure. The station is much smaller and less chaotic than New Delhi Railway Station, making it more comfortable for first-time visitors." },
      { question: "Is breakfast served on the Gatimaan Express train?", answer: "Yes — a **complimentary hot breakfast** is served onboard the Gatimaan Express in Executive Chair Car class. The meal is served by catering staff approximately 20 minutes after departure and includes a choice of vegetarian or non-vegetarian options: typically an omelette or poha (flattened rice) with toast, butter, jam, a hot beverage (tea or coffee), and juice. The food quality is above average for Indian railway catering. The breakfast service, combined with the comfortable airline-style seating and the **landscape views of the Yamuna river valley** as the train speeds through rural Uttar Pradesh, makes the 1 hour 40 minute journey an experience in itself." },
      { question: "Is a guide waiting at Agra station when the Gatimaan Express arrives?", answer: "Yes — your **Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide** meets you on the platform at **Agra Cantt Railway Station** the moment the Gatimaan Express arrives at 9:50 AM. The guide holds a signboard with your name for easy identification. From the platform, you proceed directly to the waiting **private air-conditioned vehicle** parked outside the station — the transfer to the Taj Mahal South Gate takes approximately **15 minutes**. This seamless station-to-monument transition is a key advantage of the guided tour — no haggling with auto-rickshaws or navigating Agra's confusing streets independently." },
      { question: "How long do I get to spend at the Taj Mahal on the Gatimaan Express tour?", answer: "You get approximately **2 to 2.5 hours** at the Taj Mahal — more than sufficient for a comprehensive guided visit covering the complete complex: the Great Gate, the charbagh garden, the main mausoleum exterior and interior (including the cenotaphs of Shah Jahan and Mumtaz Mahal), the flanking mosque, and all key photography viewpoints. The guided tour ensures you spend time efficiently at the most significant points rather than wandering. Your guide manages the security entry process to minimize wait time. If you prefer a longer, more leisurely Taj visit, consider our [Taj Mahal Sunrise Tour](/india/agra/taj-mahal-sunrise-tour) which starts earlier and allows 3+ hours." },
      { question: "Is Agra Fort included in the Gatimaan Express same-day tour?", answer: "Yes — the standard Gatimaan Express tour itinerary includes both the **Taj Mahal** (approximately 10:15 AM – 12:30 PM) and **Agra Fort** (approximately 1:30 PM – 3:00 PM), with a sit-down lunch in between. Agra Fort is a **UNESCO World Heritage Site** located just 2.5 km from the Taj Mahal and is essential for completing the Shah Jahan narrative — it is where the emperor was imprisoned by his son Aurangzeb and spent his final 8 years gazing at the Taj Mahal through a window. The combined Taj + Fort itinerary fits comfortably within the Gatimaan Express schedule, with time to spare before the return train." },
      { question: "What time does the return Gatimaan Express train depart from Agra?", answer: "The return Gatimaan Express departs **Agra Cantt Railway Station at approximately 5:50 PM**, arriving back at Hazrat Nizamuddin Railway Station in Delhi by **7:30 PM**. This schedule provides approximately **7.5 hours in Agra** (9:50 AM arrival to 5:30 PM station departure), which is ample time for the Taj Mahal, Agra Fort, lunch, and even an optional quick visit to **Mehtab Bagh** or a local marble inlay workshop. Your guide and driver ensure you arrive at Agra Cantt station **20–30 minutes before departure** so there is no last-minute rush. An evening snack or meal is served onboard the return train." },
      { question: "What is included in the Gatimaan Express tour price?", answer: "The tour price includes: **Gatimaan Express confirmed tickets** (Executive Chair Car, both directions), **hotel pickup and drop-off** in Delhi (to and from Hazrat Nizamuddin station), **private air-conditioned vehicle** in Agra for the full day, **Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide** for the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort, **all entry tickets** (Taj Mahal ₹1,300 + ₹200 mausoleum, Agra Fort ₹650), **breakfast on the train**, and a **sit-down lunch** at a quality Agra restaurant. The total included value of tickets alone is over **₹4,000 per person** (train + monuments). Tips for your guide and driver are optional but appreciated (recommended ₹300–500 per person)." },
      { question: "Is the Gatimaan Express tour better than driving from Delhi to Agra?", answer: "Both options have advantages. The **Gatimaan Express** is faster (1 hour 40 minutes vs. 3–3.5 hours driving), more comfortable (airline-style seating, no road bumps), and provides a unique Indian railway experience with onboard meals. However, driving offers **more flexibility** — earlier departure enables sunrise visits, and there is no fixed return time. The train is ideal for travellers who want a comfortable, structured day with guaranteed timings. Driving is better for photographers wanting [sunrise access](/india/agra/taj-mahal-sunrise-tour) or travellers wanting to add [Fatehpur Sikri](/india/agra/fatehpur-sikri-guided-tour) (which the train schedule does not easily accommodate). For most first-time visitors, the Gatimaan Express provides the best overall experience." },
      { question: "What happens if the Gatimaan Express is delayed or cancelled?", answer: "The Gatimaan Express has an excellent **on-time performance record** of approximately 90–95%, as it is India's premium showcase train and receives priority scheduling. In the rare event of a significant delay (over 1 hour), your guide and driver in Agra adjust the itinerary accordingly — the private vehicle provides full flexibility to compress or extend visits as needed. If the train is cancelled entirely (extremely rare — typically only during severe fog events in December–January), we arrange a **private car transfer** from Delhi to Agra at no additional charge, ensuring your day proceeds as planned. Full refund policies apply for cancellations we cannot accommodate." },
    ];
  }

  // --- END AGRA TOUR FAQS (ALL 23 COMPLETE) ---

  // --- DELHI TOUR FAQS BATCH 1 ---

  if (slug === 'delhi-full-day-guided-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What does the Delhi full-day guided tour cover?", answer: "The Delhi full-day guided tour covers the city's highlights across both Old Delhi and New Delhi in a single day: **Old Delhi** — Jama Masjid (India's largest mosque), Red Fort (UNESCO World Heritage Mughal fortress), Chandni Chowk (the iconic 17th-century bazaar), and a cycle-rickshaw ride through the old city lanes. **New Delhi** — India Gate (the 1931 war memorial), the Presidential Palace and Parliament (exterior), Humayun's Tomb (UNESCO Heritage, the architectural predecessor to the Taj Mahal), Qutub Minar (UNESCO Heritage, 12th-century Islamic tower), and Lotus Temple (Bahá'í house of worship, 20th century). The tour provides a chronological sweep of Delhi's 3,000+ year history from the early Islamic sultanate through the Mughal era to the British Raj and independent India." },
      { question: "How long is the Delhi full-day guided tour?", answer: "The full-day guided tour runs approximately **10–11 hours** from hotel pickup (typically 8:30–9:00 AM) to hotel drop-off (approximately 7:00–8:00 PM). The tour covers 7–8 sites across the city, with a sit-down lunch included at approximately 1:00–2:00 PM. Delhi is a large city and travel time between sites adds up — having a private vehicle and guide eliminates the stress of navigation and public transport. The day is designed to be comprehensive without being rushed — each site receives 30–90 minutes of quality time depending on its significance and size." },
      { question: "Is a licensed guide included in the Delhi full-day tour?", answer: "Yes — a Ministry of Tourism-licensed professional guide accompanies you throughout the day. Delhi's history is extraordinarily complex — 3,000 years, 8 successive cities built on the same site, ruled by the Delhi Sultanate, the Mughals, the British, and independent India. Without a guide, the connections between sites, the chronological narrative, and the significance of architectural details are largely inaccessible. Your guide provides context that transforms a visit to Humayun's Tomb from 'interesting building' to 'the architectural prototype that directly inspired the Taj Mahal, built 90 years later.' This narrative connects the sites into a coherent, fascinating story of one of the world's great cities." },
      { question: "What is the best way to see both Old Delhi and New Delhi in one day?", answer: "The strategic approach to seeing both Old and New Delhi in a day: **Start in Old Delhi** in the morning (before midday heat) when Chandni Chowk and Jama Masjid are at their most energetic. The Red Fort exterior, the cycle-rickshaw ride through the old city lanes, and the street food observation are all best in the cooler morning. **Move to New Delhi in the afternoon**: Humayun's Tomb (best in mid-afternoon light), Qutub Minar (good afternoon light for photography), and India Gate at sunset (magnificent). This east-west sequence also follows a logical geographic route that minimizes backtracking across Delhi's notorious traffic." },
      { question: "What type of vehicle is used for the Delhi full-day tour?", answer: "A private air-conditioned vehicle is used throughout the day — typically a Toyota Innova (6-seat SUV) for groups up to 5–6, or a sedan for couples/solo travellers. The vehicle stays with your group for the entire day, serving as a mobile base between sites and providing air-conditioned respite from Delhi's heat and pollution. The driver is experienced with Delhi's complex traffic patterns and monument parking areas. USB charging and Wi-Fi are available. For groups of 7+, a larger tempo traveller is arranged. The private vehicle is the most practical way to navigate Delhi efficiently given the distances between major sites." },
      { question: "Is the Chandni Chowk bazaar walk included in the full-day Delhi tour?", answer: "Yes — the Chandni Chowk bazaar walk is one of the highlights of the Old Delhi section. Your guide leads you through the historic 17th-century market lanes, explaining the original Mughal bazaar layout designed by Shah Jahan's daughter Jahanara Begum, pointing out the specialized trade lanes (spice market, silver market, wedding market), and introducing you to the extraordinary street food culture of Old Delhi. The cycle-rickshaw ride through the narrow lanes provides a protected vantage point for observing the sensory chaos of one of Asia's oldest and most atmospheric urban markets. This section is best experienced in the company of a local guide who can navigate and explain simultaneously." },
      { question: "Which UNESCO World Heritage Sites are on the Delhi full-day tour?", answer: "The Delhi full-day tour includes three UNESCO World Heritage Sites: (1) **Red Fort** — the 17th-century Mughal sandstone and marble palace fortress built by Shah Jahan as the seat of the Mughal Empire; (2) **Humayun's Tomb** — the 1570 Persian garden tomb that served as the direct architectural model for the Taj Mahal (same red sandstone and white marble combination, same charbagh garden layout, built 61 years earlier); and (3) **Qutub Minar** — the 12th-century 73-metre tall minaret, the tallest brick minaret in the world, built by the Delhi Sultanate and representing the earliest Islamic architectural monument in India. Visiting all three in a single day with a guide who explains their chronological and architectural connections is extraordinary." },
      { question: "Is lunch included in the Delhi full-day guided tour?", answer: "Yes — a sit-down lunch is included at a quality Delhi restaurant between the Old Delhi and New Delhi sections (typically around 1:00–2:00 PM). The restaurant serves a broad selection of North Indian, Mughlai, and continental dishes, with comprehensive vegetarian, vegan, Jain, halal, and allergen-aware options. Many Delhi food enthusiasts consider a quality North Indian lunch in Old Delhi — featuring dishes that originated in Mughal royal kitchens (butter chicken, seekh kebab, nihari, biryani) — to be as much of a highlight as the monuments. Inform your guide of dietary requirements at booking." },
      { question: "What time should I be ready for hotel pickup on the Delhi full-day tour?", answer: "Hotel pickup is at **8:30–9:00 AM** for most Delhi hotels. Starting mid-morning allows you to avoid the worst morning rush hour traffic in Delhi while still completing Old Delhi before peak midday heat. For visitors who specifically want to experience the morning energy of Chandni Chowk's wholesale traders (most active before 9 AM), an earlier pickup at 7:30 AM can be arranged. The tour concludes at approximately 7:00–8:00 PM depending on pace. If you have a late-evening flight, the tour can be scheduled and timed to end at the airport rather than your hotel." },
      { question: "Is the Delhi full-day tour suitable for first-time visitors to India?", answer: "The Delhi full-day guided tour is specifically optimized for first-time India visitors. Delhi can be overwhelming independently — the traffic, the navigation between distant sites, the complexity of entry ticketing, and the density of touts and rickshaw drivers outside monument gates. A private guide and vehicle create a managed, stress-free framework that lets you absorb and enjoy the city rather than spending mental energy on logistics. Your guide briefs you before each site on what to expect, what to watch for, and how to interact with locals respectfully. By the end of the day, first-time visitors typically feel significantly more comfortable with India and ready for the rest of their trip." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'golden-triangle-3-day-tour-from-delhi') {
    return [
      { question: "What is the Golden Triangle and why is it India's most popular circuit?", answer: "The Golden Triangle is India's most famous tourist circuit connecting three cities in a triangle shape on the map: **Delhi** (the capital, 3,000 years of history), **Agra** (home of the Taj Mahal), and **Jaipur** (the 'Pink City' of Rajasthan). The three cities lie approximately 200 km apart from each other, making the circuit feasible in 3 days. Together, they represent the greatest concentration of UNESCO World Heritage Sites and iconic travel experiences in India: Red Fort, Humayun's Tomb, Qutub Minar (Delhi), the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort (Agra), and Amber Fort, City Palace, Jantar Mantar (Jaipur). The circuit is India's most visited travel route for first-time visitors — a logical, efficient overview of the country's greatest historical sites." },
      { question: "What is the day-by-day itinerary for the 3-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "**Day 1 — Delhi:** Old Delhi (Jama Masjid, Chandni Chowk, Red Fort exterior, cycle-rickshaw), New Delhi (India Gate, Humayun's Tomb, Qutub Minar). Drive to Agra in the evening (3.5 hours). **Day 2 — Agra:** Taj Mahal at sunrise (full guided visit), Agra Fort, optional Mehtab Bagh or Itmad-ud-Daula. Drive to Jaipur in the afternoon (5 hours via Fatehpur Sikri optional stop). **Day 3 — Jaipur:** Amber Fort (elephant ride optional), City Palace, Jantar Mantar (astronomical observatory), Hawa Mahal (Palace of Winds). Drop-off in Jaipur (or return to Delhi, 5 hours). All sites, entries, meals, and hotel nights are included." },
      { question: "What is included in the 3-day Golden Triangle tour from Delhi?", answer: "Included: all transportation between Delhi, Agra, and Jaipur in a private air-conditioned vehicle, 2 nights hotel accommodation (1 night Agra, 1 night Jaipur — 3-star standard, upgrades to 4-star or 5-star available), Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide throughout all 3 days, all entry tickets (Red Fort, Humayun's Tomb, Qutub Minar, Taj Mahal + inner mausoleum, Agra Fort, Amber Fort, City Palace, Jantar Mantar), and all daily breakfasts. Lunches and dinners can be included on request. The tour is fully private — no shared groups or fixed coaches." },
      { question: "Is the 3-day Golden Triangle tour suitable for first-time visitors to India?", answer: "The 3-day Golden Triangle tour is India's most popular first-time visitor itinerary for excellent reasons: it efficiently covers the country's three most iconic cities, includes India's most famous monument (Taj Mahal), and provides a complete historical sweep from the 12th-century Delhi Sultanate through the Mughal Empire to the Rajputana kingdoms of Jaipur — all in just 3 days. The private format with a dedicated guide removes all logistical complexity, allowing first-time visitors to fully absorb and enjoy India without navigation stress. Most first-time India visitors regard this tour as one of the best decisions of their trip." },
      { question: "What is the best time of year for the Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "**October to March** is the ideal season for the Golden Triangle circuit. October–November is fresh after monsoon with lush green surroundings. December–February is the most popular period: cool days (18–28°C), clear skies, and comfortable for extensive outdoor sightseeing. January can bring morning fog in Agra and Delhi — atmospheric for photography. **March–May** is increasingly hot but still manageable with early starts. **June–September** (monsoon and peak summer) is not recommended for extended outdoor monument sightseeing — heat (40–46°C) and humidity make it uncomfortable. The Golden Triangle can be done year-round; October–March is simply when conditions are most pleasant." },
      { question: "Can the 3-day Golden Triangle tour be extended to 4, 5, or 6 days?", answer: "Yes — the Golden Triangle is frequently extended into longer tours for more comprehensive coverage: **4 days** adds Fatehpur Sikri (Akbar's abandoned city, en route from Agra to Jaipur) and more time in each city. **5 days** adds Ranthambore National Park (tiger safari, between Agra and Jaipur) or Pushkar (sacred Hindu city near Jaipur). **6 days** adds Jodhpur or Udaipur (Rajasthan's most beautiful cities). **8–14 days** covers the full Rajasthan circuit. Our [5-day Golden Triangle tour from Delhi](/india/delhi/5-days-golden-triangle-tour-from-delhi) and [6-day Golden Triangle tour](/india/delhi/6-days-golden-triangle-tour-from-delhi) are the most popular extensions." },
      { question: "What hotel standard is included in the 3-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "The standard tour includes comfortable 3-star hotels in Agra and Jaipur — well-located, clean, and reliable. The Agra hotel is typically in the Taj Ganj area with Taj Mahal views, and the Jaipur hotel is within the old city or nearby for convenient access to all sites. Upgrades to 4-star (heritage havelis, business hotels) or 5-star (Oberoi Amarvilas Agra, Taj Hotels, ITC Rajputana Jaipur) are available at adjusted pricing and are highly recommended for a luxury experience. Heritage properties in Jaipur — restored Rajput havelis converted to boutique hotels — add significantly to the cultural experience." },
      { question: "Is there a guide for the entire 3-day Golden Triangle, or does it change each city?", answer: "For most 3-day Golden Triangle tours, there is **one guide for Delhi and Agra** (typically a Delhi-Agra specialist) and **a second guide in Jaipur** (a Jaipur specialist, since local expertise matters significantly in each city). Some luxury tours arrange a single senior guide for all three days. The driver typically remains the same throughout (Delhi–Agra–Jaipur–Delhi) for continuity. Both guides are Ministry of Tourism-certified. If you prefer a single guide for all three days, this can be arranged at a premium." },
      { question: "Can I start the Golden Triangle from Jaipur or Agra instead of Delhi?", answer: "Yes — the Golden Triangle can start from any of the three cities. If you are flying into Jaipur or arriving in India at Agra (some itineraries transit from Nepal or Mumbai), the circuit works equally well in any direction: Jaipur → Agra → Delhi, or Agra → Delhi → Jaipur. The most common starting point is Delhi (the main international gateway), but the logistics are identical regardless of direction. The tour ends with a drop-off at the city of your choice — Delhi airport, Jaipur airport, or Agra railway station, depending on your onward travel plans." },
      { question: "What are the distances between Delhi, Agra, and Jaipur?", answer: "**Delhi to Agra:** 200 km via Yamuna Expressway, approximately 3–3.5 hours. **Agra to Jaipur:** 240 km via NH21, approximately 4.5–5 hours (passing through or stopping at Fatehpur Sikri, 40 km from Agra). **Jaipur to Delhi:** 270 km via NH48, approximately 5 hours. Total Golden Triangle circuit distance: approximately 710 km. All roads are national highways — smooth, well-maintained, and driven in comfortable air-conditioned vehicles. The longest single day of driving is the Agra-to-Jaipur leg; departing after the Agra Fort morning visit (around 1–2 PM) arrives in Jaipur by evening in time for dinner." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'delhi-to-agra-overnight-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What does the Delhi to Agra overnight tour include?", answer: "The Delhi to Agra overnight tour is a 2-day, 1-night package that provides: Day 1 — Delhi hotel pickup, drive to Agra (3.5 hours), afternoon visit to [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort) or Mehtab Bagh, 1 night at a quality Agra hotel; Day 2 — **Taj Mahal at sunrise** (the primary reason for an overnight stay in Agra), [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort) if not visited on Day 1, optional additional sites (Itmad-ud-Daula, Mehtab Bagh), drive back to Delhi. Included: private air-conditioned vehicle for both days, Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide, 1 night hotel in Agra, all entry tickets, and breakfasts. The overnight format allows the sunrise Taj Mahal visit that is impossible on a same-day Delhi tour without an extremely early 4 AM departure." },
      { question: "Why choose an overnight tour over a same-day Delhi-Agra trip?", answer: "An overnight stay in Agra makes a fundamental difference to the quality of your Taj Mahal experience. Same-day visitors from Delhi arrive at the Taj Mahal around 9–10 AM — by which time hundreds of tour groups are already inside. Overnight visitors can be at the Taj Mahal gate precisely at opening time (5:30–6:00 AM) for the sunrise experience — the most beautiful and least crowded time of day. Additionally, an overnight stay allows you to see the Taj Mahal in **two different lights**: if you arrive in Agra by late afternoon on Day 1, you can make a brief evening visit (watching the amber light on the marble at sunset), and then the full sunrise visit on Day 2. No same-day trip can replicate this." },
      { question: "What hotel is used in Agra for the overnight tour?", answer: "The standard overnight tour includes a 3-star hotel in Agra's Taj Ganj area (the historic neighborhood immediately south of the Taj Mahal) — ideally with a rooftop terrace that offers direct views of the white marble dome. Several well-regarded mid-range properties in this area provide exactly this, and watching the Taj Mahal change colour across an Agra evening from your hotel rooftop is a genuinely special experience at no extra cost. Upgrades to 4-star or **5-star** are available — the **Oberoi Amarvilas** (rated one of the world's best hotels, every room with direct Taj Mahal views) is the ultimate choice for a luxury overnight experience." },
      { question: "Can I visit the Taj Mahal in the evening on Day 1 and again at sunrise on Day 2?", answer: "Yes — visiting the Taj Mahal twice (evening and sunrise) is one of the great advantages of the overnight format. The evening visit (typically 4:00–5:30 PM, as the monument closes 30 minutes before sunset) offers golden afternoon light on the marble and smaller crowds than midday. A separate entry ticket is required for the second visit (your guide manages this). The sunrise visit the next morning then provides the soft gold dawn light and near-empty grounds. Experiencing the Taj Mahal in two different lighting conditions — warm amber evening light and soft golden sunrise — doubles the value of the visit and provides photographic perspectives that no single-visit day trip can match." },
      { question: "What is visited in Agra beyond the Taj Mahal on the overnight tour?", answer: "The overnight Agra itinerary typically covers: **Day 1 afternoon** — [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort) (if arriving by 3:00 PM; the fort closes at sunset) or an exploratory walk through the Taj Ganj bazaar area; evening rooftop at hotel overlooking the Taj Mahal. **Day 2 morning** — Taj Mahal at sunrise (2–2.5 hours), followed by Mehtab Bagh (rear-view Taj photography), Itmad-ud-Daula (Baby Taj, 1 hour), and optionally a visit to a marble inlay craft workshop to see living Pietra Dura craftsmen at work. The 2-day format allows comprehensive Agra coverage without rushing — every visitor who has done a same-day Agra trip wishes they had stayed overnight." },
      { question: "How long is the drive from Delhi to Agra?", answer: "The drive from Delhi to Agra takes **3 to 3.5 hours** via the Yamuna Expressway (165 km) — a smooth, modern 6-lane divided highway. Departure from Delhi is typically at 12:00–2:00 PM to arrive in Agra by 3:30–5:30 PM (allowing afternoon monument visits and/or hotel check-in before evening). The return drive on Day 2 departs Agra at approximately 12:00–1:00 PM after the morning sightseeing, arriving in Delhi by 4:00–5:00 PM. Total round-trip driving is approximately 7 hours over 2 days — comfortable in an air-conditioned private vehicle." },
      { question: "Is breakfast included in the overnight Agra tour?", answer: "Yes — breakfast is included at your Agra hotel on Day 2. Most Agra hotels offer a buffet breakfast (Indian and continental options) or a la carte service. Given the early 5:00 AM departure for the sunrise Taj Mahal visit, breakfast is typically served after the monument visit returns (approximately 9:00–9:30 AM) — a perfect post-sunrise meal before the Day 2 morning sightseeing continues at Agra Fort or other sites. Some luxury hotel packages include dinner on Day 1 as well. Confirm meal inclusions when booking." },
      { question: "What is the best Agra hotel for Taj Mahal views?", answer: "The most celebrated Agra hotel for Taj Mahal views is the **Oberoi Amarvilas** — a 5-star luxury property where every single room has direct, unobstructed Taj Mahal views from a private balcony. Waking up to the Taj Mahal outside your bedroom window is extraordinary. At a more accessible price point: **The Gateway Hotel Agra**, **Trident Agra**, and **ITC Mughal** all offer good Taj views from certain room categories. In the Taj Ganj area, numerous mid-range and budget guesthouses have rooftop restaurants with Taj views. For the overnight tour, specify 'Taj-view room' when booking to ensure your room orientation is optimal." },
      { question: "Can the overnight Agra tour be extended to Jaipur to form the Golden Triangle?", answer: "Yes — the Delhi to Agra overnight tour is the first two days of the [3-day Golden Triangle tour](/india/delhi/golden-triangle-3-day-tour-from-delhi). Adding a third day from Agra to Jaipur (5-hour drive, stopping at Fatehpur Sikri) and a guided Jaipur day (Amber Fort, City Palace, Jantar Mantar, Hawa Mahal) converts the overnight Agra trip into the complete Golden Triangle circuit. This is the most natural extension — most travellers who book the overnight Agra tour decide within the first day that they want to continue to Jaipur rather than returning directly to Delhi." },
      { question: "Is a moonlight visit to the Taj Mahal available on the overnight tour?", answer: "Yes — if your overnight Agra dates coincide with the full moon (and the two nights before and after — 5 permitted nights per month), a moonlight Taj Mahal visit can be added to your overnight tour itinerary. The moonlight permit (₹750 per person for foreign nationals) allows a 30-minute group session (max 50 people per session, starting at 8:30 PM, 9 PM, 9:30 PM, 10 PM, or 10:30 PM). Seeing the white marble in full moonlight — a blue-silver glow over the Yamuna — is described by many visitors as even more beautiful than the daytime visit. Your guide books the moonlight permit in advance. Combine evening moonlight + next morning sunrise for the ultimate Agra experience." }
    ];
  }

  // --- END DELHI TOUR FAQS BATCH 1 ---

  // --- DELHI TOUR FAQS BATCH 2 ---

  if (slug === '6-days-golden-triangle-tour-from-delhi') {
    return [
      { question: "What does the 6-day Golden Triangle tour from Delhi cover?", answer: "The 6-day Golden Triangle tour provides comprehensive coverage of three of India's most historically rich destinations: **Delhi (Days 1–2)** — Old Delhi (Jama Masjid, Red Fort, Chandni Chowk, cycle-rickshaw), New Delhi (Humayun's Tomb, Qutub Minar, India Gate), and the colonial Lutyens' Delhi area; **Agra (Days 2–3)** — Taj Mahal at sunrise, Agra Fort, Mehtab Bagh, Itmad-ud-Daula (Baby Taj), and Fatehpur Sikri (Akbar's abandoned city, en route); **Jaipur (Days 4–5)** — Amber Fort, City Palace, Jantar Mantar, Hawa Mahal, the Jaipur bazaars (block printing, blue pottery), and optionally Nahargarh Fort and Sisodia Rani Garden; **Return to Delhi (Day 6)** or departure from Jaipur airport. All hotels (5 nights), guides, entry fees, and breakfasts included." },
      { question: "How is the 6-day Golden Triangle tour different from the 3-day version?", answer: "The 3-day Golden Triangle covers the headline sites at a fast pace (one day per city). The 6-day version doubles the time in each city, transforming rushed coverage into genuine immersion: **Delhi** gets 2 days — enough to cover both the historic and modern city, including the colonial Lodi Garden and Humayun's Tomb neighbourhood. **Agra** gets 1.5–2 days — enabling the sunrise Taj Mahal visit, a separate afternoon session, all four major Agra monuments, and Fatehpur Sikri. **Jaipur** gets 2 days — covering the complete fort circuit, the old city bazaars, a village visit, and possibly Ranthambore day trip or Abhaneri step-well. The 6-day tour is for travellers who want to understand these cities, not just photograph them." },
      { question: "Is Fatehpur Sikri included in the 6-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "Yes — Fatehpur Sikri is included en route from Agra to Jaipur on Day 3 or 4. Fatehpur Sikri was Emperor Akbar's purpose-built imperial capital (1569–1585), constructed entirely in red sandstone on a rocky plateau 40 km from Agra. It is one of India's best-preserved and most striking Mughal cities — a complete royal complex of audience halls, palaces, a mosque, and a stunning gateway (Buland Darwaza, the largest mosque gateway in Asia). Most remarkably, Akbar abandoned the entire city just 14 years after completion — the reasons are debated. Your guide examines this mystery on location. Fatehpur Sikri is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and entry is included." },
      { question: "What hotel standard is included in the 6-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "The standard 6-day tour includes comfortable 4-star hotels in each city: a centrally located business or heritage hotel in Delhi (near Connaught Place or Karol Bagh), a Taj Ganj area property in Agra (Taj view preferred), and a heritage haveli or well-rated city hotel in Jaipur (old city location). Upgrade to **5-star luxury** is available: Leela Palace, ITC Maurya, or The Imperial in Delhi; Oberoi Amarvilas (every room with Taj Mahal view) in Agra; Rambagh Palace, Oberoi Rajvilas, or Samode Haveli in Jaipur. The 5-star upgrade transforms the 6-day tour into a premium luxury experience worth every rupee extra." },
      { question: "Is the 6-day Golden Triangle tour fully private?", answer: "Yes — the entire 6-day tour is 100% private. Your dedicated vehicle (and driver) covers all ground transportation between cities. A specialist guide in each city accompanies your group for all sightseeing. No other travellers are ever combined with your group at any point. This is the critical advantage of a private tour over any group coach or shared-bus option: you determine pace, request itinerary adjustments mid-tour, ask any question without group pressure, and experience every site without being herded. For a 6-day immersion, the private format is the only one that allows genuine flexibility and personalisation." },
      { question: "Can I extend the 6-day tour to include Ranthambore National Park?", answer: "Yes — Ranthambore National Park (home to Bengal tigers and UNESCO-listed medieval fort) is 175 km from Jaipur and 280 km from Agra. Adding 2 nights at Ranthambore between Agra and Jaipur extends the tour to **8 days** and adds one of India's best wildlife experiences to the cultural circuit. Morning and afternoon tiger safaris in open Gypsy jeeps produce extraordinary wildlife sightings — Ranthambore has a high tiger density and visibility rate. See our [Ranthambore full-day tour](/india/jaipur/ranthambore-full-day-tour) for day-trip details, or the 8-day extension for the full Ranthambore experience." },
      { question: "What is the daily transport schedule for the 6-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "**Day 1:** Delhi hotel check-in (arrival), first Delhi sightseeing afternoon. **Day 2:** Full Delhi day (Old Delhi morning, New Delhi afternoon). Evening drive to Agra (3.5 hours). **Day 3:** Taj Mahal sunrise, Agra Fort, Mehtab Bagh, lunch in Agra. Afternoon drive via Fatehpur Sikri to Jaipur (3.5 hours). **Day 4:** Full Jaipur day (Amber Fort, City Palace, Jantar Mantar). **Day 5:** Second Jaipur day (Hawa Mahal, bazaars, Nahargarh Fort, Jaipur pink city walk). **Day 6:** Drive Jaipur to Delhi airport (5 hours) or end tour in Jaipur. All drives use the private air-conditioned vehicle." },
      { question: "Are meals included in the 6-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "Daily **breakfasts** at hotels are included across all 5 nights. **Lunches and dinners** can be added to the package at a supplement, or you can arrange meals independently each day (your guide recommends specific restaurants at each stop). Most travellers prefer the flexibility of self-arranged lunches and dinners — this allows you to explore local street food, follow recommendations, and eat on your own schedule. The guide's restaurant recommendations in each city are excellent — they know the best local establishments for both quality and hygiene. Inform us of any dietary requirements so the guide can advise appropriately throughout the tour." },
      { question: "Is the 6-day Golden Triangle suitable for families with children?", answer: "The 6-day Golden Triangle is an excellent family itinerary — longer durations at each city mean less rushing, more flexibility for meal breaks and rest, and time to engage children at sites they find particularly interesting without sacrificing coverage elsewhere. Highlights that children typically love: the elephant ride at Amber Fort Jaipur, the cycle-rickshaw ride through Old Delhi's Chandni Chowk, the Taj Mahal's scale and love story, the mechanical astronomical instruments at Jantar Mantar, and the Agra Fort's towers. All guides are experienced with family groups and adapt commentary to engage children alongside adults." },
      { question: "What visa do I need for the 6-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "Most international travellers require an **Indian e-Visa** (electronic visa), which can be applied for online at the official Indian government portal (indianvisaonline.gov.in). The **e-Tourist Visa** is the most common type: available for citizens of **160+ countries**, valid for **30 days, 1 year, or 5 years** depending on the option selected, and typically approved within **24–72 hours** of application. Key requirements: a passport valid for at least **6 months beyond your arrival date**, a recent passport-size photograph (white background), and a return or onward flight booking. **Important:** the e-Visa must be obtained **before departure** — it cannot be obtained on arrival. Citizens of a few countries (including Japan, South Korea, and UAE) may qualify for **visa-on-arrival** at select Indian airports. Your tour confirmation and hotel bookings can serve as supporting documents for the visa application. We recommend applying at least **2 weeks before travel** to allow for any processing delays. For detailed planning around your Delhi arrival, see our <a href='/india/delhi/delhi-travel-guide-2026'>Delhi travel guide</a>." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'from-delhi-same-day-taj-mahal-fastest-train') {
    return [
      { question: "What is the fastest train from Delhi to the Taj Mahal?", answer: "The **Gatimaan Express** (train 12049) is India's fastest train, traveling at up to 160 km/h and covering the Delhi Hazrat Nizamuddin to Agra Cantonment route in just **1 hour 40 minutes**. This is significantly faster than the road journey (3–3.5 hours by car). The Gatimaan Express departs Hazrat Nizamuddin station at **8:10 AM** and arrives at Agra Cantonment at **9:50 AM**, returning from Agra at **8:05 PM** and arriving back in Delhi at **9:45 PM**. This schedule provides approximately 10 hours in Agra — ample time for the Taj Mahal, Agra Fort, and lunch with a comfortable pace. The train is the fastest way to get from Delhi to the Taj Mahal." },
      { question: "How does the same-day Taj Mahal train tour from Delhi work?", answer: "Your tour package includes: private vehicle pickup from your Delhi hotel to Hazrat Nizamuddin station, Gatimaan Express round-trip tickets (Executive Chair Car), an AC vehicle waiting at Agra Cantonment station on arrival, Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide for all Agra sightseeing, all entry tickets (Taj Mahal + Agra Fort), sit-down lunch in Agra, and return transfer from Agra station to Delhi hotel. The guide meets you at Agra Cantonment station platform as you disembark and manages all logistics from that point. The entire experience is seamlessly coordinated — no independent ticket buying, vehicle hailing, or navigation required." },
      { question: "What class of train is included in the fastest train Taj Mahal tour?", answer: "**Executive Chair Car (EC)** — the premium Gatimaan Express class — is included as standard. EC class offers wider, more comfortable reclining seats with extra legroom, and complimentary in-seat meals: a hot breakfast is served on the morning journey, and an evening snack with tea is served on the return. The carriage is clean, well-maintained, and significantly more comfortable than standard Indian train classes. EC class ticket prices are higher than AC Chair Car but the experience is worth the premium — arriving in Agra having eaten a hot breakfast at 300+ km/h is a genuinely enjoyable start to the day." },
      { question: "What station should I use for the fastest train to Agra in Delhi?", answer: "The Gatimaan Express departs from **Hazrat Nizamuddin Railway Station** (station code: NZM) — not New Delhi station, not Old Delhi station. Hazrat Nizamuddin is in south-central Delhi, approximately 20–25 minutes from most central Delhi hotels and 30–40 minutes from north Delhi or Connaught Place hotels (depending on traffic). Your tour package includes a private vehicle pickup from your hotel to Hazrat Nizamuddin, with departure from the hotel approximately **90 minutes before the 8:10 AM train** (so typically 6:30–6:45 AM hotel pickup) to allow for station arrival, baggage, and boarding." },
      { question: "Is the Taj Mahal visited with a guide on the fastest train tour?", answer: "Yes — a Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide is included for the complete Taj Mahal and Agra Fort visits. The guide meets you at Agra Cantonment station and accompanies you throughout the day. Arriving by train at 9:50 AM means you reach the Taj Mahal by approximately 10:30 AM — slightly later than a car-based sunrise visit (which starts at 9 AM or earlier). However, with a full 10 hours in Agra, there is ample time for an unhurried and comprehensive visit. The guide manages all ticketing, entry, and navigation so you experience Agra without any logistical concern." },
      { question: "Is the fastest train tour better for the Taj Mahal than driving by car?", answer: "Both options have distinct strengths. **Fastest train (Gatimaan):** Journey in just 1h40m vs 3.5 hours driving; on-board meals served at seat; a unique Indian railway experience; arrives at Agra slightly later (10:30 AM at Taj Mahal vs 9:00 AM by car). **Private car:** Door-to-door flexibility; can depart at 5:30 AM for sunrise Taj Mahal experience; no fixed timetable; can stop en route. **Best choice:** The Gatimaan Express is ideal for travellers who want the fastest and most comfortable transit, a genuine Indian train experience, and comfortable timing. The car is better for those who prioritize the sunrise Taj Mahal visit or who want maximum scheduling flexibility." },
      { question: "What time does the same-day fastest train tour from Delhi return?", answer: "The return Gatimaan Express (train 12050) departs **Agra Cantonment at 8:05 PM** and arrives at **Hazrat Nizamuddin Delhi at 9:45 PM**. Your driver will be waiting at Hazrat Nizamuddin to transfer you back to your Delhi hotel, arriving approximately 10:30–11:00 PM. This is a long day (hotel pickup ~6:30 AM, return ~10:30–11 PM) but the 10 hours in Agra make it completely worthwhile. If you prefer an earlier return, an alternative afternoon train (Taj Express or Intercity) can be used — discuss your return timing preference when booking." },
      { question: "Are all entry tickets included in the fastest train Taj Mahal tour?", answer: "Yes — all entry tickets are included: Taj Mahal main complex (₹1,300 for foreign nationals), inner mausoleum entry (₹200), and Agra Fort (₹650). The guide pre-arranges or purchases tickets on arrival, meaning no additional payment is required at any monument gate during the day. The included ticket value for a foreign national is approximately ₹2,150. Any optional additions (Mehtab Bagh ₹300, Itmad-ud-Daula ₹310) are purchased on the day if you choose to include them — your guide advises based on your available time and interest." },
      { question: "What should I eat on the Gatimaan Express train to Agra?", answer: "In Executive Chair Car class, a **hot breakfast** is served at your seat on the morning journey — typically a choice of Indian (upma, poha, or paratha with pickle) or continental (bread with jam and butter) with a hot beverage (tea or coffee). The food is prepared by Indian Railways catering and is included in your EC class ticket. On the return evening journey, a **snack and tea** are served. For travellers with specific dietary requirements (vegetarian, vegan, halal, gluten-free), the train catering is limited — inform us when booking so alternative snack arrangements can be made for the journey if needed." },
      { question: "How fast is the Vande Bharat Express compared to the Gatimaan Express for Agra?", answer: "The **Vande Bharat Express** and **Gatimaan Express** are India's two fastest train options for the Delhi–Agra route, but they differ in key ways. **Gatimaan Express (12049):** maximum speed **160 km/h**, journey time **1 hour 40 minutes** (Delhi Hazrat Nizamuddin to Agra Cantonment), departs **8:10 AM**. **Vande Bharat Express:** India's newest semi-high-speed train, maximum speed **160 km/h** (same top speed as Gatimaan), but with **faster acceleration and modern tilting technology** that reduces journey time on curves. The Vande Bharat on the Delhi–Agra route covers the distance in approximately **1 hour 30–40 minutes** — marginally faster. Key differences: Vande Bharat has **newer rolling stock** (manufactured 2019 onward), automatic doors, bio-vacuum toilets, GPS-based passenger information screens, and a more modern interior. Gatimaan has a longer track record and established scheduling. Both trains offer Executive Chair Car with in-seat meals. Your tour operator selects whichever train offers the best timing and availability for your travel date. For more on planning your complete Delhi experience, see our <a href='/india/delhi/delhi-1-day-itinerary'>Delhi 1-day itinerary</a> guide." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'explore-old-new-delhi-city-luxury-car-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What does the luxury car Delhi city tour cover?", answer: "The luxury car Delhi city tour covers both historic Old Delhi and modern New Delhi in an air-conditioned premium vehicle with a private guide: **Old Delhi** — Jama Masjid (India's largest mosque, built 1656), Red Fort (UNESCO Mughal fortress, built 1648), Chandni Chowk bazaar (rickshaw ride through the historic market lanes), and Khari Baoli (Asia's largest spice market). **New Delhi** — India Gate and Rajpath (the ceremonial boulevard of the British Raj), Humayun's Tomb (UNESCO Heritage, 1570, architectural predecessor to the Taj Mahal), Qutub Minar (UNESCO Heritage, 12th-century Islamic minaret), and the Lodi Garden (Mughal and pre-Mughal tombs in a park setting). Optional: Akshardham Temple, Lotus Temple, and the colonial Connaught Place area." },
      { question: "What type of luxury vehicle is used for the Delhi city tour?", answer: "The luxury car Delhi tour uses a premium air-conditioned vehicle — options include the **Toyota Innova Crysta** (premium SUV, ideal for families and small groups up to 6), **Toyota Fortuner** (larger luxury SUV), or **Mercedes E-Class / BMW 5 Series** for couples and individuals seeking maximum comfort. All vehicles are chauffeur-driven by professionally dressed, experienced Delhi city drivers. The vehicle is your private transport for the full day — it waits at each monument while you are inside with the guide, acting as a mobile base providing cool air-conditioned respite between sites. USB charging, mineral water, and Wi-Fi are available in all vehicles." },
      { question: "Is a guide included in the luxury Delhi city tour?", answer: "Yes — a senior Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide is included throughout the day. For a luxury car tour, the guide is matched to the premium vehicle — a senior professional with deep expertise in Delhi's history and architecture, strong communication skills, and experience with discerning international travellers. The guide provides comprehensive commentary at each site: Old Delhi's Mughal history, the architectural significance of Humayun's Tomb as the Taj Mahal's prototype, the colonial history of New Delhi designed by Edwin Lutyens and Herbert Baker, and the archaeological layers of Delhi's 3,000-year history. This guide-vehicle combination is the most comfortable and educational way to experience Delhi." },
      { question: "What makes this different from a standard Delhi city tour?", answer: "Standard Delhi tours use a Toyota Innova or similar mid-level vehicle with a competent guide. The luxury car tour upgrades every element: premium vehicle with leather interior, chauffeur-level driver, **senior specialist guide** rather than standard guide, personalized attention to your specific interests, and often access to premium restaurants for lunch. The pace is also more relaxed — the luxury format assumes you want depth at each site, not a rapid drive-by of landmarks. For business travellers, high-net-worth visitors, or travellers for whom Delhi is a once-in-a-lifetime destination, the luxury car tour provides an experience commensurate with the city's extraordinary historical significance." },
      { question: "Can the luxury Delhi tour include a Mughal dinner experience?", answer: "Yes — a private Mughal-style dinner at a heritage restaurant can be added as an evening extension to the luxury car Delhi city tour. Delhi has several excellent restaurants specializing in Mughal royal cuisine: dishes derived from the recipe books of the imperial kitchens (nihari, mughlai biryani, korma, shahi tukda). Karim's in Old Delhi (operating since 1913, reportedly descended from Mughal royal khansamas/chefs) is the most historically authentic. For a premium experience, reservations at Bukhara (ITC Maurya hotel) — consistently ranked among Asia's best restaurants — can be arranged. The driver and vehicle return you to your hotel after dinner." },
      { question: "Is the Chandni Chowk rickshaw ride included in the luxury Delhi tour?", answer: "Yes — a cycle-rickshaw ride through Chandni Chowk's historic market lanes is included and is one of the most authentic elements of the Old Delhi experience. The luxury car is parked safely while you transfer to a cycle-rickshaw for approximately 30–45 minutes of slow, immersive navigation through the 17th-century bazaar. The guide accompanies you on the rickshaw (or walks alongside), pointing out the specialized trade lanes (silver market, wedding sari shops, spice vendors, sweet makers) and explaining the original Mughal bazaar layout. This deliberate slowing-down in a rickshaw after hours in an air-conditioned car is the highlight of Old Delhi for most visitors." },
      { question: "What time does the luxury Delhi city tour start?", answer: "Pickup from your Delhi hotel is at **8:30–9:00 AM** — starting mid-morning allows you to avoid the worst rush hour traffic and arrive at Old Delhi as the Jama Masjid opens. For visitors who specifically want to experience the early morning wholesale spice trade at Khari Baoli (the spice market is most atmospheric before 9 AM), an earlier 7:30 AM pickup can be arranged. The tour runs until approximately **7:00–8:00 PM** (including an optional sunset at India Gate). Lunch at a premium Delhi restaurant is included at approximately 1:00 PM. The guide designs the sequence to minimize traffic and maximize morning light at key sites." },
      { question: "How many sites does the luxury Delhi tour cover in one day?", answer: "The luxury Delhi city tour covers 7–9 sites over the full day, with 30–90 minutes at each depending on significance: Jama Masjid (45 min), Red Fort exterior and forecourt (30 min), Chandni Chowk rickshaw (45 min), Khari Baoli spice market walk (30 min), Humayun's Tomb (60–90 min), Qutub Minar (60 min), India Gate (30 min). Optional additions: Lodi Garden (45 min), Lotus Temple (30 min), Akshardham Temple (90 min). The pace is deliberately unhurried — the luxury format prioritises depth over quantity. If you find yourself particularly captivated by one site, the guide extends time there and adjusts the remaining itinerary." },
      { question: "Is the Delhi luxury car tour suitable for senior travellers?", answer: "The luxury car Delhi tour is the most appropriate format for senior travellers. The premium vehicle provides maximum comfort between sites, door-to-door hotel service eliminates any walking to transport, and the guide manages all logistics including entry queuing, security, and ticket purchase. Inside monuments, electric golf buggies are available for mobility-impaired visitors at Humayun's Tomb, Qutub Minar, and Red Fort areas. The guide adapts the pace to suit the group — there is no fixed schedule to keep, no rush, and no compromise on comfort. For senior travellers visiting Delhi for the first time, this tour provides the maximum historical immersion with the minimum physical stress." },
      { question: "What specific luxury car models are used for the Delhi city tour?", answer: "The luxury car Delhi city tour offers a selection of premium vehicles matched to your group size and preference: **For couples and solo travellers (1–2 persons):** **Mercedes E-Class** (flagship sedan with leather interior, rear climate control, and superior ride quality on Delhi's varied road surfaces), **BMW 5 Series** (sport-luxury sedan with exceptional road handling), or **Audi A6** (refined comfort with advanced sound insulation). **For small groups (3–4 persons):** **Toyota Innova Crysta Luxury** (India's most popular premium SUV, spacious third-row seating, captain seats in the top trim), **Toyota Fortuner** (full-size SUV with commanding road position), or **Mercedes GLE** (luxury SUV). **For larger groups (5–7 persons):** **Toyota Alphard** (ultra-luxury van with executive reclining seats and privacy glass), **Mercedes V-Class** (premium people-mover with captain chairs), or **Toyota Land Cruiser Prado** (full-size luxury SUV). All vehicles are **late-model (2022 or newer)**, professionally maintained, and equipped with **leather seating, dual-zone climate control, USB-C charging ports, Wi-Fi hotspot, cold mineral water, and hand sanitiser**. The chauffeur wears a professional uniform and is an experienced Delhi city driver. Specify your vehicle preference when booking. For more on Delhi's highlights, see our <a href='/india/delhi/old-new-delhi-guided-tour'>Old and New Delhi guided tour</a> page." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'old-new-delhi-private-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What does the Old Delhi and New Delhi private tour cover?", answer: "The private Old Delhi and New Delhi tour covers the city's two distinct historical personalities in a single day: **Old Delhi (Shahjahanabad)** — the 17th-century Mughal city built by Emperor Shah Jahan: Jama Masjid (India's largest mosque), Red Fort (UNESCO Mughal fortress), the Chandni Chowk bazaar (rickshaw ride through the original market lanes), and the Fatehpuri Masjid. **New Delhi** — the British Raj-era capital designed by Edwin Lutyens and Herbert Baker in the 1920s–30s: India Gate (war memorial), the Presidential Palace and Parliament (exterior), Humayun's Tomb (UNESCO Heritage), and Qutub Minar (UNESCO Heritage, 12th century). The private tour format means all timing, pace, and emphasis are determined by your group's preferences." },
      { question: "Is this tour truly private — just for my group?", answer: "Yes — this is a 100% private tour with no shared participants. Your guide and vehicle work exclusively for your group throughout the day. This private format is what distinguishes the experience from shared group tours: the guide focuses entirely on your questions, pacing is adjusted to your interests, photography stops are as long or as brief as you wish, and the itinerary can be modified mid-day based on what you are most enjoying. For a city as complex and layered as Delhi, the difference between a private guide and a group tour guide is enormous — private commentary is richer, more responsive, and more personalized." },
      { question: "What is the Jama Masjid and can non-Muslims visit?", answer: "Jama Masjid is the largest mosque in India, built by Emperor Shah Jahan between 1644 and 1656 with 5,000 daily workers. It can accommodate 25,000 worshippers in its sandstone and marble courtyard. Non-Muslims are welcome to visit during non-prayer hours (typically 9 AM–12 PM and 1:30 PM–sunset, except during Friday Jumu'ah prayers when only Muslims enter). Modest dress is required: covered head and shoes removed at the main entrance (shoe deposit available). Women must cover their hair (scarves provided at the entrance for a small fee). From the mosque's minarets (additional fee, small climb), the view over the old city rooftops to the Red Fort is extraordinary. Your guide explains the mosque's architecture and history before entry." },
      { question: "How long does the full Old Delhi and New Delhi private tour take?", answer: "The complete private tour covers 7–8 sites and runs approximately **9–10 hours** from hotel pickup to hotel drop-off: pickup at 8:30–9:00 AM, return at approximately 6:30–7:30 PM. Old Delhi sites (Jama Masjid, Chandni Chowk, Red Fort exterior): approximately 2.5–3 hours in the morning. Lunch: 1 hour at approximately 1:00 PM. New Delhi sites (Humayun's Tomb, Qutub Minar, India Gate): approximately 3–3.5 hours in the afternoon. Transit between sites (Delhi traffic): approximately 1.5–2 hours across the day. This is a full, packed day that comprehensively covers both Old and New Delhi at a quality pace." },
      { question: "What is the best order for visiting Old Delhi vs. New Delhi in one day?", answer: "**Old Delhi first, New Delhi in the afternoon** is the recommended sequence for this private tour. Old Delhi's energy is best in the morning — the spice markets, the bazaar activity, and the Jama Masjid puja morning atmosphere are all at their peak before noon. Chandni Chowk is also cooler and less oppressively hot in the morning than the afternoon. New Delhi's monuments (Humayun's Tomb, Qutub Minar) benefit from afternoon light for photography and are less affected by the midday heat than Chandni Chowk's open bazaar lanes. India Gate at sunset (approximately 5:30–6:30 PM depending on season) is a beautiful way to conclude the day." },
      { question: "Are entry tickets included in the private Old and New Delhi tour?", answer: "Yes — all monument entry tickets are included: Jama Masjid interior access, Red Fort main complex (₹600 foreign nationals), Humayun's Tomb (₹600 foreign nationals), and Qutub Minar (₹600 foreign nationals). Total included ticket value for a foreign national visitor is approximately ₹1,800. India Gate, the President's House area (exterior viewing), and the Chandni Chowk rickshaw ride are included in the tour price. The Lodi Garden (free entry) is added if time permits. Children under 15 enter all ASI monuments for free." },
      { question: "Is a cycle-rickshaw ride through Chandni Chowk included?", answer: "Yes — a cycle-rickshaw ride through the lanes of Chandni Chowk is included and is one of the most memorable elements of the Old Delhi experience. The rickshaw gives you a street-level, immersive view of the 17th-century market that is impossible from a car or on foot (the lanes are too narrow for vehicles and too overwhelming to navigate alone). Your guide either rides with you or walks alongside, pointing out the specialized trade streets: the gold jewellery lane (Dariba Kalan), the wedding decoration street (Kinari Bazaar), the wholesale spice market (Khari Baoli), and the famous sweet shops (jalebi, rabri, kulfi). The 30–45 minute rickshaw section is typically the most talked-about part of the day." },
      { question: "What should I wear for the Old Delhi private tour?", answer: "Comfortable, breathable cotton clothing is essential — Delhi can be very hot. Modest dress is required for mosque visits: covered shoulders and knees, and a head covering for women (scarves are available at mosque entrances). Comfortable walking shoes are important — the Chandni Chowk section involves 20–30 minutes of walking through bazaar lanes on uneven surfaces. Closed shoes provide better protection than open sandals in the crowded bazaar environment. A compact bag (not a large backpack) is more manageable in narrow market lanes. Sunscreen, sunglasses, and a small personal water bottle are recommended for the outdoor sections." },
      { question: "Can I try street food in Old Delhi on this private tour?", answer: "Yes — Old Delhi is India's street food capital and trying local specialties is highly encouraged on this private tour. Your guide can introduce you to the most famous Old Delhi street foods with full context: **Paranthe Wali Gali** (the century-old stuffed flatbread lane near Chandni Chowk), **Karim's restaurant** (Mughal-descended cooking since 1913), **rabri (condensed milk dessert) stalls**, and **jalebi (crispy fried sugar syrup coils)** at famous century-old vendors. Your guide is familiar with the food safety standards of each stall and recommends only vendors with reliable hygiene. Most travellers with open minds and basic food safety awareness have excellent street food experiences in Old Delhi." },
      { question: "Can the Old and New Delhi private tour be customized to specific interests?", answer: "Yes — full customization is one of the key advantages of this private tour format. Your guide adapts the itinerary to your specific interests: **Architecture enthusiasts** — extended time at Humayun's Tomb (the direct architectural prototype of the Taj Mahal) and Qutub Minar complex, with detailed structural and design commentary. **Photography enthusiasts** — the guide adjusts the sequence and timing to capture the best light at each monument (morning for Old Delhi lanes, late afternoon for Humayun's Tomb golden tones). **Food and culture enthusiasts** — add a **2-hour Old Delhi food walk** covering Paranthe Wali Gali, Karim's, and hidden local vendors the guide personally recommends. **History enthusiasts** — add the **Partition Museum** at Red Fort or the **National Museum** for Indus Valley and Mughal collections. **Spiritual interests** — add **Gurudwara Bangla Sahib** (Sikh temple with communal kitchen serving 10,000 meals daily), **Lotus Temple** (Baha'i house of worship), or a visit to **Nizamuddin Dargah** (Sufi shrine with Thursday evening qawwali singing). Share your interests when booking and the guide will propose a tailored sequence. For itinerary ideas, see our <a href='/india/delhi/things-to-do-in-delhi'>things to do in Delhi</a> page." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'sunrise-taj-mahal-tour-delhi-all-inclusive') {
    return [
      { question: "What does 'all-inclusive' mean for the sunrise Taj Mahal tour from Delhi?", answer: "The all-inclusive sunrise Taj Mahal tour from Delhi covers every cost of the experience: hotel pickup and drop-off in Delhi, private air-conditioned vehicle (Delhi–Agra–Delhi), Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide, all Taj Mahal entry tickets (main complex + inner mausoleum, ₹1,500 combined for foreign nationals), Agra Fort entry tickets (₹650), overshoes for the marble platform, bottled water, and a sit-down lunch in Agra. There are no additional payments required at any monument gate, no hidden charges, and no cash management during the day. The price you pay at booking covers the complete experience from hotel departure to hotel return." },
      { question: "Why is this a sunrise tour from Delhi if Delhi is 3.5 hours from Agra?", answer: "This tour achieves the sunrise experience despite the 3.5-hour drive by requiring an **early 4:00–4:30 AM departure from Delhi**. This allows arrival at the Taj Mahal gate for approximately 7:30–8:00 AM — past the absolute first opening but still in the morning's best light and before the main tourist wave arrives at 9–10 AM. For visitors who want the classic 'sunrise' Taj Mahal shot from Delhi in a single day without overnight accommodation, a 4 AM departure is the necessary trade-off. Alternatively, the tour can be split into an overnight: travel to Agra the evening before, stay overnight, and begin the sunrise visit from your Agra hotel at 5:00 AM — a dramatically better experience." },
      { question: "Is a guide included throughout the all-inclusive Delhi Taj Mahal tour?", answer: "Yes — a Ministry of Tourism-licensed professional guide accompanies the group throughout the Agra visit. The guide provides complete historical and architectural commentary at the Taj Mahal (2–2.5 hours) and Agra Fort (1.5 hours). For the Delhi-to-Agra driving segments, the guide may travel separately to Agra and meet you there, or in some packages, rides in the vehicle and provides contextual information about the passing Yamuna plain landscape and Mughal history. The guide manages all ticketing, security navigation, and entry logistics at each monument." },
      { question: "What time is the pickup for the all-inclusive sunrise Taj Mahal tour from Delhi?", answer: "Pickup from Delhi hotels is at **4:00–4:30 AM** — earlier than a standard same-day tour to allow arrival at the Taj Mahal for the best morning light. The driver and guide coordinate exactly based on your hotel location (hotels in south Delhi are closest to the Yamuna Expressway entry). A 4:00 AM pickup from Connaught Place-area hotels typically arrives at the Taj Mahal by 7:30–8:00 AM. The early start is demanding but most travellers find the Taj Mahal at 8 AM (soft morning light, reduced crowds) far superior to 10–11 AM (harsh light, large crowds). Tea and snacks are provided in the vehicle for the early morning journey." },
      { question: "Is Agra Fort included in the all-inclusive Delhi sunrise tour?", answer: "Yes — [Agra Fort](/india/agra/agra-fort) entry tickets and guided visit are included in the all-inclusive price. After the sunrise Taj Mahal visit (approximately 7:30–10:00 AM), the tour moves to Agra Fort (10:00–11:30 AM) for a 1.5-hour guided visit. Agra Fort contains the Musamman Burj — the octagonal tower from which Shah Jahan was imprisoned by his son Aurangzeb (1658–1666) and from which he could see the distant Taj Mahal across the Yamuna. This narrative connects the two monuments emotionally and historically. Entry tickets (₹650 for foreign nationals) are included in the all-inclusive price." },
      { question: "Is lunch included in the all-inclusive Taj Mahal tour from Delhi?", answer: "Yes — a sit-down lunch at a quality restaurant in Agra is included in the all-inclusive price. The meal takes place between approximately 12:00–1:00 PM after the Agra Fort visit and before the return drive to Delhi. The restaurant offers North Indian, Mughlai, and continental dishes with comprehensive vegetarian, vegan, Jain, halal, and allergen options. The all-inclusive pricing means you pay once at booking and do not need to manage cash or negotiate with restaurants during the day. Inform us of dietary requirements at booking so the restaurant is briefed in advance." },
      { question: "How many hours are actually spent at the Taj Mahal on this tour?", answer: "Approximately **2–2.5 hours** inside the Taj Mahal complex (the same as any quality guided visit). This is sufficient for the complete guided tour: Great Gate, gardens, main terrace, mausoleum exterior, inner chamber visit, and photography at key viewpoints. The 'sunrise' designation refers to arriving in the morning light (as early as possible from Delhi) rather than literally at the moment of sunrise — arriving at the Taj Mahal at 7:30–8:00 AM from Delhi still provides excellent morning light and pre-crowd conditions. The 2.5-hour guided visit is not reduced by the all-inclusive format." },
      { question: "What is the return time to Delhi on the all-inclusive sunrise tour?", answer: "Departure from Agra is at approximately **1:30–2:00 PM** after lunch, with arrival back in Delhi at approximately **5:00–5:30 PM** (3.5-hour return drive). This return timing is one of the advantages of the early departure — by leaving Agra in the early afternoon, you avoid Delhi's severe rush hour traffic (worst 6–9 PM) and arrive back before evening. Total day duration: approximately 13 hours (4:00 AM hotel departure to 5:30 PM hotel return). The early morning start and afternoon return make this the most time-efficient all-inclusive Taj Mahal day trip format from Delhi." },
      { question: "What makes this better than a standard same-day Delhi-Agra tour?", answer: "The all-inclusive sunrise tour from Delhi improves on standard same-day tours in several ways: (1) **Earlier departure (4 AM vs 5:30–6 AM)** — better morning Taj Mahal timing; (2) **Complete all-inclusive pricing** — no money management during the day; (3) **Everything pre-arranged** — tickets, vehicle, guide, lunch all confirmed before departure; (4) **Full day return to Delhi (5 PM vs 7 PM)** — earlier home/hotel arrival. For first-time India visitors who want the simplest, most stress-free approach to the Taj Mahal day trip from Delhi, the all-inclusive format removes every decision and every cash transaction from the day." },
      { question: "What exactly is included in the all-inclusive price — full breakdown?", answer: "The all-inclusive price covers every element of the tour with **zero additional costs on the day**. Full breakdown: (1) **Hotel pickup and drop-off** — private air-conditioned vehicle collects you from any Delhi hotel (including Aerocity, Noida, and Gurgaon) and returns you door-to-door; (2) **Vehicle** — private AC sedan or SUV (Toyota Innova Crysta or equivalent) with professional driver for the full Delhi–Agra–Delhi journey (~400 km round trip), including all fuel, tolls (Yamuna Expressway ₹415 each way), and monument parking fees; (3) **Guide** — Ministry of Tourism-licensed professional guide for the complete Agra sightseeing day; (4) **Taj Mahal tickets** — main complex entry (₹1,300 foreign nationals) + inner mausoleum entry (₹200); (5) **Agra Fort tickets** — ₹650 for foreign nationals; (6) **Taj Mahal overshoes** — shoe covers for the marble platform (provided free); (7) **Lunch** — sit-down meal at a quality Agra restaurant (vegetarian, vegan, Jain, halal, and allergen options available); (8) **Bottled water** — cold mineral water in the vehicle throughout the day; (9) **Morning refreshments** — tea/coffee and light snacks for the early morning drive. **Not included (optional):** tips for guide and driver, personal shopping, and any optional add-on sites (Mehtab Bagh, Itmad-ud-Daula). Total included value for a foreign national exceeds **₹2,500 in tickets alone**, plus vehicle, guide, meals, and refreshments. For full Taj Mahal entry details, see our <a href='/india/agra/taj-mahal-entry-ticket'>Taj Mahal entry ticket</a> page." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-agra-day-trip-luxury-car') {
    return [
      { question: "What type of luxury car is used for the Agra day trip?", answer: "The Agra day trip luxury car tour uses a premium vehicle — typically a **Mercedes E-Class, BMW 5 Series, or Toyota Land Cruiser** for couples and small groups, or a **Mercedes V-Class or Toyota Alphard** for groups of 4–6 seeking the ultimate luxury van experience. All vehicles are late-model, professionally cleaned, chauffeur-driven, and fully air-conditioned. Interior amenities include leather seating, USB-C charging, Wi-Fi hotspot, cold mineral water and refreshments in the console, and a phone charging station. The driver wears a professional uniform and is experienced on the Delhi–Agra Yamuna Expressway. This is the most comfortable, private road transfer available for the Delhi–Agra journey." },
      { question: "Is a guide included in the luxury car Agra day trip?", answer: "Yes — a senior Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide accompanies you throughout the Agra visit. For a luxury vehicle day trip, the guide is matched to the premium experience — a senior professional with deep historical and architectural knowledge, strong English or other language fluency, and experience with high-end international travellers. The guide meets your group at the Taj Mahal gate (or travels with you from Delhi depending on the package) and provides full commentary at the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort. The driver and guide coordinate seamlessly so the transition between sites is smooth and unhurried." },
      { question: "What is included in the luxury car Taj Mahal Agra day trip?", answer: "Included: luxury vehicle (Mercedes, BMW, or equivalent) for the full Delhi–Agra–Delhi day, professionally uniformed chauffeur, senior Ministry of Tourism guide, all entry tickets (Taj Mahal main complex + inner mausoleum + Agra Fort), a premium lunch at a quality Agra restaurant (4-star level), refreshments in the vehicle throughout the day, and hotel pickup/drop-off. The complete all-inclusive pricing means no hidden costs on the day. Premium add-ons available: moonlight Taj Mahal visit permit (₹750/person), Mehtab Bagh entry, private dinner at a heritage Agra property." },
      { question: "What makes the luxury car Agra day trip different from a standard car tour?", answer: "Standard Agra day tours use a Toyota Innova or Mahindra SUV — reliable, comfortable, and perfectly adequate. The luxury car tour upgrades the vehicle to a prestige European or premium Japanese model with leather interior, superior suspension for the 400 km round trip, and a chauffeur-level driver. Beyond the vehicle: a senior specialist guide rather than a standard guide, a premium restaurant for lunch (rather than a mid-range establishment), pre-chilled mineral water and a travel amenity bag in the vehicle, and concierge-level attention to preferences. For travellers celebrating a special occasion or those accustomed to luxury travel standards, this format provides an Agra experience commensurate with the destination's significance." },
      { question: "Can the luxury car Agra day trip be customized for a proposal or anniversary?", answer: "Yes — the luxury car Agra day trip is one of our most popular choices for romantic proposals. The setup can include: a private moment arranged at the Taj Mahal terrace or in Mehtab Bagh garden (away from crowds) for the proposal itself; a bottle of champagne in the luxury vehicle; pre-arranged flowers in the car; and a private dinner at a heritage Agra property in the evening (extended to overnight). For anniversaries, a Taj Mahal rooftop restaurant lunch with views of the monument is a beautiful addition. Inform us of the occasion at booking so every detail is personalized. The guide is briefed to create a memorable, private atmosphere throughout." },
      { question: "What time is the pickup for the luxury car Agra day trip from Delhi?", answer: "Pickup from Delhi hotels is at **5:30–6:00 AM** for a full-day luxury experience. This allows arrival at the Taj Mahal by approximately **9:00 AM** — the optimal time for morning light, reasonable crowds, and comfortable temperature. For clients who specifically want the sunrise experience (arriving before 7:30 AM), a **4:30–5:00 AM pickup** can be arranged. The luxury vehicle is available from the agreed pickup time, and the chauffeur is at the hotel entrance 5 minutes early. For Agra-hotel-based clients, the luxury vehicle picks up at **5:00 AM** for the short drive to the Taj Mahal gate in time for sunrise." },
      { question: "Is lunch at a 5-star hotel included in the luxury car Agra tour?", answer: "The standard luxury car tour includes a premium 4-star restaurant lunch in Agra. Upgrading to a **5-star hotel lunch** (Oberoi Amarvilas, ITC Mughal, or Trident Agra) is available at a supplement and is highly recommended for the complete luxury experience. The Oberoi Amarvilas restaurant in particular offers a fine dining lunch with direct Taj Mahal views — the combination of exceptional Mughal-inspired cuisine and the monument framed through floor-to-ceiling windows is extraordinary. A 5-star lunch adds approximately 1–1.5 hours to the Agra visit time. Specify your preference when booking." },
      { question: "Can the luxury car tour be extended to an overnight Agra stay?", answer: "Yes — extending the luxury car day trip to an overnight stay in Agra is strongly recommended for the ultimate experience. Overnight at the Oberoi Amarvilas (direct Taj Mahal views from every room and private balcony), followed by the sunrise Taj Mahal session the next morning, is one of India's finest travel experiences. The luxury car returns to Delhi on Day 2 morning after the sunrise visit. The Oberoi Amarvilas costs significantly more than standard hotels but the Taj Mahal viewed from a private balcony at dawn and dusk — in absolute comfort — is an experience with no equivalent in world travel." },
      { question: "Where does the luxury car park at the Taj Mahal?", answer: "The luxury car parks at the **Shilpgram Parking Complex** — the designated vehicle parking area approximately **1 km from the Taj Mahal's East or West Gate**. No private vehicles are permitted within 500 metres of the Taj Mahal to reduce air pollution damage to the white marble. From the parking area, electric battery-operated buses (included, no extra charge) or horse-drawn tongas shuttle visitors to the gate. Your chauffeur drops you at the closest permitted point and waits with the vehicle for the duration of your visit, with the air-conditioning running so the car is cool when you return. The guide manages all gate entry and ticketing so you walk directly from the shuttle to the monument without delay. For full <a href='/india/agra/taj-mahal-entry-ticket'>Taj Mahal entry ticket</a> details, see our dedicated guide." },
      { question: "What are the best photo spots at the Taj Mahal on the luxury car tour?", answer: "Your senior guide knows the **best photography positions** at every hour of the day. The top spots include: (1) **The Diana Bench** — the iconic front-facing bench on the central water channel, made famous by Princess Diana's 1992 photograph; (2) **The Great Gate frame** — standing inside the main entrance arch, the Taj Mahal is perfectly framed within the red sandstone gateway; (3) **The raised marble platform** — from the base of the mausoleum itself, looking down the reflecting pools and gardens; (4) **The mosque side terrace** — a less crowded angle showing the Taj Mahal's western profile against the Yamuna River; (5) **Mehtab Bagh** (optional addition) — the garden across the Yamuna providing the classic postcard reflection shot, especially at sunset. Your guide times the visit to capture **morning golden-hour light** (best between 7:00–9:00 AM) for the most stunning photographs. For more on planning your Agra visit, see our <a href='/india/agra/taj-mahal-sunrise-tour'>Taj Mahal sunrise tour</a> page." }
    ];
  }

  // --- END DELHI TOUR FAQS BATCH 2 ---

  // --- DELHI TOUR FAQS BATCH 3 ---

  if (slug === 'delhi-private-4-day-golden-triangle-luxury-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What does the 4-day luxury Golden Triangle tour include?", answer: "The 4-day luxury Golden Triangle tour covers Delhi, Agra, and Jaipur in a premium format over 4 days and 3 nights: **Day 1 — Delhi** (Old Delhi, New Delhi, all UNESCO sites); **Day 2 — Agra** (Taj Mahal at sunrise, Agra Fort, Mehtab Bagh, optional Itmad-ud-Daula, Fatehpur Sikri en route to Jaipur); **Day 3 — Jaipur** (Amber Fort, City Palace, Jantar Mantar, Hawa Mahal, Jaipur bazaars); **Day 4 — Return to Delhi** or departure from Jaipur. Included: 3 nights at 5-star hotels (The Imperial Delhi, Oberoi Amarvilas Agra, Rambagh Palace Jaipur), private luxury vehicle throughout, senior guides in each city, all entry tickets, daily breakfasts, and curated dining recommendations." },
      { question: "What 5-star hotels are included in the luxury Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "The luxury Golden Triangle tour typically includes the finest properties in each city: **Delhi** — The Imperial (most prestigious colonial hotel in Delhi, Lutyens' zone), Taj Mahal Hotel, or Leela Palace New Delhi; **Agra** — Oberoi Amarvilas (the world's best Taj Mahal view hotel — every room has direct Taj Mahal views from a private balcony, consistently rated one of Asia's finest hotels); **Jaipur** — Rambagh Palace (a former royal palace of the Maharajas of Jaipur, now a Taj Hotels property, featuring impeccable Rajput architecture and gardens). This combination of the three finest heritage properties on the Golden Triangle circuit defines the luxury travel experience in north India." },
      { question: "Is the Taj Mahal visited at sunrise on the luxury Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "Yes — the sunrise Taj Mahal visit is a standard inclusion on the luxury Golden Triangle tour. Staying at the Oberoi Amarvilas in Agra means the Taj Mahal is literally visible from your room and balcony across the Yamuna, and the hotel arranges priority access. Your guide meets you at the Amarvilas shortly before opening time and accompanies you to the gate for the first-entry sunrise visit. The combination of waking up to a Taj Mahal view from your private balcony, followed by a guided sunrise walk through the monument, is the defining luxury travel experience of the Golden Triangle circuit." },
      { question: "How does the 4-day luxury tour differ from the 3-day standard tour?", answer: "The 4-day luxury version provides one extra full day compared to the 3-day standard tour, with all elements upgraded to luxury standard: (1) **Extra day** — allows more depth in each city (typically an extra morning in Agra for optional sites like Itmad-ud-Daula, or an afternoon at leisure); (2) **5-star hotels** vs. 3-star standard; (3) **Luxury vehicle** (Mercedes, BMW, or Innova Crysta Luxury vs. standard Innova); (4) **Senior specialist guides** with deeper expertise; (5) **Curated dining** at the finest restaurants in each city. The result is a fundamentally different quality of experience — immersive, unhurried, and commensurate with the extraordinary historical significance of the destinations." },
      { question: "Is a private guide provided for all 4 days of the luxury Golden Triangle?", answer: "Yes — senior Ministry of Tourism-licensed guides are provided in each city. The Delhi guide accompanies you for Day 1. The Agra guide (a specialist in Mughal history and Taj Mahal architecture) accompanies you for Day 2. The Jaipur guide (a specialist in Rajput history and Rajasthani culture) accompanies you for Day 3. Each guide is the best available in their city — selected specifically for the luxury tour based on expertise, communication, and experience with high-end international travellers. The luxury vehicle driver typically remains the same throughout all 4 days for continuity." },
      { question: "Is the 4-day luxury Golden Triangle available for couples?", answer: "The 4-day luxury Golden Triangle tour is one of the most popular honeymoon and anniversary itineraries for India. For couples: the Oberoi Amarvilas in Agra is consistently listed among the world's most romantic hotels, with Taj Mahal views from every room; the Rambagh Palace in Jaipur (a former royal palace) provides a fairytale setting for romantic dinners. Special arrangements can be made for honeymooners — room decorations, rose petal turndowns, champagne on arrival, private dinners in palace courtyards or on Agra rooftops with Taj Mahal views. Inform us of any honeymoon or anniversary celebration when booking." },
      { question: "What is the vehicle for the 4-day luxury Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "A luxury private vehicle is used throughout all 4 days — the same vehicle and chauffeur cover all intercity travel and local sightseeing. Standard vehicle for groups of 2–4: **Toyota Innova Crysta Luxury**, **Mercedes E-Class**, or **BMW 5 Series**. For groups of 5–6: **Toyota Alphard**, **Mercedes V-Class**, or **Land Cruiser Prado**. The vehicle is exclusively yours for all 4 days. Leather interior, Wi-Fi, USB charging, cold refreshments, and a chauffeur in professional uniform. All highway tolls and monument parking fees are included. Fuel costs are included in the tour price." },
      { question: "Can meals be included in the 4-day luxury Golden Triangle?", answer: "Daily breakfasts at the 5-star hotels are included. Lunches and dinners can be added to the package at a supplement for a fully all-inclusive experience. Recommended dining highlights: lunch at the Oberoi Amarvilas Agra with Taj Mahal views, dinner at Bukhara (ITC Maurya Delhi — consistently Asia's top Indian restaurant), and dinner at the Rambagh Palace Jaipur (fine Rajasthani cuisine in a palace courtyard). These dining experiences are as memorable as the monuments. Curated restaurant recommendations in each city are provided by your guide even for independently arranged meals." },
      { question: "Is there any flexibility to customize the 4-day luxury itinerary?", answer: "Yes — the luxury tour format is inherently flexible. All itinerary elements can be adjusted: additional sites substituted (Fatehpur Sikri for Itmad-ud-Daula, Nahargarh Fort added in Jaipur, Lodi Garden added in Delhi), pace adjusted (slower at preferred sites), hotel upgrades or downgrades, and special activities added (hot air balloon over Jaipur, elephant sanctuary visit, Abhaneri step-well, private heritage walk with a local academic). For corporate groups requiring team-building elements or conference facilities, Taj Hotels properties on this route all offer business amenities. Share your specific interests when booking for a tailored itinerary proposal." },
      { question: "Which luxury hotel brands are included in the 4-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "The 4-day luxury Golden Triangle tour partners with the **finest heritage and luxury hotel brands** across all three cities: **Delhi** — **The Imperial** (Delhi's most prestigious colonial-era hotel, located on Janpath in the heart of Lutyens' Delhi, home to an extraordinary private art collection), **Leela Palace New Delhi** (modern ultra-luxury with Lutyens-inspired architecture), or **Taj Mahal Hotel New Delhi** (Tata Group flagship property near India Gate). **Agra** — **Oberoi Amarvilas** (the signature property — every single room has an unobstructed **Taj Mahal view from a private balcony**, consistently ranked among Asia's top 10 luxury hotels; room rates start at approximately ₹35,000–50,000 per night), **ITC Mughal** (Mughal garden-inspired 5-star with extensive grounds and spa), or **Trident Agra** (Oberoi Group's premium tier with Taj-facing rooms). **Jaipur** — **Rambagh Palace** (the former **royal palace of the Maharajas of Jaipur**, converted to a Taj Hotels property with original royal suites, peacock gardens, and polo grounds), **Oberoi Rajvilas** (set in a 32-acre estate with private pool villas), or **Samode Haveli** (intimate heritage mansion in Jaipur's old city). Hotel selection can be customised to your preference and budget at booking. For planning your Delhi day, see our <a href='/india/delhi/delhi-full-day-guided-tour'>Delhi full-day guided tour</a> page." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'delhi-guided-shopping-tour-female-expert') {
    return [
      { question: "What does the Delhi guided shopping tour with a female expert cover?", answer: "The Delhi guided shopping tour with a female expert is specifically designed for travellers (especially women) who want to explore Delhi's extraordinary textile, craft, and jewellery markets with the guidance of a knowledgeable local female shopping specialist. The tour covers: **Lajpat Nagar** (Delhi's best fabric and textile market, where fashion designers source their materials), **Dilli Haat** (government-curated craft fair with artisans from all 36 Indian states, including block printing, weaving, and traditional jewellery), **Janpath** (government emporium lane with fixed-price authentic crafts), **Connaught Place** (upmarket jewellery and garment stores), and optionally **Sarojini Nagar** (the original designer surplus market with exceptional value). The female expert guide helps you identify authentic crafts, negotiate fair prices, and avoid tourist traps." },
      { question: "Why choose a female shopping guide for Delhi?", answer: "A female shopping guide provides several specific advantages in Delhi's markets: (1) **Gender comfort** — female travellers often find it easier to shop, negotiate, and explore market lanes with a female companion rather than a male guide; (2) **Shopping expertise** — female guides on this specific tour are selected for their genuine market knowledge, not just historical knowledge; they know which vendors are trustworthy, which fabrics are authentic, and which prices are fair; (3) **Tailoring and fitting** — a female guide can accompany you into fitting rooms when trying on garments and provide honest feedback on fit and style; (4) **Cultural navigation** — the guide explains the social customs of Delhi's markets (bargaining etiquette, what vendors expect, when to walk away)." },
      { question: "What crafts and products are best to buy in Delhi?", answer: "Delhi's markets offer India's greatest variety of authentic crafts: **Textiles** — block-printed fabrics from Jaipur (buy at source at Dilli Haat for fair prices), Banarasi silk (best quality from UP artisan stalls), and pashmina wool (beware fakes — your guide identifies authentic pashmina). **Jewellery** — Meenakari (Jaipur enamel work), kundan (Mughal royal jewellery style), and silver filigree. **Pottery** — blue pottery (Jaipur), black pottery (Manipur), and terracotta. **Papier-mâché** — Kashmir lacquerwork. **Shawls** — Kantha embroidered shawls from Bengal, Phulkari from Punjab. Your guide explains the origin and quality indicators for each craft, preventing you from buying inferior machine-made versions of what should be handmade artisan products." },
      { question: "Is this shopping tour suitable for non-shoppers?", answer: "The Delhi shopping tour is genuinely enjoyable even for travellers who do not consider themselves shoppers. The real experience is the cultural immersion: watching artisans at Dilli Haat demonstrate weaving, block printing, and miniature painting; understanding the economics of Indian handicraft production; and seeing the extraordinary diversity of Indian textile traditions from 36 different states in a single market. You can browse, observe, and learn without purchasing anything. Many 'non-shoppers' who join this tour are surprised by how engaging the craft education component is — and usually leave with at least a few small artisan-made items they would not have found independently." },
      { question: "What is Dilli Haat and why is it recommended?", answer: "Dilli Haat is a government-operated open-air crafts market in south Delhi that rotates artisans from all 36 Indian states (union territories included) on a monthly roster. At any visit, you can find genuine artisans — not middlemen or mass-produced imitations — demonstrating and selling crafts from their home regions. Prices are set by the artisans themselves (no aggressive bargaining culture here), products are authentic and often one-of-a-kind, and the cultural variety in a single market is extraordinary. Dilli Haat is specifically recommended for serious craft buyers over tourist trap markets because the source traceability is clear — you meet the artisan who made what you buy. Entry fee is approximately ₹100." },
      { question: "How long is the Delhi guided shopping tour?", answer: "The standard Delhi shopping tour with a female expert runs approximately **5–6 hours** — typically a half-day format (morning: 9:30 AM–2:00 PM, or afternoon: 2:00 PM–7:00 PM). This covers 3–4 markets with comfortable browsing time at each. A full-day shopping tour (9:30 AM–6:00 PM) covers additional markets (Khan Market, Mehrauli crafts area) and includes a lunch break. The half-day format is the most popular — it can be combined with a Delhi historical tour in the morning or afternoon, making a full Delhi day with both cultural and shopping content." },
      { question: "Does the female guide help with bargaining in Delhi's markets?", answer: "Yes — bargaining assistance is one of the most valuable services the female shopping guide provides. In markets like Lajpat Nagar and Janpath, bargaining is expected and the starting price can be 2–3x the fair price. Without local knowledge, tourists consistently overpay. Your guide knows the fair market price for every common product category, stays by your side during negotiations, and can either negotiate on your behalf (speaking in Hindi for better results) or coach you on when to push further and when the price is fair. At fixed-price government emporiums (Dilli Haat, the Central Cottage Industries Emporium), no bargaining occurs and prices are genuinely fair." },
      { question: "Is the Delhi shopping tour suitable for solo female travellers?", answer: "This tour is specifically designed to be the ideal Delhi experience for solo female travellers. Delhi can feel overwhelming for women travelling alone — the crowds, the navigation, and occasionally unwanted attention in crowded markets. A female guide provides immediate companionship, local knowledge, and a trusted companion for the entire experience. She knows which market lanes are safe, which vendors are reputable, and when and how to firmly decline unwanted approaches. Many solo female travellers who book this tour report it as the highlight of their Delhi visit — the combination of genuine local female friendship, craft education, and authentic market immersion is unique." },
      { question: "What is the best time of year for the Delhi shopping tour?", answer: "**October to March** is the best season for Delhi shopping — specifically: **November** (Diwali aftermath — artisan markets are fully stocked after the festival season), **December–January** (maximum variety of shawls, winter textiles, and craft fair schedules), and **February–March** (pleasant temperature for outdoor market walking). **Summer (April–June)** — markets are still operational but outdoor shopping becomes uncomfortable by 11 AM; morning sessions are manageable. **Monsoon (July–September)** — some outdoor market areas become muddy; Dilli Haat has covered sections. The guide schedules the tour to indoor or covered markets during the hottest part of any summer day." },
      { question: "What makes the female guide's perspective unique on the Delhi shopping tour?", answer: "A female shopping guide brings a distinctly different perspective that enriches the experience in ways a standard male guide typically cannot: (1) **Textile expertise** — female guides on this tour have **personal knowledge of Indian fabrics, weaves, and garment construction** gained through years of buying, wearing, and understanding these products, not just academic knowledge; they can feel a fabric and tell you whether the **pashmina is genuine** (real pashmina burns like hair, not plastic) or whether a **silk is machine-woven vs. handloom**; (2) **Cultural context** — a female guide explains the significance of specific textiles in **Indian women's lives** — wedding trousseaus, festival saris, daily wear hierarchies — providing cultural depth that transforms a shopping trip into an anthropological experience; (3) **Vendor relationships** — the female guides have built **trusted personal relationships** with specific women artisans and family-run stalls, giving you access to workshops and back rooms that male guides and independent tourists do not enter; (4) **Safety and comfort** — in crowded markets like Lajpat Nagar and Sarojini Nagar, a female companion provides a natural sense of security, and market vendors are notably **less aggressive in their sales tactics** when a local woman is present with you. For more on exploring Delhi, see our <a href='/india/delhi/old-new-delhi-guided-tour'>Old and New Delhi guided tour</a> page." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'delhi-agra-private-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What does the Delhi to Agra private tour include?", answer: "The Delhi to Agra private tour is a full-day excursion from Delhi covering the complete Agra experience: hotel pickup in Delhi at approximately 5:30–6:00 AM, 3–3.5 hour drive to Agra via the Yamuna Expressway, Taj Mahal with licensed guide (2–2.5 hours, all tickets included), Agra Fort with guide (1.5 hours, tickets included), sit-down lunch at a quality Agra restaurant, and return drive to Delhi arriving approximately 6:00–7:00 PM. The tour is 100% private — dedicated vehicle and guide for your group only, no shared participants, complete schedule flexibility. Mehtab Bagh or Itmad-ud-Daula can be added for visitors interested in more Agra monuments." },
      { question: "Is the Delhi-Agra private tour available for one person?", answer: "Yes — solo travellers can book the Delhi-Agra private tour. The private vehicle and guide are exclusively yours for the day regardless of group size. Per-person pricing for a solo traveller is higher than for groups (costs divided by one person), but the experience — one-on-one guide attention, flexible timing, complete personal schedule — is significantly superior to a shared group tour. If cost is the primary concern, enquire about our shared group tour option from Delhi to Agra, which allows participation at a significantly lower per-person rate by sharing costs with other travellers." },
      { question: "What is the best time to depart Delhi for the Agra private tour?", answer: "**5:30–6:00 AM departure from Delhi** is strongly recommended. This arrival time in Agra (approximately 9:00 AM) catches the Taj Mahal before the main tourist crowds arrive and in the best morning light. Departing later than 7 AM pushes Taj Mahal arrival past 10–10:30 AM — noticeably more crowded and hotter. For visitors who want to combine the Agra private tour with a Delhi half-day (visiting Old Delhi in the late afternoon on the return), a 6:30 AM departure is possible but the Taj Mahal experience is slightly less optimal. Earliest possible departure for a sunrise Taj Mahal experience from Delhi: 4:00–4:30 AM." },
      { question: "Is the Taj Mahal inner chamber visit included in the Delhi-Agra private tour?", answer: "Yes — the Taj Mahal inner mausoleum entry (₹200 for foreign nationals, in addition to the ₹1,300 main complex entry) is included in the tour price. The inner chamber contains the marble cenotaphs of Mumtaz Mahal and Shah Jahan, surrounded by an ornate carved marble jali screen with intricate Pietra Dura inlay work. Entry to the inner chamber is managed by ASI (Archaeological Survey of India) staff and limited to groups of approximately 20 at a time. Your guide ensures your group enters in a timely batch rather than waiting in the queue. Photography inside the inner chamber is restricted (no flash)." },
      { question: "Can the Delhi-Agra private tour end in Agra (one-way)?", answer: "Yes — the tour can be arranged as a one-way trip from Delhi to Agra (dropping you at your Agra hotel) or from Agra to Delhi (collecting you from your Agra hotel and returning to Delhi). This is useful for travellers whose itinerary has them arriving in India to Delhi and spending the first night in Delhi before proceeding to Agra, or for travellers on the Golden Triangle circuit who are finishing their circuit in Delhi. One-way pricing is lower than round-trip as it requires only one leg of vehicle use. Confirm whether you need a one-way or round-trip arrangement when booking." },
      { question: "What happens if the Taj Mahal is closed during the Delhi-Agra private tour?", answer: "The Taj Mahal is closed every **Friday** (for Islamic prayers) and occasionally for government events or VIP visits (rare, with little public notice). If you book on a Friday, your tour guide will redirect the day to Agra Fort, Mehtab Bagh, Itmad-ud-Daula, Fatehpur Sikri, and Sikandra — a full Agra day without the Taj Mahal but still extraordinarily rich in content. Confirm your visit date is not a Friday before booking. In the extremely rare case of a last-minute government closure, we reschedule to the next available date or provide a full refund for the missed monument." },
      { question: "Is the Yamuna Expressway used for the Delhi-Agra private tour?", answer: "Yes — all Delhi-Agra private tours use the **Yamuna Expressway (NH19)** — India's most modern expressway connecting the Delhi NCR with Agra. The expressway is 165 km, 6-lane, divided, with no intersections or traffic signals, modern crash barriers, and regular police patrols. Travel time is 3–3.5 hours depending on entry/exit traffic near Delhi and Agra. Toll charges (approximately ₹415 each way) are included in the tour price. The expressway is significantly faster and smoother than the older NH2 (through Mathura), which adds 45+ minutes and considerably more stress." },
      { question: "Can the Delhi-Agra private tour be extended to include Jaipur?", answer: "Yes — the Delhi-Agra private tour is the first leg of the [3-day Golden Triangle tour](/india/delhi/golden-triangle-3-day-tour-from-delhi). From Agra, the Golden Triangle continues to Jaipur (5-hour drive, passing through Fatehpur Sikri), making a logical extension that adds just 2 more days for a comprehensive three-city experience. Most travellers who do the Delhi-Agra private tour wish they had extended to Jaipur — Rajasthan's Pink City adds a completely different cultural and architectural dimension (Rajput vs. Mughal history) to the circuit. Enquire about extending your Agra day trip to the full Golden Triangle when booking." },
      { question: "What is the pickup and drop-off area for the Delhi-Agra private tour?", answer: "Hotel-to-hotel pickup and drop-off from anywhere in Delhi is included — Connaught Place area, South Delhi, Aerocity, Noida, or Gurgaon. Simply provide your hotel name and address when booking. For hotels near the Yamuna Expressway entry (Noida, Greater Noida) the total journey time to Agra may be slightly shorter. For hotels in north Delhi (Karol Bagh, Old Delhi area), allow an extra 20–30 minutes for the drive south to the expressway. The driver confirms exact pickup time the evening before based on your hotel's precise location." },
      { question: "What 5-star lunch restaurants are used on the Delhi-Agra private tour?", answer: "The standard Delhi-Agra private tour includes lunch at a **quality 4-star restaurant** in Agra. For travellers who prefer a **5-star dining upgrade**, the following premium restaurants are available at a supplement: (1) **Oberoi Amarvilas — Bellevue Restaurant** — fine dining with **direct Taj Mahal views** through floor-to-ceiling windows; North Indian and continental cuisine; the most exclusive lunch setting in Agra and arguably in India; expect to spend ₹3,000–5,000 per person. (2) **ITC Mughal — Peshawri Restaurant** — specialising in North-West Frontier cuisine (tandoor-grilled meats, dal Peshawri, naan) in an intimate rustic setting; a sister restaurant of the legendary Bukhara in Delhi. (3) **ITC Mughal — Taj Bano Restaurant** — Mughlai royal cuisine in a garden courtyard with Mughal architectural elements; dishes inspired by the imperial kitchen recipes of the Mughal emperors. (4) **Trident Agra — The Restaurant** — contemporary Indian and international menu with garden views; a lighter, more modern alternative. Your guide recommends the best option based on your cuisine preference and schedule. A 5-star lunch adds approximately **1–1.5 hours** to the Agra visit (vs. 45 minutes at the standard restaurant) but the experience is memorable. For more on the Agra experience, see our <a href='/india/agra/taj-mahal-sunrise-tour'>Taj Mahal sunrise tour</a> page." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-same-day-express-train-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "Which express train is used for the same-day Taj Mahal train tour from Delhi?", answer: "This tour uses the **Gatimaan Express** (trains 12049/12050) — India's fastest train operating at up to 160 km/h. The Gatimaan Express departs **Hazrat Nizamuddin station (Delhi) at 8:10 AM** and arrives at **Agra Cantonment at 9:50 AM** — just 1 hour 40 minutes. The return departs **Agra at 8:05 PM** arriving Delhi at 9:45 PM. An alternative is the **Shatabdi Express** (train 12001/12002), which departs New Delhi station at 6:00 AM and arrives Agra Cantonment at 8:40 AM — slightly slower (2h40m) but with an earlier arrival time, making it better for sunrise Taj Mahal visits. The tour specifies which train is used based on your timing preference." },
      { question: "How much time is available in Agra on the express train day tour?", answer: "**Gatimaan Express option:** Arrives Agra 9:50 AM, departs 8:05 PM — approximately **10 hours** in Agra. This is ample time for the Taj Mahal, Agra Fort, lunch, and optional additional sites (Mehtab Bagh, Itmad-ud-Daula). **Shatabdi Express option:** Arrives Agra 8:40 AM, departs approximately 6:30 PM — approximately **10 hours** also but with an earlier start allowing a better Taj Mahal morning experience. Both options provide more time in Agra than a car-based same-day trip (which typically allows 5–7 hours in Agra due to 3.5 hours each way driving)." },
      { question: "Are train tickets included in the same-day express train Taj Mahal tour?", answer: "Yes — round-trip train tickets are included in the tour price. For the Gatimaan Express, tickets are in **Executive Chair Car (EC)** class (premium, with in-seat meals service) or **AC Chair Car (CC)** (comfortable, air-conditioned, reserved seating). For the Shatabdi Express, tickets are in **Executive Chair Car** (the only class available on Shatabdi). EC class on both trains includes complimentary breakfast (morning journey) and snacks (return journey) served at your seat. The guide pre-purchases tickets before your travel date so boarding is seamless." },
      { question: "Is a guide included for sightseeing in Agra on the express train tour?", answer: "Yes — a Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide meets you at Agra Cantonment station upon your train's arrival and accompanies you for all Agra sightseeing. An AC vehicle (private car) is also pre-arranged at Agra station for transit between the station, Taj Mahal, Agra Fort, restaurant, and other sites. The guide manages all entry ticketing and logistics in Agra so you can step off the train and immediately begin sightseeing without any organization required. All entry tickets for the Taj Mahal (including inner mausoleum) and Agra Fort are included." },
      { question: "What is the difference between the Gatimaan Express and Shatabdi Express for the Agra trip?", answer: "**Gatimaan Express (12049):** India's fastest train (160 km/h), departs Delhi Hazrat Nizamuddin 8:10 AM, arrives Agra 9:50 AM (1h40m). More modern rolling stock. In-seat breakfast included. **Shatabdi Express (12001):** Established premium service, departs New Delhi 6:00 AM, arrives Agra 8:40 AM (2h40m). Earlier arrival — significantly better for a morning Taj Mahal experience. Also includes in-seat breakfast. **Best choice for Taj Mahal:** Shatabdi (earlier arrival, morning Taj Mahal in better light). **Best experience for the train journey itself:** Gatimaan (faster, newer). Your tour operator selects the optimal train based on your timing priorities." },
      { question: "What should I bring on the express train to Agra?", answer: "**Essential:** Your passport or national ID (required for ticket verification at Indian Railway stations and Taj Mahal entry), a light day bag, and your phone with the tour confirmation. **Recommended:** A change of clothes if you plan to visit a 5-star hotel restaurant in Agra, a small amount of Indian rupees for personal expenses (approximately ₹500–1,000), and a camera. **Not required:** Large luggage (leave at your Delhi hotel), food (breakfast and snacks are served in the train), or a separate travel guide (your Agra guide handles everything). The train journey is smooth and comfortable — no pre-journey stress." },
      { question: "Is the express train tour suitable for families with children?", answer: "Yes — the express train tour is an excellent choice for families with children. The train journey is an exciting experience for children (especially the Gatimaan Express at 160 km/h), and EC class seats are spacious enough for families with young children. The Agra sightseeing with a private guide and dedicated vehicle is more manageable than public transport or group tours for families. A private car in Agra (rather than walking between sites) allows quick breaks if children need rest. The Taj Mahal is genuinely fascinating for children of all ages — the guide can tailor the narrative with appropriate engagement for younger visitors." },
      { question: "How do I get to Hazrat Nizamuddin station from my Delhi hotel?", answer: "Your tour includes a private vehicle pickup from your Delhi hotel to **Hazrat Nizamuddin Railway Station (NZM)**. The driver typically picks you up approximately **90 minutes before the 8:10 AM Gatimaan departure** (so ~6:40 AM pickup). Station travel time from central Delhi hotels is 20–30 minutes. Your driver navigates directly to the station, assists with luggage, and helps you locate your platform and coach number. Hazrat Nizamuddin is a large station — arriving with your guide or driver ensures you find the correct coach without confusion." },
      { question: "What happens if the express train to Agra is delayed?", answer: "Indian Railways' premium trains (Gatimaan Express and Shatabdi Express) have a **punctuality rate above 90%**, and significant delays are uncommon. However, if a delay occurs, here is how the tour handles it: (1) **Minor delay (15–30 minutes)** — the Agra guide and vehicle wait at Agra Cantonment station; the itinerary is slightly compressed but all major sites are still covered; (2) **Major delay (1–2 hours)** — the guide adjusts the sightseeing sequence, prioritising the Taj Mahal and reducing time at secondary sites; lunch timing is shifted accordingly; (3) **Cancellation or extreme delay** — the tour operator arranges an alternative private vehicle transfer from Delhi to Agra (3.5 hours) so your Agra day proceeds by road; full train ticket refund is processed through Indian Railways. Your tour coordinator monitors train status from **5:00 AM on the travel day** and contacts you immediately if any disruption is detected. For more on planning your Delhi day, see our <a href='/india/delhi/delhi-1-day-itinerary'>Delhi 1-day itinerary</a> guide." },
      { question: "Is there luggage storage available on the express train tour?", answer: "Yes — luggage management is straightforward on this tour. **At your Delhi hotel:** leave large luggage at the hotel reception (all Delhi hotels provide free luggage storage for guests, even after checkout). Carry only a **small day bag** with essentials — passport, phone, camera, a light jacket, and sunscreen. **On the train:** Executive Chair Car has overhead luggage racks and under-seat storage sufficient for a day bag or small carry-on. **In Agra:** your private vehicle serves as a mobile luggage store — any bags travel in the vehicle boot while you sightsee at each monument. **At Agra station (return):** if you have a small bag, your guide assists with platform navigation and boarding. There are also **cloak rooms at Agra Cantonment station** (₹20–30 per item) if you need formal luggage storage, though this is rarely necessary for a day trip. For a comprehensive overview of planning your trip, see our <a href='/india/delhi/things-to-do-in-delhi'>things to do in Delhi</a> page." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'old-new-delhi-guided-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What is covered on the Old Delhi and New Delhi guided tour?", answer: "The Old and New Delhi guided tour covers the city's 3,000-year history in a single day across two distinct eras. **Old Delhi (Shahjahanabad, 17th-century Mughal city):** Jama Masjid (India's largest mosque, 1656), Red Fort (UNESCO Mughal fortress, 1648), Chandni Chowk bazaar (rickshaw ride), and Khari Baoli (Asia's largest spice wholesale market). **New Delhi (20th-century British Raj capital):** India Gate (1931 war memorial), Lutyens' ceremonial boulevard, Humayun's Tomb (UNESCO, 1570), and Qutub Minar (UNESCO, 1193). Optional additions: Lodi Garden, Lotus Temple, Akshardham Temple, and Indira Gandhi Memorial. Entry tickets, vehicle, and guide are all included." },
      { question: "Is this guided tour private or shared?", answer: "This is a private guided tour — your Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide and private air-conditioned vehicle are exclusively for your group throughout the day. There are no strangers, no shared schedule, and no compromise on pace or depth. This private format is particularly valuable in Delhi: the city is complex, the traffic requires an experienced driver, and the historical narrative spanning multiple dynasties (Delhi Sultanate → Mughal → British Raj → Independent India) requires a guide who can give your group undivided attention and adapt commentary to your specific interests and questions." },
      { question: "What is the Red Fort and is it worth visiting?", answer: "The Red Fort (Lal Qila) is the UNESCO-listed 17th-century Mughal palace fortress built by Emperor Shah Jahan between 1639 and 1648 as the seat of Mughal imperial power. Built in red sandstone (hence the name) with white marble palace interiors, it housed the Mughal court for over 200 years. Every year on Indian Independence Day (15 August), the Prime Minister addresses the nation from its ramparts. The fort is extensive (2 km perimeter) and contains several museums, audience halls, and palace structures. Your guide provides a curated 60–90 minute tour of the most significant structures — the complete fort would take half a day. Combined with Jama Masjid and Chandni Chowk, it forms the heart of the Old Delhi itinerary." },
      { question: "What is the Qutub Minar and why is it historically significant?", answer: "Qutub Minar is a 73-metre-tall tapering minaret built in 1193 by Qutb ud-Din Aibak, the founder of the Delhi Sultanate — making it one of the earliest surviving Islamic structures in India. It is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and the tallest brick minaret in the world. The surrounding Qutub complex contains the remains of India's first mosque (Quwwat ul-Islam, 'Might of Islam'), built using materials from 27 demolished Hindu and Jain temples (the pillars and carvings of which are still visible incorporated into the mosque's colonnade). This story — the collision of pre-Islamic and Islamic India visible in a single site — is one of the most historically charged narratives your guide covers on the New Delhi section." },
      { question: "What is Humayun's Tomb and how does it relate to the Taj Mahal?", answer: "Humayun's Tomb (1570) is the mausoleum of the Mughal Emperor Humayun, built by his Persian-born widow Haji Begum. It is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and architecturally crucial: it is the **direct prototype for the Taj Mahal**, built 61 years earlier. The same architectural vocabulary — a raised platform (char bagh garden), a domed mausoleum in the centre, the combination of red sandstone and white marble, and Persian-style arches — was refined and perfected at the Taj Mahal. Your guide at Humayun's Tomb explicitly connects the two monuments, making the subsequent Taj Mahal visit (if you are also going to Agra) architecturally richer. Humayun's Tomb is also the largest garden-tomb complex in India after the Taj Mahal." },
      { question: "How long does the Old and New Delhi guided tour take?", answer: "The guided tour typically runs **9–10 hours total** from hotel pickup (8:30–9:00 AM) to hotel drop-off (6:30–7:30 PM). Time allocation across sites: Jama Masjid (45 min), Red Fort area and Chandni Chowk rickshaw (60–75 min), Khari Baoli spice market (30 min), Humayun's Tomb (60–90 min), Qutub Minar (60 min), India Gate (30 min), and lunch (60 min). Transit between sites accounts for approximately 1.5–2 hours across the day. Optional additions (Lodi Garden, Lotus Temple) extend the tour but the core 7–8 sites are achievable in a full day without rushing." },
      { question: "Is this tour suitable for children?", answer: "Yes — the Old and New Delhi guided tour can be tailored effectively for families with children. Highlights that children typically find engaging: the Red Fort's scale and military architecture, the Chandni Chowk cycle-rickshaw ride (a favourite with children), the spice market's extraordinary colours and smells, and the Qutub Minar's sheer height. The guide adapts commentary for children — explaining Mughal emperors in terms of power, war, and court intrigue that children find naturally compelling. Bring snacks and water for children; the full-day format is demanding for young children and the guide will suggest rest stops and timing adjustments as needed." },
      { question: "Are entry tickets to all Delhi monuments included?", answer: "Yes — all monument entry tickets are included in the guided tour price: Red Fort (₹600 foreign nationals), Humayun's Tomb (₹600), and Qutub Minar (₹600). Total included ticket value for a foreign national is ₹1,800. The Jama Masjid has no fixed entry fee for the main complex (optional ₹300 fee to climb the minaret for views). India Gate is free. Khari Baoli spice market and Chandni Chowk are public spaces with no entry fee. Children under 15 enter all ASI monuments for free. No additional payments are required at any monument gate during the tour." },
      { question: "Is it safe to eat street food during the Old and New Delhi guided tour?", answer: "Old Delhi is widely regarded as **India's street food capital**, and trying local specialties is one of the tour's highlights — but food safety awareness is important. Your guide follows these principles: (1) **Vendor selection** — the guide only recommends stalls with **high turnover** (fresh preparation, not sitting out), visible cooking processes, and long-established reputations (many Old Delhi vendors have operated for 3–4 generations); (2) **Cooked over raw** — freshly fried, grilled, or boiled items (jalebi, samosa, paratha, chai) are safer than raw salads or cut fruit; (3) **Water discipline** — drink only **sealed bottled water** (provided on the tour), never tap water or ice from street vendors; (4) **Moderation** — the guide suggests small tastings across multiple stalls rather than a full meal at one street vendor. Highlights include **Paranthe Wali Gali** (century-old stuffed bread lane), **Karim's** (Mughal-descended cooking since 1913), and famous **jalebi** and **rabri** stalls near Jama Masjid. For more tips on navigating Delhi, see our <a href='/india/delhi/delhi-travel-guide-2026'>Delhi travel guide</a>." },
      { question: "What is the cycle-rickshaw ride in Chandni Chowk like?", answer: "The **cycle-rickshaw ride through Chandni Chowk** is one of the most vivid and memorable experiences on the guided tour. You board a traditional pedal-powered rickshaw near the Red Fort or Jama Masjid and ride through the **narrow 17th-century bazaar lanes** for approximately **30–45 minutes**. The experience is sensory overload in the best way: the silver jewellery lane (Dariba Kalan), wedding decoration shops (Kinari Bazaar), wholesale spice stalls (Khari Baoli), and iconic sweet makers all pass at walking pace. The rickshaw-wallah navigates expertly through lanes barely **3 metres wide**, dodging pedestrians, handcarts, and other rickshaws. Your guide either rides alongside in a second rickshaw or walks next to you, providing running commentary on the history of each lane. **Safety:** rickshaws move slowly (walking speed) so the ride is gentle and safe; hold bags on your lap and keep cameras secured. **Tipping:** a tip of **₹50–100** for the rickshaw-wallah is customary and appreciated. For a complete overview of Delhi attractions, see our <a href='/india/delhi/delhi-full-day-guided-tour'>Delhi full-day guided tour</a> page." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'golden-triangle-tour-delhi-agra-jaipur') {
    return [
      { question: "What cities does the Golden Triangle Delhi-Agra-Jaipur tour cover?", answer: "The Golden Triangle covers India's three most visited historical cities in a connected loop: **Delhi** — the capital, home to Mughal and British Raj monuments, Old Delhi's 17th-century bazaars, and three UNESCO World Heritage Sites (Red Fort, Humayun's Tomb, Qutub Minar); **Agra** — home of the Taj Mahal (one of the world's most iconic monuments), Agra Fort (second UNESCO site), and the Baby Taj; **Jaipur** — the 'Pink City' of Rajasthan, home to Amber Fort (third UNESCO site), City Palace, Hawa Mahal, Jantar Mantar, and the crafts and textile culture of Rajasthan. The three cities form a triangle approximately 200 km apart, making a 3–5 day circuit logical and highly efficient." },
      { question: "How many days is the Golden Triangle Delhi-Agra-Jaipur tour?", answer: "This Golden Triangle tour runs over **4 days / 3 nights** — the most balanced version of the circuit that avoids the excessive rushing of the 3-day version while not extending to the full 5 or 6 days. Day 1: Delhi (full day). Day 2: Drive to Agra (3.5 hours), afternoon/evening in Agra, overnight. Day 3: Taj Mahal sunrise, full Agra sightseeing, drive to Jaipur (5 hours via Fatehpur Sikri). Day 4: Full Jaipur day. Return to Delhi on Day 4 evening (5 hours) or fly from Jaipur. The 4-day format allows one full sightseeing day in each city plus travel days, with the Agra overnight enabling the essential sunrise Taj Mahal visit." },
      { question: "What is included in the Golden Triangle Delhi-Agra-Jaipur tour?", answer: "Included: all intercity and local transportation in a private air-conditioned vehicle, Ministry of Tourism-licensed guides in Delhi, Agra, and Jaipur, 3 nights hotel accommodation (1 Delhi, 1 Agra, 1 Jaipur — hotel standard specified at booking), all monument entry tickets across all three cities (Red Fort, Humayun's Tomb, Qutub Minar, Taj Mahal + inner mausoleum, Agra Fort, Amber Fort, City Palace, Jantar Mantar), and daily breakfasts. Lunches and dinners are not included in the standard package but can be added. All tours are 100% private — no shared groups." },
      { question: "Is the Golden Triangle tour good value compared to booking independently?", answer: "A Golden Triangle tour package consistently offers better value than independent booking for most travellers: the guide fees, vehicle hire, entry ticket management, hotel coordination, and route planning are all handled for you. For first-time India visitors specifically, the logistical complexity of independently organizing 3 cities, multiple monuments, and intercity transport across 4 days in India is significant. Tour packages also provide a single point of contact for any issue that arises. Independent booking can be marginally cheaper for experienced India travellers who are comfortable managing logistics, but for most, the convenience, quality, and time-saving justify the package price." },
      { question: "Is Fatehpur Sikri included in the Delhi-Agra-Jaipur Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "Yes — Fatehpur Sikri is typically included as a stop on the Agra-to-Jaipur drive (Day 3). The UNESCO-listed abandoned Mughal city is exactly on the route between Agra and Jaipur (40 km from Agra, en route to the Jaipur highway). The visit takes approximately 1.5–2 hours with a guide. Akbar's complete 16th-century imperial capital — abandoned mysteriously just 14 years after construction — includes the Jama Masjid with the grand Buland Darwaza (the largest mosque gateway in the world), the Panch Mahal (a 5-storey palace tower), and Jodha Bai's Palace. Entry is included in the tour price." },
      { question: "What time of year is best for the Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "**October to March** is the ideal season, with October–November and February–March being the most pleasant (mild temperatures, clear skies, minimal dust). **December–January** is peak tourist season with the most comfortable daytime temperatures (18–28°C) but can bring morning fog in Delhi and Agra. **April–June** is increasingly hot (38–46°C) — feasible but demanding; start sightseeing early. **July–September** (monsoon): green, humid, and occasionally dramatic — Taj Mahal in monsoon light is extraordinary for photographers; outdoor sightseeing can be disrupted by heavy rain. The Golden Triangle can be done year-round; October–March simply offers the most comfortable conditions." },
      { question: "Can I add a tiger safari to the Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "Yes — **Ranthambore National Park** (Bengal tiger safari) is located between Agra and Jaipur (approximately 180 km from Agra, 160 km from Jaipur) and is the most popular Golden Triangle extension. Adding 2 nights at Ranthambore extends the tour to a 6-day circuit: Delhi → Agra → Ranthambore (2 nights, tiger safaris morning and afternoon) → Jaipur → Delhi. Ranthambore has one of India's highest tiger sighting rates — mornings in a private open Gypsy jeep with a naturalist guide offer extraordinary wildlife experiences. See our [Ranthambore full-day tour](/india/jaipur/ranthambore-full-day-tour) for details." },
      { question: "How do I travel between Delhi, Agra, and Jaipur on the Golden Triangle?", answer: "All intercity travel on this tour is in a **private air-conditioned vehicle** — the same vehicle and driver for the entire circuit. Delhi to Agra: 3–3.5 hours via Yamuna Expressway. Agra to Jaipur: 4.5–5 hours via NH21 (passing Fatehpur Sikri). Jaipur to Delhi: 5 hours via NH48 (National Highway). Total driving across the circuit: approximately 12–13 hours over 4 days. All highway tolls and monument parking fees are included. The vehicle is your private mobile base throughout — the driver manages navigation and parking while the guide manages sightseeing." },
      { question: "Is the Golden Triangle tour suitable for senior travellers?", answer: "Yes — the Golden Triangle is one of India's most senior-friendly itineraries because: (1) it uses private vehicles door-to-door; (2) major monuments (Taj Mahal, Amber Fort) have golf buggy services for mobility-impaired visitors; (3) 4-star hotels are standard, with good amenities; (4) 4 days provides a comfortable pace — not rushed. The main challenges for senior travellers are heat (April–October: start sightseeing before 9 AM) and uneven cobblestone surfaces at some monuments. The guide always knows the most accessible routes through each monument and arranges buggy service when relevant. Inform us of any mobility requirements when booking." },
      { question: "Is 3 days enough to cover all 3 cities on the Golden Triangle?", answer: "A **3-day Golden Triangle** is feasible but demanding — it covers all headline monuments across Delhi, Agra, and Jaipur at a fast pace with significant daily driving. Here is a realistic assessment: **Day 1 — Delhi:** a compressed half-day covering Humayun's Tomb, Qutub Minar, India Gate, and a brief Old Delhi drive-through (no time for a full Chandni Chowk rickshaw ride or Red Fort interior). **Day 2 — Agra:** early morning departure from Delhi (5:30 AM), Taj Mahal and Agra Fort, then a 5-hour drive to Jaipur via a brief Fatehpur Sikri stop. **Day 3 — Jaipur:** Amber Fort, City Palace, and Hawa Mahal, then 5-hour return drive to Delhi. **The honest verdict:** 3 days covers the must-see monuments but leaves **no time for cultural immersion** — no Old Delhi food walks, no Jaipur bazaar browsing, no Agra sunset at Mehtab Bagh, and no breathing room. **4 days** is the minimum recommended duration for a satisfying experience, and **5–6 days** is ideal for genuine immersion. If you only have 3 days available, prioritise Agra (Taj Mahal) and one other city rather than rushing all three. For a detailed Delhi-only itinerary option, see our <a href='/india/delhi/delhi-1-day-itinerary'>Delhi 1-day itinerary</a> guide." }
    ];
  }

  // --- END DELHI TOUR FAQS BATCH 3 ---

  // --- DELHI TOUR FAQS BATCH 4 (FINAL DELHI) ---

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-sunrise-elephant-conservation-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What is the elephant conservation element of this Taj Mahal tour?", answer: "The elephant conservation component of this tour is a visit to an ethical elephant sanctuary near Agra where retired working elephants live in a protected, humane environment. Unlike elephant riding attractions (which Asia by Locals does not endorse), this sanctuary focuses on elephant welfare, rehabilitation, and education. Visitors observe and interact with elephants in their natural resting environment — feeding, bathing, and walking alongside them under the supervision of their long-term mahouts (caretakers). The tour provides direct revenue support to the sanctuary, which is otherwise funded through conservation donations. The combination of a Taj Mahal sunrise visit and an ethical elephant experience creates a uniquely meaningful day in Agra." },
      { question: "Is elephant riding offered at the elephant conservation sanctuary?", answer: "No — this tour specifically partners with sanctuaries that do not offer elephant riding. Elephant riding involves training practices that cause significant distress to elephants, and Asia by Locals does not support or promote this activity. The ethical elephant experience offered on this tour involves observing elephants in a semi-natural habitat, feeding them (fruits and sugarcane), watching them bathe in water channels, and learning about their histories, personalities, and conservation status from their mahouts and sanctuary staff. This interaction is rewarding precisely because it involves no exploitation — elephants engage willingly because they are not being forced." },
      { question: "What is the Taj Mahal sunrise part of this tour?", answer: "The tour begins with a **Taj Mahal sunrise visit** — the single best time to experience the monument. Your group arrives at the Taj Mahal gate approximately 30 minutes before opening (5:30–6:00 AM depending on season). A Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide provides complete historical and architectural commentary for approximately 2–2.5 hours inside the complex, covering the complete monument in the soft gold morning light before the main crowds arrive. All Taj Mahal entry tickets (main complex + inner mausoleum) are included. After the sunrise session (complete by approximately 8:30 AM), a hot breakfast is served before the journey to the elephant sanctuary." },
      { question: "Is the elephant sanctuary near Agra?", answer: "Yes — the elephant sanctuary is located in the Agra region, typically 30–60 minutes from the Taj Mahal by private vehicle. Exact location varies by which sanctuary is partnered — verified ethical sanctuaries in the Agra district and surrounding area are used based on current welfare standards and availability. The tour includes all vehicle transport between the Taj Mahal, breakfast venue, elephant sanctuary, and return to your hotel or Delhi. Agra Fort can be added between the Taj Mahal visit and the elephant sanctuary for visitors who want to complete the standard Agra monument circuit." },
      { question: "How long is the elephant conservation visit?", answer: "The ethical elephant interaction session typically runs **2–3 hours** at the sanctuary: an orientation from the mahout about the elephant's history and care requirements (30 minutes), a guided walk alongside the elephant through the sanctuary (45 minutes), the feeding experience (sugarcane, bananas, pumpkins — 30 minutes), optional elephant bathing observation (30 minutes), and a brief education session on Asian elephant conservation status, threats, and how the sanctuary supports local communities (30 minutes). The unhurried, intimate format means you leave with a genuine understanding of and connection to these extraordinary animals rather than a transactional tourism experience." },
      { question: "What is the full itinerary for the Taj Mahal sunrise elephant conservation tour?", answer: "**5:00 AM** — Hotel pickup from Delhi or Agra. **6:00–8:30 AM** — Taj Mahal sunrise guided visit (all tickets included). **8:30–9:30 AM** — Breakfast at a quality Agra café or restaurant (included). **9:30–10:00 AM** — Drive to elephant sanctuary. **10:00 AM–12:30 PM** — Elephant conservation experience (feeding, walking, bathing observation, conservation education). **12:30–1:30 PM** — Lunch at a quality restaurant (included). **1:30 PM onward** — Return to hotel or optional Agra Fort visit (additional). Return to Delhi if applicable: approximately 5–6 PM arrival." },
      { question: "Is the tour suitable for children?", answer: "Yes — the combination of the Taj Mahal and an ethical elephant interaction is particularly memorable for children. Children are naturally fascinated by elephants, and the opportunity to feed and walk alongside them (with full safety supervision from experienced mahouts) creates a lasting childhood memory. The guide calibrates the Taj Mahal commentary for young visitors (the scale, the love story, the construction time of 22 years). Age recommendation for the elephant interaction: 5 years and above with parental supervision. Children under 12 must remain with a parent or guardian throughout the elephant interaction. The elephants in ethical sanctuaries are accustomed to visitors and are calm and gentle." },
      { question: "Are all costs included in the elephant conservation Taj Mahal tour?", answer: "Included in the tour price: hotel pickup and drop-off (Agra or Delhi), private air-conditioned vehicle throughout, Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide, all Taj Mahal entry tickets (main complex + inner mausoleum), elephant sanctuary entry and interaction fees, breakfast, and lunch. Not included: Agra Fort entry (if added, ₹650 for foreign nationals), personal purchases from the sanctuary's conservation gift shop, and tips for the guide, driver, and mahout (recommended). The sanctuary visit fee is fully allocated to elephant welfare and mahout salaries — your visit makes a direct conservation contribution." },
      { question: "What ethical practices does the elephant sanctuary follow?", answer: "The elephant sanctuaries partnered with this tour adhere to strict ethical standards verified by Asia by Locals: (1) **No riding** — elephants are never ridden by tourists, as the howdah (seat) and sustained weight cause spinal damage over time; (2) **No chains** — elephants roam freely within the sanctuary compound and are not chained except during brief veterinary procedures; (3) **No performance** — elephants are not trained to perform tricks, paint, or engage in any forced behaviour; (4) **Proper nutrition** — each elephant receives **200–250 kg of fresh fodder daily** including sugarcane, bananas, pumpkins, and seasonal grasses, supervised by a veterinarian; (5) **Mahout welfare** — the sanctuary ensures mahouts receive **fair wages, housing, and healthcare**, recognising that ethical elephant care requires ethical human employment; (6) **Veterinary oversight** — a qualified veterinarian conducts regular health checks, foot care, and dental monitoring. Revenue from tourist visits directly funds these welfare standards. For more on ethical experiences in the Agra area, see our <a href='/india/agra/taj-mahal-sunrise-tour'>Taj Mahal sunrise tour</a> page." },
      { question: "Can I combine the elephant conservation tour with an Agra Fort visit?", answer: "Yes — adding **Agra Fort** to the elephant conservation Taj Mahal tour is a popular and highly recommended extension. The typical combined itinerary is: **6:00–8:30 AM** — Taj Mahal sunrise guided visit; **8:30–9:30 AM** — breakfast; **9:30–11:00 AM** — Agra Fort guided visit (1.5 hours); **11:00–11:30 AM** — drive to elephant sanctuary; **11:30 AM–2:00 PM** — elephant conservation experience; **2:00–3:00 PM** — lunch; **3:00 PM onward** — return to hotel or Delhi. Agra Fort is the **UNESCO-listed 16th-century Mughal fortress** where Emperor Shah Jahan was imprisoned by his son Aurangzeb for 8 years — from the Musamman Burj tower, Shah Jahan could see the Taj Mahal (built for his beloved wife Mumtaz) in the distance, making the two monuments emotionally inseparable. Agra Fort entry (₹650 for foreign nationals) is charged as an additional fee. The combined tour adds approximately **2 hours** to the overall day. For full entry details, see our <a href='/india/agra/taj-mahal-entry-ticket'>Taj Mahal entry ticket</a> information page." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === '5-days-golden-triangle-tour-from-delhi') {
    return [
      { question: "What does the 5-day Golden Triangle tour from Delhi cover?", answer: "The 5-day Golden Triangle tour from Delhi covers the classic three cities (Delhi, Agra, Jaipur) with the additional time needed for proper immersion in each: **Day 1 — Delhi** (Old Delhi, New Delhi, UNESCO Heritage sites); **Day 2 — Agra** (Taj Mahal at sunrise, Agra Fort, Mehtab Bagh, optional Baby Taj); **Day 3 — Agra/Fatehpur Sikri/Jaipur** (morning at leisure in Agra, Fatehpur Sikri visit en route, evening arrival Jaipur); **Day 4 — Jaipur** (Amber Fort, City Palace, Jantar Mantar, Hawa Mahal, Jaipur bazaars); **Day 5 — Return to Delhi** (optional Nahargarh Fort morning, afternoon drive to Delhi). The extra 2 days vs. the 3-day version transform rushed monument-ticking into genuine cultural immersion." },
      { question: "How is the 5-day Golden Triangle different from the 3-day version?", answer: "The 3-day Golden Triangle visits all headline sites at a fast pace: essentially one city per day with heavy driving. The 5-day version provides breathing room in each destination: Agra gets a sunrise Taj Mahal visit + afternoon at leisure (visit a marble inlay workshop, explore Agra's bazaar); Fatehpur Sikri gets a full guided 2-hour visit rather than a rushed stop; Jaipur gets a full day for all major sites plus time for the bazaars and optional Nahargarh Fort sunset views. For most travellers, the 5-day version is the optimal balance between efficiency (covering all three cities) and depth (enough time to absorb each destination). The 3-day version feels rushed in retrospect." },
      { question: "Is the Taj Mahal visited at sunrise on the 5-day tour?", answer: "Yes — the sunrise Taj Mahal visit is included on Day 2. Staying in Agra overnight (Day 2) means you are in position for the 5:30–6:00 AM gate opening. This is the fundamental advantage of the 5-day format over same-day Delhi-to-Agra day trips: arriving the previous evening and staying overnight means the Taj Mahal visit begins at peak time (sunrise) in the best light and minimum crowds. The 5-day tour specifically builds in the overnight Agra stay to make this possible. On Day 2, after the sunrise session (complete by 9 AM), you have the rest of the morning for Agra Fort and the afternoon at leisure." },
      { question: "Is Fatehpur Sikri visited on the 5-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "Yes — Fatehpur Sikri is included as a dedicated 2-hour stop on Day 3 (between Agra and Jaipur). This UNESCO World Heritage Site — Akbar the Great's completely preserved 16th-century imperial capital, abandoned just 14 years after completion — is one of India's most compelling historical sites. The guide examines the mystery of its abandonment on location, showing physical evidence in the city's incomplete infrastructure that suggests a more complex reason than the officially stated water shortage. With 2 dedicated hours (vs. a rushed 45-minute group tour stop), you experience Fatehpur Sikri properly: the Jama Masjid, Buland Darwaza, Diwan-i-Am, Panch Mahal, and Jodha Bai's Palace." },
      { question: "What hotel standard is included in the 5-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "The standard 5-day tour includes 3-star to 4-star accommodation: a comfortable business hotel in Delhi, a heritage-adjacent property with Taj-view potential in Agra, and a well-located heritage haveli or city hotel in Jaipur. Upgrade packages to 4-star or 5-star are available: notable upgrades include the Oberoi Amarvilas in Agra (every room with Taj Mahal view) and Rambagh Palace (former Maharaja's palace) in Jaipur. The 5-day format makes the hotel experience more meaningful — extra nights mean you spend real time at each property rather than simply sleeping there." },
      { question: "Can I extend the 5-day Golden Triangle to include a tiger safari?", answer: "Yes — adding Ranthambore National Park extends the tour to **7 days** and is the most popular Golden Triangle extension. Ranthambore (between Agra and Jaipur, approximately 180 km from Agra) is India's most accessible tiger reserve with a high sighting rate. Two days at Ranthambore (4 jeep safaris: 2 morning, 2 afternoon) significantly increases the probability of tiger sightings. See our [Ranthambore full-day tour](/india/jaipur/ranthambore-full-day-tour) for details. The complete Delhi-Agra-Ranthambore-Jaipur-Delhi circuit is one of India's best-value multi-day itineraries combining culture, history, and wildlife." },
      { question: "Are all meals included in the 5-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "Daily **breakfasts** at hotels are included for all 4 nights. Lunches and dinners can be added as an all-inclusive supplement for complete hassle-free pricing, or arranged independently at your guide's restaurant recommendations each day. Most travellers prefer the independent meal approach for dinners in particular — your guide recommends the best local restaurants in each city, giving you authentic options at all price points rather than being limited to tour-approved venues. If you want complete peace of mind without any daily financial management, the all-inclusive meal supplement is available when booking." },
      { question: "What is the driving schedule for the 5-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "**Day 1:** Delhi sightseeing (local vehicle, no long drive). **Day 2:** Delhi hotel to Agra — 3.5 hours morning drive (pickup ~5:30 AM to arrive Agra ~9:00 AM for Taj Mahal). **Day 3:** Agra to Jaipur via Fatehpur Sikri — 5.5–6 hours total including 2-hour Fatehpur Sikri stop. **Day 4:** Jaipur local sightseeing (no long drive). **Day 5:** Jaipur to Delhi — 5 hours afternoon drive (return to Delhi ~7:30 PM). Total long-distance driving: approximately 14 hours over 5 days. In a comfortable private air-conditioned vehicle, this is very manageable — no back-to-back long days, and Day 4 is entirely local." },
      { question: "Can I upgrade the hotels on the 5-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "Yes — hotel upgrades are available at every level for the 5-day Golden Triangle tour. **Standard (included):** 3–4 star business or heritage hotels in each city. **4-star upgrade:** well-known branded properties such as Radisson, Courtyard by Marriott, or ITC WelcomHotel — a meaningful step up in room quality, breakfast buffet, and facilities. **5-star luxury upgrade:** the finest properties on the circuit — **The Imperial or Leela Palace** in Delhi, **Oberoi Amarvilas** in Agra (every room has a direct Taj Mahal view from a private balcony), and **Rambagh Palace** in Jaipur (former royal palace of the Maharajas, now a Taj Hotels property). The 5-star upgrade transforms the 5-day tour into an ultra-premium experience where the hotels themselves become highlights. Upgrade pricing is quoted per city, so you can mix levels — for example, 4-star in Delhi and Jaipur with 5-star Oberoi Amarvilas in Agra for the Taj Mahal view. For more on planning your Delhi leg, see our <a href='/india/delhi/delhi-full-day-guided-tour'>Delhi full-day guided tour</a> page." },
      { question: "Are there shopping opportunities during the 5-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "Yes — the 5-day Golden Triangle provides excellent shopping opportunities in all three cities, and the extra time (vs. a 3-day tour) means you can browse without rushing: **Delhi** — Dilli Haat (government-curated artisan market with crafts from all Indian states), Chandni Chowk (silver, textiles, spices), Khan Market (upmarket boutiques), and the Central Cottage Industries Emporium (fixed-price authentic handicrafts). **Agra** — **marble inlay workshops** (Pietra Dura, the same technique used on the Taj Mahal), leather goods (Agra is India's leather capital), and Mughal miniature paintings. **Jaipur** — the shopping highlight of the circuit: **block-printed textiles** (Sanganer and Bagru prints), **blue pottery** (a Jaipur speciality), **kundan and Meenakari jewellery** (Rajasthani royal jewellery traditions), **gemstones** (Jaipur is India's gem-cutting capital), and **lac bangles** from the old city bazaars. Your guide in each city recommends **trusted vendors with fair fixed prices** and helps you avoid tourist-trap overcharging. See our <a href='/india/jaipur/amber-fort-official-guided-tour'>Amber Fort guided tour</a> page for more on Jaipur's heritage." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'old-new-delhi-private-half-day-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What does the Old and New Delhi private half-day tour cover?", answer: "The private half-day tour of Old and New Delhi covers the most essential highlights of each area in approximately 4–5 hours: **Old Delhi** — Jama Masjid (India's largest mosque, exterior and courtyard), the Chandni Chowk bazaar (cycle-rickshaw ride through the historic lanes), and a glimpse of the Red Fort exterior and forecourt; **New Delhi** — India Gate (the iconic 1931 Raj-era war memorial), Humayun's Tomb (UNESCO Heritage, 1570, architectural predecessor to the Taj Mahal), and Qutub Minar (UNESCO Heritage, 12th century). The half-day format prioritizes the most significant sites over comprehensive coverage, making it ideal for visitors with limited time in Delhi." },
      { question: "Is this half-day tour private — just for my group?", answer: "Yes — this is a 100% private half-day tour. Your Ministry of Tourism-licensed guide and private air-conditioned vehicle are exclusively assigned to your group for the entire duration. No other visitors share the vehicle, the guide, or the itinerary. This private format ensures the guide's full attention, your preferred pace, and complete schedule flexibility — even on a half-day tour. If you want to spend 45 minutes at Humayun's Tomb instead of the standard 30, the guide adapts without compromising the remaining itinerary." },
      { question: "How long is the private Delhi half-day tour?", answer: "The private half-day Delhi tour runs approximately **4–5 hours** from hotel pickup to hotel drop-off. Morning tours (8:30 AM–1:00–1:30 PM) cover Old Delhi in the cooler morning and New Delhi sites in the late morning. Afternoon tours (2:00 PM–6:30–7:00 PM) cover New Delhi sites in good afternoon light, with Humayun's Tomb and Qutub Minar looking excellent in warm late-afternoon sunlight. A full-day tour (9 hours) allows more comprehensive coverage of both areas — if your schedule permits, the full-day version is recommended for first-time Delhi visitors who want thorough coverage." },
      { question: "Is the cycle-rickshaw ride through Chandni Chowk included in the half-day tour?", answer: "Yes — a cycle-rickshaw ride through Chandni Chowk's historic bazaar lanes is included in the half-day tour and is one of the most vivid urban experiences in India. Even in a 25–30 minute ride, you see the specialized trade lanes (jewellery, textiles, spices, sweets), the 17th-century Mughal street layout designed by Shah Jahan's daughter, and the extraordinary sensory environment of one of Asia's oldest commercial districts. The guide accompanies the rickshaw (either riding alongside or walking) and provides commentary on the specific lane, vendor, and historical context of what you are passing." },
      { question: "Are entry tickets included in the half-day Delhi private tour?", answer: "Yes — monument entry tickets are included for the sites that require them: Red Fort exterior viewing area (₹600 if entering the fort complex), Humayun's Tomb (₹600 for foreign nationals), and Qutub Minar (₹600 for foreign nationals). Jama Masjid main courtyard has no mandatory entry fee. India Gate is free. The Chandni Chowk rickshaw area is a public space. Total included ticket value for a foreign national visiting Humayun's Tomb and Qutub Minar: ₹1,200. Children under 15 enter all ASI monuments for free." },
      { question: "Is the half-day Delhi tour suitable for a transit day or layover?", answer: "Yes — the private half-day Delhi tour is specifically ideal for transit passengers with a long Delhi layover. With 5–7+ hours between flights, a half-day tour allows you to cover Delhi's most significant monuments and one of Asia's most atmospheric bazaars before returning to the airport. The private vehicle means you can request drop-off directly at the airport (Terminal 2 domestic or Terminal 3 international) at the end of the tour. Delhi's Indira Gandhi International Airport is approximately 45 minutes from central Delhi's monument areas. The guide can advise on the latest hotel pickup time based on your flight departure." },
      { question: "What is the best time of day for the half-day Delhi private tour?", answer: "**Morning (8:30 AM–1:00 PM)** is recommended for the Old Delhi section first — Chandni Chowk and the Jama Masjid area are most energetic in the morning. **Afternoon (2:00–7:00 PM)** suits visitors who prefer more time for lunch before starting. For photography: **morning light** is excellent for the Chandni Chowk lanes; **afternoon-to-sunset light** is excellent for Humayun's Tomb (warm golden tones on the red sandstone facade) and Qutub Minar. **Avoid midday (11 AM–1 PM)** for outdoor sightseeing in summer months — temperatures peak. The guide selects the optimal sequence within your chosen time window." },
      { question: "Can the half-day tour be extended to a full day?", answer: "Yes — extending from a half-day to a full-day Delhi tour adds comprehensive coverage of the remaining sites: Khari Baoli (Asia's largest spice wholesale market), Lodi Garden (Mughal and pre-Mughal tombs in a beautiful park), Hauz Khas village (medieval water reservoir with contemporary cafes), and optionally the Lotus Temple or Akshardham Temple. The full-day tour (9–10 hours) provides the most complete Delhi experience possible in a single day. If you have the time available, the full day is highly recommended — Delhi's historical depth rewards more time rather than less." },
      { question: "Which half-day slot is best for photography in Delhi?", answer: "For photography enthusiasts, the **afternoon half-day (2:00–7:00 PM)** produces the most stunning results. The reason is light quality: **Humayun's Tomb** — the red sandstone and white marble facade glows in warm golden tones during late afternoon (4:00–5:30 PM), creating the most photogenic conditions for this UNESCO monument; **Qutub Minar** — the 73-metre sandstone tower is beautifully side-lit in the afternoon, with long shadows adding depth and drama; **India Gate** — at sunset (5:30–6:30 PM depending on season), the war memorial is bathed in warm light and the surrounding gardens fill with locals creating an atmospheric street photography scene. The **morning half-day (8:30 AM–1:00 PM)** is better for **Chandni Chowk and Old Delhi street photography** — the bazaar lanes are most active and photogenic before noon, with dramatic light shafts cutting through the narrow alleys. If photography is your primary interest, discuss this with your guide at pickup so the sequence is optimised for the best light at each site. For a complete photography-focused itinerary, see our <a href='/india/delhi/delhi-1-day-itinerary'>Delhi 1-day itinerary</a> guide." },
      { question: "What are the tipping customs on the Delhi private half-day tour?", answer: "Tipping in India is appreciated but not obligatory. For the private half-day Delhi tour, customary tips are: **Guide** — **₹500–1,000** (approximately USD 6–12) for a half-day tour, or **₹1,000–2,000** for a full day; adjust upward for exceptional service, in-depth knowledge, or large groups. **Driver** — **₹300–500** for a half-day, or **₹500–800** for a full day; the driver manages Delhi's challenging traffic and deserves recognition. **Rickshaw-wallah** (Chandni Chowk cycle-rickshaw) — **₹50–100** for the ride. **Monument staff** — not expected; do not tip ASI (Archaeological Survey of India) guards or ticket sellers. Tips can be given in **Indian rupees (cash)** at the end of the tour. There is no pressure to tip — it is entirely at your discretion based on your experience. Your guide will never request a tip. For more insights on Delhi customs and culture, see our <a href='/india/delhi/things-to-do-in-delhi'>things to do in Delhi</a> guide." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'delhi-to-jaipur-royal-private-day-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What does the Delhi to Jaipur royal private day tour cover?", answer: "The Delhi to Jaipur royal private day tour is a premium one-day excursion from Delhi to Jaipur, covering the Pink City's essential royal heritage: **Amber Fort** (the magnificent 16th-century Rajput hill fort, UNESCO Heritage Site, with optional elephant ride), **City Palace** (the partial royal residence of the Maharaja of Jaipur, with world-class royal collection museum), **Jantar Mantar** (the UNESCO-listed 18th-century astronomical observatory built by Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh II), and **Hawa Mahal** (the iconic 'Palace of Winds' with 953 windows, built 1799). An optional bazaar walk covers Jaipur's famous markets (block printing, blue pottery, kundan jewellery). All entry tickets, guide, and premium vehicle are included." },
      { question: "How long is the drive from Delhi to Jaipur?", answer: "The drive from Delhi to Jaipur is approximately **270 km** — approximately **4.5–5 hours** each way via NH48 (the Delhi–Jaipur National Highway). For a same-day trip from Delhi, departure at **6:00–6:30 AM** is recommended to arrive in Jaipur by approximately 11:00–11:30 AM for sightseeing. The return drive departs Jaipur at approximately **6:00–7:00 PM**, arriving back in Delhi at approximately **10:30–11:30 PM**. Total same-day road time: approximately 10 hours. This is a long but manageable one-day excursion in a comfortable luxury vehicle. Most travellers who make the same-day Delhi-Jaipur trip recommend the overnight option (staying in Jaipur) for a less exhausting experience." },
      { question: "Why is it called a 'royal' Jaipur day tour?", answer: "The 'royal' designation refers to both the tour's content and its experience quality. **Content:** Jaipur is literally a royal city — the Maharajas of Jaipur still reside in City Palace (the public museum section is open to visitors while the royal family occupies the private quarters). Amber Fort was the royal residence of the Kachawa Rajput dynasty for 300 years. Jantar Mantar was a royal scientific project of Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh II. The entire city was designed by the Maharaja as a functioning royal capital in 1727. **Quality:** The 'royal' tour uses a premium vehicle (luxury sedan or SUV), senior specialist guide, priority entry where available, and a quality restaurant for lunch." },
      { question: "Is Amber Fort accessible by elephant on this tour?", answer: "The traditional approach to Amber Fort was by elephant along the ramped pathway from the fort's base. However, this practice is increasingly discouraged due to animal welfare concerns (overworked elephants, abusive training methods) and Asia by Locals does not recommend or include elephant rides at Amber Fort. An alternative shared jeep service up the ramp (government-operated) or the walk up the ramped pathway (approximately 10 minutes) are the appropriate modes of access. From inside the fort, the views from the battlements over the Maota Lake and surrounding Aravalli hills are extraordinary and no elephant ride is needed to experience them." },
      { question: "What is included in the Delhi to Jaipur royal private day tour?", answer: "Included: premium private vehicle (luxury sedan or SUV), experienced chauffeur, hotel pickup in Delhi and drop-off (Delhi hotel on return), Ministry of Tourism-licensed senior Jaipur guide, all entry tickets (Amber Fort, City Palace, Jantar Mantar, Hawa Mahal exterior), and sit-down lunch at a quality Jaipur restaurant. Amber Fort and City Palace entry fees for foreign nationals total approximately ₹1,200. Optional Nahargarh Fort (sunset views) can be added for the late afternoon. Not included: tips for guide and driver, personal shopping, or optional site additions." },
      { question: "Is it better to do the Delhi-Jaipur day trip or stay overnight in Jaipur?", answer: "An **overnight stay in Jaipur** is strongly recommended over a same-day trip if your schedule allows. The Delhi-Jaipur drive is 4.5–5 hours each way, meaning a same-day trip involves 9–10 hours of driving with only 4–5 hours of actual Jaipur sightseeing. An overnight stay: allows a more relaxed pace, covers more sites (Nahargarh Fort sunset, Jaipur markets, Abhaneri step-well), gives access to Jaipur's excellent dinner scene (Rajasthani thali, rooftop restaurants), and eliminates the exhaustion of the long return drive at night. Jaipur as an overnight destination is one of India's finest travel experiences and deserves more than a rushed day trip." },
      { question: "What is the City Palace Jaipur and what can visitors see?", answer: "The City Palace of Jaipur is a partially functional royal residence — the Maharaja of Jaipur still lives in the private Chandra Mahal section, while the public Mubarak Mahal section houses the Maharaja Sawai Man Singh II Museum, one of India's finest royal collections. Visitor highlights: the 'largest silver urns in the world' (used to carry Ganga river water to England for Maharaja Madho Singh II's coronation visit in 1901), an extraordinary royal textile collection (costumes of Maharajas including a 2-metre-tall Maharaja's robe), and royal weaponry. The Pritam Niwas Chowk courtyard has four peacock gates in exquisitely detailed polychrome work, a perfect photography subject. The City Palace combines 250 years of Jaipur royal history in one complex." },
      { question: "What is the best season for the Delhi to Jaipur private day tour?", answer: "**October to March** is ideal for the Delhi-Jaipur day trip. Jaipur's desert climate means: pleasant October–February days (20–28°C), cold January nights (8–12°C), and clear dry winter air that makes Amber Fort's white marble and city views particularly vivid. **March–April** is warm but manageable. **May–June** is very hot (40–46°C) — avoid midday outdoor sightseeing; earlier starts are essential. **July–September** (monsoon): Jaipur and surrounding Rajasthan receive less rain than north India, and the Aravalli hills briefly turn green — an unusual perspective. Winter evenings in Jaipur are particularly atmospheric — the illuminated Hawa Mahal and City Palace are stunning, and a rooftop dinner is a perfect end to the day." },
      { question: "Are there rest stops on the Delhi-Jaipur highway during the day tour?", answer: "Yes — the **NH48 Delhi-Jaipur highway** has several well-maintained service plazas and rest stops along the 270 km route. The driver typically makes **one planned stop** approximately **2 hours into the journey** (near Neemrana or Behror) at a clean, modern highway complex with restrooms, snack counters, and coffee chains. These plazas have been significantly upgraded in recent years and include brands like **Haldiram's, McDonald's, and Café Coffee Day**. The stop lasts **10–15 minutes** — enough for a restroom break and a quick chai or coffee. Additional stops can be requested at any time. The Neemrana area also features the historic Neemrana Fort-Palace (visible from the highway) which can be a brief photo stop if desired. For a more in-depth Jaipur experience when you arrive, consider extending to include our [Amber Fort official guided tour](/india/jaipur/amber-fort-official-guided-tour) for the most comprehensive fort visit." },
      { question: "Can the Delhi-Jaipur royal day tour be extended to an overnight trip?", answer: "Yes — an **overnight extension in Jaipur** is strongly recommended and is the single best upgrade you can make to this tour. Converting from a same-day trip to an overnight stay transforms the experience: you gain a **Nahargarh Fort sunset** (Jaipur's most spectacular viewpoint), a **Jaipur rooftop dinner** (the city's evening food scene is exceptional), a relaxed morning the next day for a **heritage walk through the Pink City bazaars**, and the elimination of the exhausting late-night return drive. Jaipur has excellent heritage hotels ranging from **₹3,000–₹15,000 per night** — many are converted havelis (traditional mansions) with courtyard dining and rooftop terraces. The guide can recommend and arrange accommodation based on your preferences and budget. A second day in Jaipur allows adding experiences like the [elephant village tour](/india/jaipur/elephant-village-tour-jaipur) or a cooking class that simply cannot fit in a single-day visit." }
    ];
  }

  // --- END DELHI TOUR FAQS (ALL 19 COMPLETE) ---

  // --- JAIPUR TOUR FAQS BATCH 1 ---

  if (slug === 'jaipur-full-day-sightseeing-tour-by-car') {
    return [
      { question: "What does the Jaipur full-day sightseeing tour by car cover?", answer: "The Jaipur full-day sightseeing tour by car covers all of the Pink City's major attractions in a comprehensive day with a private vehicle: **Amber Fort** (UNESCO-listed 16th-century Rajput hilltop fortress, 15 km from Jaipur city), **City Palace** (partial royal residence with exceptional museum), **Jantar Mantar** (UNESCO-listed 18th-century astronomical observatory), **Hawa Mahal** (the iconic 5-storey 'Palace of Winds' with 953 latticed windows), **Jaigarh Fort** (the 'Victory Fort' on the hill above Amber with Asia's largest wheeled cannon), and **Nahargarh Fort** (sunset viewpoint overlooking the entire Jaipur skyline). The car-based format allows efficient transit between these geographically spread sites without the physical exhaustion of walking between them." },
      { question: "Why do the Jaipur sightseeing tour by car rather than a cycle-rickshaw or walking tour?", answer: "Jaipur's major attractions are spread across a 15–20 km area, making a car essential for comfortable coverage. Amber Fort alone is 15 km from the city centre. The fort circuit (Amber + Jaigarh) requires vehicle access. Even within the old city, a car provides relief from Jaipur's heat (which regularly reaches 40°C in summer) between sites. Walking tours work excellently for the Jaipur old city bazaar area (Johari Bazaar, Bapu Bazaar) where lanes are too narrow for vehicles, but a car-based tour that includes strategic walking sections at each monument is the most efficient and comfortable way to see all of Jaipur's highlights in a single day." },
      { question: "Is a guide included in the Jaipur full-day sightseeing tour?", answer: "Yes — a Ministry of Tourism-licensed professional guide is included and accompanies you throughout the full day. Jaipur's history is the story of the Kachawa Rajput dynasty — 300 years of warrior kings, royal intrigue, the relationship with Mughal emperors (Amber Fort's Rajput commander served as Akbar's chief general), and the vision of Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh II who designed the planned city of Jaipur in 1727. Your guide connects all sites chronologically and architecturally — the transition from the old capital (Amber Fort) to the new planned city (Jaipur) is a fascinating story of political modernization that transforms the monument visits into a coherent historical narrative." },
      { question: "What is Amber Fort and why is it Jaipur's most important monument?", answer: "Amber Fort (Amer Qila) is a UNESCO World Heritage Site — a magnificent 16th–17th-century Rajput palace fortress built on a rocky hillside 15 km from Jaipur. It was the capital of the Kachawa Rajput dynasty for nearly 300 years before Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh II moved the capital to the newly planned city of Jaipur in 1727. The fort is a masterpiece of Rajput-Mughal architectural fusion: red sandstone and white marble, mirrored mosaic ceilings (Sheesh Mahal — 'Palace of Mirrors'), ornate carved marble screens, and massive fortified walls following the natural ridgeline. From the fort battlements, the Maota Lake below and the surrounding Aravalli hills create an extraordinarily scenic vista. The full guided visit takes approximately 2 hours." },
      { question: "What is the Hawa Mahal and can I go inside?", answer: "Hawa Mahal ('Palace of Winds') is Jaipur's most photographed landmark — a distinctive 5-storey screened facade with 953 intricately carved sandstone windows ('jharokhas') built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh. The facade was designed to allow royal women of the zenana (female quarters) to observe street processions while remaining unseen. The interior is accessible (entry ₹200 for foreign nationals) and contains a small museum and several viewing platforms from which you can see the Jaipur bazaar through the honeycombed windows — a uniquely framed view. However, many visitors are satisfied with exterior photography (the Hawa Mahal is best photographed from the tea stalls on the opposite side of Badi Chaupar square). Your guide includes the interior visit." },
      { question: "Is lunch included in the Jaipur full-day sightseeing tour?", answer: "Yes — a sit-down lunch at a quality Jaipur restaurant is included. Jaipur's culinary tradition is one of India's richest: the **dal baati churma** (baked wheat rounds with five-lentil broth and a sweetened wheat crumble) is Rajasthan's signature dish and should be tried in Jaipur. Other specialties: Laal Maas (fiery red mutton curry), ker sangri (wild desert bean curry), gatte ki sabzi (chickpea flour dumplings in yoghurt sauce), and mishri mawa (a traditional Jaipur sweet). The lunch restaurant is selected for quality Rajasthani cuisine and reliable food hygiene. Vegetarian, vegan, and Jain options are always available." },
      { question: "How long is the Jaipur full-day sightseeing tour by car?", answer: "The full-day tour runs approximately **8–10 hours** from hotel pickup (8:30–9:00 AM) to hotel drop-off (approximately 6:00–7:30 PM): Amber Fort (2 hours), Jaigarh Fort (45 minutes, above Amber), transit to city, City Palace + Jantar Mantar (2 hours combined), lunch (1 hour), Hawa Mahal exterior + interior (45 minutes), Nahargarh Fort sunset (45 minutes, approximately 5:00 PM). The car ensures efficient transit between these spread-out sites — without a vehicle, the same coverage would be impossible in a single day. The tour ends with the Nahargarh sunset, one of Jaipur's most beautiful natural experiences." },
      { question: "Are entry tickets to all Jaipur monuments included?", answer: "Yes — all monument entry tickets are included in the tour price: Amber Fort (₹500 for foreign nationals), City Palace (₹700), Jantar Mantar (₹200), Hawa Mahal (₹200), Jaigarh Fort (₹35, included in the Amber composite ticket), and Nahargarh Fort (₹200). Total included ticket value for a foreign national: approximately ₹1,800. The Jaipur composite ticket ('Jaipur City Palace + Amber + Jantar Mantar Heritage Entry Pass') can sometimes be used advantageously — your guide selects the most cost-effective ticketing approach based on current availability." },
      { question: "What is the best time to visit Amber Fort during the Jaipur day tour?", answer: "**8:00–10:00 AM** is the ideal window for Amber Fort — the morning light from the east illuminates the red sandstone facade beautifully, temperatures are comfortable, and crowds are significantly smaller than the 10 AM–12 PM peak. The full-day tour is designed to start at Amber Fort first thing in the morning for exactly this reason. By 11:00 AM, tour buses begin arriving in large numbers. The Sheesh Mahal (mirrored hall interior) is most spectacular in the morning when sunlight streams through the southern entrance creating the 'starry sky' mirror reflection effect. Your guide positions your group for the optimal lighting in the Sheesh Mahal based on the sun angle on the day of your visit." },
      { question: "Can the Jaipur full-day sightseeing tour itinerary be customized?", answer: "Yes — the itinerary is **fully customizable** to your interests. The standard route (Amber Fort, Jaigarh Fort, City Palace, Jantar Mantar, Hawa Mahal, Nahargarh Fort) covers all essential Jaipur landmarks, but your guide adjusts based on your preferences. **Architecture enthusiasts** can extend Amber Fort to 3 hours and add the Panna Meena Ka Kund stepwell. **Photography-focused visitors** can rearrange timing to optimize golden-hour light at specific monuments. **Families with children** can swap Jantar Mantar for the Elefantastic elephant sanctuary. **Spiritual travellers** can add the Galtaji Monkey Temple or Birla Mandir. **Shoppers** can replace Nahargarh Fort sunset with a 2-hour guided bazaar walk through Johari Bazaar and Bapu Bazaar. Simply inform your guide of your priorities at the start of the day — or at booking — and the route is tailored accordingly. No two private tours need to follow the identical script. For a dedicated craft experience, consider adding our [block printing workshop](/india/jaipur/jaipur-block-printing-workshop) as a half-day complement." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'jaipur-city-tour-with-official-guide') {
    return [
      { question: "What makes an 'official guide' different for Jaipur?", answer: "An 'official guide' for Jaipur refers specifically to a guide who is certified by the **Ministry of Tourism, Government of India** and authorized by the Archaeological Survey of India (ASI) to provide guiding services inside all federally protected monuments in Jaipur, including Amber Fort, City Palace, Jantar Mantar, and the Hawa Mahal. This certification involves a rigorous government examination covering Rajput architectural history, Mughal-Rajput political relations, Rajasthani art and culture, and tour management. Unauthorized guides (who operate without this certification) cannot legally provide commentary inside the protected monument areas and often provide inaccurate historical information. Your official guide carries and shows their government-issued ID card." },
      { question: "What does the Jaipur city tour with official guide cover?", answer: "The official guide Jaipur city tour covers the complete heritage circuit: **Amber Fort** (UNESCO World Heritage Site — 16th-century Rajput palace fortress, 2-hour guided tour including Sheesh Mahal, Diwan-i-Am, Sukh Mahal, and battlements), **City Palace** (royal residence museum with royal textile, weaponry, and art collections), **Jantar Mantar** (UNESCO World Heritage Site — 18th-century royal astronomical observatory with 19 giant stone instruments), **Hawa Mahal** (Palace of Winds, exterior and interior), and optionally **Nahargarh Fort** (sunset viewpoint). The official guide provides authoritative commentary at each site that would be unavailable from unlicensed alternatives." },
      { question: "Is the official guide licensed for all Jaipur monuments?", answer: "Yes — the official guide is licensed for all federally protected monuments in Jaipur and throughout Rajasthan. This includes Amber Fort, City Palace, Jantar Mantar, and Hawa Mahal (all require ASI authorization for guiding). The guide's Ministry of Tourism certificate covers the entire state of Rajasthan, not just specific monuments, allowing seamless commentary across all sites on your itinerary. The guide also has the local knowledge to advise on the best entry times, the least-crowded viewing areas within each monument, and the photography positions that most visitors miss." },
      { question: "What is the Jantar Mantar in Jaipur and why is it a UNESCO Heritage Site?", answer: "Jaipur's Jantar Mantar is an 18th-century open-air astronomical observatory built by Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh II between 1724 and 1735. It contains 19 major astronomical instruments, all built in stone, marble, and brick at monumental scale — some reaching 30+ metres in height. The instruments were used to measure celestial positions, track seasonal changes, predict eclipses, and determine time with extraordinary precision. The largest instrument (Samrat Yantra) can measure time to an accuracy of 2 seconds and still functions today. Jantar Mantar was awarded UNESCO World Heritage status in 2010 as 'an expression of the astronomical skills and cosmological concepts of the court of a scholarly prince at the end of the Mughal period.' Without an official guide, most instruments are simply large stone objects; with the guide, they become a working scientific system." },
      { question: "How long is the Jaipur city tour with official guide?", answer: "The official guide city tour runs approximately **8–9 hours** with a private vehicle from hotel pickup to drop-off. Time allocation: Amber Fort (2 hours), Jaigarh Fort (optional, 45 minutes), lunch (1 hour), City Palace (1 hour), Jantar Mantar (45 minutes), Hawa Mahal (45 minutes), Nahargarh Fort (45 minutes at sunset). A shorter half-day version (4–5 hours) covering Amber Fort + City Palace + Jantar Mantar is available for visitors with limited time. The full-day version is recommended for first-time Jaipur visitors to cover all major monuments with adequate depth." },
      { question: "What is the Sheesh Mahal (Palace of Mirrors) inside Amber Fort?", answer: "The Sheesh Mahal ('Palace of Mirrors') is the most spectacular interior within Amber Fort — a private audience hall where the walls and ceiling are entirely encrusted in tiny convex mirror tiles set in plaster, creating an extraordinary glittering effect. When a single candle is lit inside the dark chamber, the reflections multiply to simulate a night sky filled with thousands of stars. The craftwork (known as Aina Kari or mirror work) is a Mughal decorative technique adopted by Rajput builders. Photography inside the Sheesh Mahal is dramatically improved by the morning sunlight entering through the southern doorway, which your official guide times your visit to capture. It is widely considered the most photographed interior in Rajasthan." },
      { question: "Are entry tickets included in the Jaipur official guide city tour?", answer: "Yes — all monument entry tickets are included in the tour price: Amber Fort (₹500 for foreign nationals), City Palace (₹700), Jantar Mantar (₹200), Hawa Mahal (₹200), and Nahargarh Fort (₹200). Total included ticket value: approximately ₹1,800. The official guide also manages any audio guide devices, photography permits, or special access permissions required at each site. For high-season visits (October–March) when Amber Fort can be very crowded, the guide uses their knowledge of access timings and entry flow to minimize waiting." },
      { question: "Is the official guide city tour available in languages other than English?", answer: "Yes — Ministry of Tourism-certified official guides in Jaipur are available in: English (standard), Spanish, French, German, Italian, Japanese, Chinese (Mandarin), and Russian. Language-specific guides are vetted for both historical expertise and language fluency. When booking, specify your preferred language. English-language tours can be arranged with 24 hours notice; less common languages (Chinese, Russian, Japanese) may require 48–72 hours advance notice to confirm a suitably qualified guide. The depth of historical commentary is maintained in all languages — Rajput and Mughal history is equally rich in any language." },
      { question: "What is the City Palace Jaipur and what is in the museum?", answer: "The City Palace complex was built by Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh II as the administrative and cultural centre of his new planned city of Jaipur in 1727. The outer courtyard (Mubarak Mahal) now houses the **Maharaja Sawai Man Singh II Museum** with four major collections: (1) Textile gallery — royal costumes including Maharaja Madho Singh I's clothing (he was reportedly 2 metres tall and 250 kg); (2) Armory — royal Rajput weapons spanning 5 centuries; (3) Transport gallery — royal carriages and palanquins; (4) The famous pair of pure silver urns (Gangajali) — each 1.6 metres tall, holding 4,000 litres, the largest silver objects in the world according to the Guinness Book — used to carry Ganga water to England for the Maharaja's 1902 coronation visit." },
      { question: "How can I verify my Jaipur guide's government ID and official certification?", answer: "Every official Jaipur guide carries a **Ministry of Tourism photo ID card** and an **ASI (Archaeological Survey of India) authorization certificate** — you can and should request to see these at the start of your tour. The ID card displays the guide's **photograph, name, registration number, authorized languages, and validity dates**. Genuine government guide IDs have a **holographic security feature** and an **official Ministry of Tourism stamp**. Your guide will proactively show their credentials at the first monument entry gate, as ASI security personnel verify guide authorization before allowing entry. If a guide refuses to show credentials or provides a laminated card without security features, they are likely unauthorized. Unauthorized guides are common at Amber Fort's entrance — they approach tourists aggressively offering 'official' guiding services at discounted rates. These individuals lack the historical training and examination certification of genuine Ministry guides and frequently provide inaccurate information. Booking through Asia by Locals guarantees a verified, government-certified guide. For the most comprehensive Jaipur experience with your official guide, see our [things to do in Jaipur guide](/india/jaipur/things-to-do-in-jaipur)." }
    ];
  }

