  if (slug === '6-day-golden-triangle-tour-with-tiger-safari') {
    return [
      { question: "What is the day-by-day itinerary for the 6-day Golden Triangle tour with tiger safari?", answer: "**Day 1 — Delhi:** Arrive and transfer to your hotel; evening orientation walk or leisure time. **Day 2 — Delhi sightseeing:** Old Delhi (Jama Masjid, Red Fort, Chandni Chowk rickshaw ride) and New Delhi (India Gate, Humayun's Tomb, Qutub Minar) with a licensed guide. **Day 3 — Delhi to Agra (200 km, ~3.5 hrs):** Taj Mahal visit, Agra Fort, optional Mehtab Bagh at sunset. **Day 4 — Agra to Ranthambore (280 km, ~5 hrs):** Drive via Fatehpur Sikri stop; evening at leisure near the national park. **Day 5 — Ranthambore tiger safari:** Morning and afternoon jeep safaris inside Ranthambore National Park with a park naturalist. **Day 6 — Ranthambore to Jaipur (180 km, ~3 hrs):** Amber Fort, City Palace, Hawa Mahal; drop-off in Jaipur or return drive to Delhi. For a condensed version, consider the [4-day Golden Triangle & Ranthambore tour](/india/delhi/golden-triangle-ranthambore-tiger-safari-4-days)." },
      { question: "Are hotels included in the 6-day Golden Triangle tour price?", answer: "Yes — **5 nights of hotel accommodation** are included: 1 night in Delhi, 1 night in Agra, 2 nights near Ranthambore National Park, and 1 night in Jaipur. The standard package uses comfortable **3-star hotels** with air conditioning, Wi-Fi, and hot water. Upgrades to 4-star heritage properties or 5-star luxury hotels (such as Oberoi Amarvilas in Agra or Taj Rambagh Palace in Jaipur) are available at supplemental pricing. In Ranthambore, accommodation is typically a wildlife lodge or resort situated within **5–10 km** of the park gate, adding to the jungle atmosphere." },
      { question: "What are the tiger safari details at Ranthambore National Park?", answer: "The tour includes **two jeep safaris** (morning and afternoon) inside Ranthambore National Park on Day 5. Morning safaris run from **6:00–9:30 AM** and afternoon safaris from **2:30–6:00 PM** (timings vary seasonally). The vehicle is an open-top **Gypsy jeep** seating 6 passengers, accompanied by a government-certified park naturalist who tracks tiger movements and knows individual tigers by name. Ranthambore has a tiger sighting probability of approximately **60–75%** per safari day — among the highest in India. All **park entry fees and safari charges** (approximately ₹1,500–₹2,500 per person per safari for foreign nationals) are included in the tour price." },
      { question: "Are meals included in the 6-day Golden Triangle tiger safari tour?", answer: "**Daily breakfasts** at all hotels are included in the standard package. Lunches and dinners can be added at the time of booking for an additional cost of approximately **₹500–₹800 per meal** at quality restaurants. During the Ranthambore segment, a packed breakfast is provided before the early morning safari, and a full lunch is arranged at the jungle lodge between safaris. The tour guide recommends excellent local restaurants at each stop — from Mughlai cuisine in Old Delhi's Chandni Chowk to Rajasthani thali in Jaipur. Vegetarian, vegan, Jain, halal, and allergen-aware options are available at all meal stops." },
      { question: "What type of vehicle is used for the 6-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "A **private air-conditioned vehicle** is provided for the entire 6-day circuit — typically a Toyota Innova Crysta (6-seat SUV) for groups up to 5, or a sedan (Swift Dzire or Honda Amaze) for couples and solo travellers. For groups of 7 or more, a **tempo traveller** (12–15 seats) is arranged. The same driver accompanies you throughout all 6 days, ensuring continuity and familiarity with your preferences. The vehicle is equipped with USB charging ports and bottled water. Inside Ranthambore National Park, a separate open-top Gypsy jeep is used for safaris, as private vehicles are not permitted inside the park." },
      { question: "Is the 6-day Golden Triangle tour private or a group tour?", answer: "This is a **fully private tour** — your group travels alone with a dedicated driver and guide, with no other tourists sharing your vehicle or itinerary. The private format allows complete flexibility: you can spend extra time at sites you enjoy, skip locations that don't interest you, and adjust start times to suit your pace. Licensed guides are provided in each city — a Delhi-Agra specialist for Days 2–3, a park naturalist for Ranthambore safaris on Day 5, and a Jaipur specialist on Day 6. This is not a fixed-departure group tour; your trip runs on your chosen dates." },
      { question: "What cities are covered on the 6-day Golden Triangle with Ranthambore tour?", answer: "The tour covers **four destinations** in a logical loop: **Delhi** (India's capital — Mughal and British-era monuments), **Agra** (home of the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort), **Ranthambore** (India's most famous tiger reserve in Rajasthan), and **Jaipur** (the 'Pink City' — Amber Fort, City Palace, Hawa Mahal). The total driving distance across all 6 days is approximately **900–950 km**. The route forms a rough diamond shape across northern India, and each driving segment is **3–5 hours**, keeping travel manageable. For Delhi-only sightseeing in more depth, see our [Delhi full-day guided tour](/india/delhi/delhi-full-day-guided-tour)." },
      { question: "What is the best season to do the 6-day Golden Triangle with tiger safari?", answer: "**October to March** is the ideal season, combining comfortable weather for monument sightseeing (18–28°C) with Ranthambore National Park being open for safaris. **March to May** offers the highest tiger sighting probability (vegetation thins, tigers gather at water sources) but temperatures reach **40–46°C**. The park is **closed from July to September** during monsoon season, making the tour unavailable in those months. For the best balance of comfortable weather and good tiger sighting odds, **November to February** is optimal. January mornings can be foggy in Delhi and Agra, adding atmosphere to sunrise visits at the [Taj Mahal](/india/agra/taj-mahal-sunrise-tour)." },
      { question: "What fitness level is needed for the 6-day Golden Triangle tiger safari tour?", answer: "The tour requires only a **moderate fitness level** — no strenuous hiking or climbing is involved. The most physically demanding activity is walking through monument complexes: the Taj Mahal gardens involve approximately **1.5 km of flat walking**, Amber Fort has ramps and steps (elephant rides or jeep rides to the top are available for ₹500–₹1,100), and Old Delhi's Chandni Chowk is a walking exploration of **1–2 km**. The tiger safaris are entirely vehicle-based — you remain seated in the Gypsy jeep throughout. Air-conditioned vehicle transfers between cities require sitting for **3–5 hours** per leg. The tour is suitable for ages 5 to 75+ and for travellers with moderate mobility." },
      { question: "What is the cancellation policy for the 6-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "Free cancellation is available up to **7 days before departure** for a full refund. Cancellations **3–6 days** before departure receive a **50% refund**. Cancellations within **48 hours** of departure are non-refundable due to pre-booked hotel rooms, safari permits, and vehicle arrangements. Ranthambore safari permits in particular must be booked well in advance through the government portal and are non-transferable once issued. Date changes (rescheduling) are free if requested **5+ days** before departure, subject to availability. Travel insurance covering trip cancellation is strongly recommended, especially during peak season (October–February)." },
      { question: "Are monument entry tickets included in the 6-day tour price?", answer: "Yes — **all monument entry tickets** are included: Red Fort (₹35 Indian / ₹500 foreign), Humayun's Tomb (₹35/₹550), Qutub Minar (₹35/₹550), Taj Mahal (₹50/₹1,100 + ₹200 mausoleum fee), Agra Fort (₹35/₹550), Fatehpur Sikri (₹35/₹550), Ranthambore National Park safari permits (₹1,500–₹2,500 per safari), Amber Fort (₹100/₹500), City Palace Jaipur (₹200/₹500), and Jantar Mantar (₹50/₹200). Camera fees where applicable are also included. The total ticket value for foreign nationals across all sites is approximately **₹7,000–₹9,000** — all pre-purchased so you skip ticket queues at every location." },
      { question: "How much walking is involved each day on the 6-day tour?", answer: "Daily walking varies by location: **Delhi (Day 2):** approximately **4–5 km** total across Old Delhi bazaar walks and New Delhi monument visits. **Agra (Day 3):** approximately **3–4 km** covering the Taj Mahal complex and Agra Fort. **Travel days (Days 1, 4):** minimal walking, primarily vehicle transfers. **Ranthambore (Day 5):** virtually **no walking** — safaris are entirely vehicle-based inside the park. **Jaipur (Day 6):** approximately **3–4 km** across Amber Fort, City Palace, and Hawa Mahal. All walking is on flat or gently graded surfaces, with rest stops and air-conditioned vehicle breaks between sites. Comfortable walking shoes are recommended." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'golden-triangle-ranthambore-tiger-safari-4-days') {
    return [
      { question: "What is the 4-day Golden Triangle & Ranthambore itinerary?", answer: "**Day 1 — Delhi to Agra (200 km, ~3.5 hrs):** Early morning pickup from your Delhi hotel, drive to Agra via Yamuna Expressway, visit the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort with a licensed guide, overnight in Agra. **Day 2 — Agra to Ranthambore (280 km, ~5 hrs):** Optional sunrise Taj Mahal revisit, then drive to Ranthambore with an en-route stop at Fatehpur Sikri; evening at the wildlife lodge. **Day 3 — Ranthambore safari & drive to Jaipur:** Morning jeep safari (6:00–9:30 AM), then drive to Jaipur (180 km, ~3 hrs); afternoon Jaipur sightseeing — Amber Fort, City Palace. **Day 4 — Jaipur to Delhi (270 km, ~5 hrs):** Morning Jaipur sightseeing (Hawa Mahal, Jantar Mantar), then return drive to Delhi with drop-off at hotel or airport. For a more relaxed pace with two safari days, see the [6-day Golden Triangle with tiger safari](/india/delhi/6-day-golden-triangle-tour-with-tiger-safari)." },
      { question: "What is the probability of seeing a tiger at Ranthambore on the 4-day tour?", answer: "Ranthambore National Park has one of the highest tiger sighting rates in India — approximately **60–75% probability** of spotting a Bengal tiger on any single safari outing. The park's relatively open terrain (lakeshores, grasslands, ancient ruins) means tigers are frequently visible in daylight rather than hidden in dense jungle. Your morning Gypsy jeep safari (3.5 hours) is led by a government-certified naturalist who tracks tiger movements and communicates with other jeeps via radio. While sightings cannot be guaranteed (these are wild animals), Ranthambore's resident population of **70+ tigers** and the park's open landscape provide excellent odds even on a single safari." },
      { question: "What category of hotels are included in the 4-day tour?", answer: "The standard 4-day package includes **3-star hotels** — 1 night in Agra (typically in the Taj Ganj area near the Taj Mahal), 1 night at a Ranthambore jungle lodge (within 5–10 km of the park gate), and 1 night in Jaipur (within the old city or close to major sites). All hotels provide air conditioning, Wi-Fi, hot water, and daily breakfast. Upgrades to **4-star heritage properties** (restored Rajput havelis) or **5-star luxury** (Oberoi, Taj Hotels, ITC) are available at supplemental pricing. The Ranthambore lodge options often feature a rustic jungle aesthetic with courtyards, wildlife artwork, and evening campfire areas." },
      { question: "What transport is used between cities on the 4-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "A **private air-conditioned vehicle** — typically a Toyota Innova Crysta (seats 6) or sedan (seats 3) — is provided for the entire 4-day circuit with the same driver throughout. Total driving distance across the 4 days is approximately **930 km**. The longest single drive is Agra to Ranthambore (**280 km, ~5 hours**), broken up by a stop at Fatehpur Sikri. All national highway roads are well-maintained. Inside Ranthambore National Park, a separate open-top **Gypsy jeep** (6 seats) is used for the safari, as private cars are not allowed inside. Tolls, parking fees, and driver accommodation are all included." },
      { question: "Are meals included in the 4-day Golden Triangle Ranthambore tour?", answer: "**Daily breakfasts** at all three hotels are included. A packed early breakfast is provided on the Ranthambore safari morning before the 6:00 AM departure. Lunches and dinners are **not included** in the standard package but can be added for approximately **₹500–₹800 per meal**. Your guide and driver recommend excellent local restaurants at each stop — Mughlai cuisine in Agra, Rajasthani thali in Jaipur, and jungle lodge dining at Ranthambore. Vegetarian, vegan, Jain, halal, and allergen-specific dietary requirements are accommodated at all stops when informed at booking." },
      { question: "How does the 4-day tour differ from the 6-day Golden Triangle with tiger safari?", answer: "The key differences: the **4-day version** includes **1 morning safari** at Ranthambore, while the [6-day version](/india/delhi/6-day-golden-triangle-tour-with-tiger-safari) includes **2 full safaris** (morning + afternoon), doubling your tiger sighting chances. The 6-day tour also spends a full day sightseeing in Delhi before departing for Agra, whereas the 4-day tour begins directly with the Agra drive on Day 1. The 6-day tour allows **2 nights at Ranthambore** (more relaxed pacing) versus 1 night in the 4-day version. The 4-day tour is ideal for travellers with limited time who want the essential Golden Triangle + Ranthambore experience; the 6-day is better for wildlife enthusiasts who want maximum safari time." },
      { question: "What should I pack for the Ranthambore tiger safari?", answer: "Essential safari packing: **Clothing** — earth-toned layers (khaki, olive, brown; avoid bright colours that startle wildlife), a warm fleece or jacket for chilly dawn safaris (October–February mornings can drop to **8–12°C** in open jeeps), a sun hat, and sunscreen. **Footwear** — closed-toe shoes or hiking sandals (the jeep is dusty). **Protection** — sunglasses, insect repellent (mosquitoes near lakes), and a scarf/bandana to cover your nose on dusty tracks. **Hydration** — a reusable water bottle (refilled at the lodge). **Binoculars** — highly recommended for spotting wildlife at distance (8x42 or 10x42 magnification). **Medication** — motion sickness tablets if prone to nausea on bumpy tracks." },
      { question: "What camera equipment is best for the Ranthambore tiger safari?", answer: "For tiger photography at Ranthambore, a **telephoto zoom lens** is essential — tigers can be spotted at distances of **50–200 metres**. A **100–400mm** or **200–600mm** zoom lens on a DSLR or mirrorless camera is ideal. Smartphone cameras with optical zoom (iPhone 15 Pro Max, Samsung S24 Ultra) can capture decent shots when tigers are closer (**30–50 metres**). Bring extra batteries (cold mornings drain batteries faster) and large-capacity memory cards (**64GB minimum**). A **beanbag** for resting long lenses on the jeep rail is more practical than a tripod in the open-top Gypsy. Set your camera to burst/continuous shooting mode — tiger movement can be sudden and brief." },
      { question: "How early do safari mornings start on the 4-day tour?", answer: "On the Ranthambore safari day (Day 3), you depart the lodge at approximately **5:30 AM** to reach the park gate by **6:00 AM** for the morning safari slot. The safari runs until approximately **9:30 AM** (3.5 hours). A packed early breakfast is provided before departure — coffee/tea, sandwiches, and fruit from the lodge. After the safari, a full hot breakfast is served at the lodge (around 10:00 AM) before the drive to Jaipur. The early start is essential because wildlife is most active in the cool dawn hours — Bengal tigers, sloth bears, and deer are all more visible before the heat of the day. Sunrise over the park's lakes and fort ruins is spectacular." },
      { question: "What is the maximum group size for the 4-day Golden Triangle tour?", answer: "This is a **fully private tour** — your group travels exclusively with your own driver and guide. There is no mixing with other tourists. The standard Gypsy jeep inside Ranthambore seats a **maximum of 6 passengers** (government regulation), so if your group exceeds 6, a second safari jeep is arranged. The private vehicle for intercity travel seats up to **6 passengers** (Innova Crysta); groups of 7–12 use a tempo traveller. Licensed city guides are provided at each destination — a Delhi/Agra specialist and a Jaipur specialist. For a comprehensive Delhi experience before starting the circuit, add our [Delhi full-day guided tour](/india/delhi/delhi-full-day-guided-tour) as a Day 0." },
      { question: "Is the 4-day Golden Triangle Ranthambore tour suitable for children?", answer: "Yes — the tour is suitable for children aged **5 and above**. Ranthambore National Park allows children of all ages on Gypsy jeep safaris (children under 5 must sit on a parent's lap). The safari is exciting and educational for children — spotting tigers, deer, monkeys, crocodiles, and hundreds of bird species. The Taj Mahal and Amber Fort also captivate younger visitors with their grandeur. **Children under 15** receive discounted entry at most Indian monuments (free at many). The private vehicle format means you can stop for breaks as needed, and the guide adjusts the pace and commentary for families. Pack snacks, water, and entertainment for the longer driving segments." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'taj-mahal-superfast-guided-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "Which train is used for the Taj Mahal superfast tour from Delhi?", answer: "The tour uses the **Gatimaan Express** (Train No. 12050) — India's fastest semi-high-speed train, operating at up to **160 km/h**. The Gatimaan Express departs from **Hazrat Nizamuddin Railway Station** in south Delhi (not New Delhi Railway Station) at **8:10 AM** and arrives at **Agra Cantt Station** at **9:50 AM** — a journey of just **1 hour 40 minutes** covering 188 km. The return train (Gatimaan Express 12049) departs Agra Cantt at **5:50 PM** and arrives back at Hazrat Nizamuddin by **7:30 PM**. The Gatimaan Express offers executive chair car class with airline-style reclining seats, onboard catering, and air conditioning." },
      { question: "Are confirmed (CNF) train tickets guaranteed on this tour?", answer: "Yes — **confirmed Gatimaan Express tickets** are pre-booked and guaranteed as part of the tour package. Gatimaan Express seats sell out weeks in advance (especially during October–March peak season), and the tour operator secures tickets through advance booking quotas. You receive your **confirmed e-ticket** with PNR number at least **48 hours before travel**. No waitlisting or RAC (Reservation Against Cancellation) — only confirmed seats. This is a significant advantage over self-booking, as independent travellers frequently find the Gatimaan Express sold out for their preferred date. Bring a government-issued photo ID (passport for foreign nationals) as it is checked onboard." },
      { question: "What is included in the Taj Mahal superfast train tour?", answer: "The package includes: **Gatimaan Express confirmed return tickets** (Delhi–Agra–Delhi), pickup from your Delhi hotel to Hazrat Nizamuddin Station (and return drop-off), a **licensed Agra guide** for the full day, private air-conditioned vehicle in Agra for all transfers between sites, **Taj Mahal entry ticket** (₹1,100 for foreign nationals + ₹200 mausoleum entry), **Agra Fort entry ticket** (₹550), and a sit-down **lunch** at a quality Agra restaurant. The guide meets you at Agra Cantt Station with a name board. Total time in Agra is approximately **8 hours** — ample for a comprehensive visit to the Taj Mahal, Agra Fort, and lunch." },
      { question: "How long do I spend at the Taj Mahal on this tour?", answer: "You spend approximately **2.5–3 hours** at the Taj Mahal complex, which is generous for a thorough visit. This includes time at the main gate (Great Gate or Darwaza-i-Rauza), the charbagh garden with the iconic reflecting pool, the main mausoleum platform (where you must wear shoe covers), and the interior of the mausoleum to see the marble screens and cenotaphs of Shah Jahan and Mumtaz Mahal. Your licensed guide provides the complete historical narrative — the 22-year construction, 20,000 artisans, and the inlaid semi-precious stone work (pietra dura). Photography time is built in. For a sunrise experience instead, consider the [Taj Mahal sunrise tour](/india/agra/taj-mahal-sunrise-tour)." },
      { question: "Is Agra Fort included in the Taj Mahal train tour?", answer: "Yes — **Agra Fort** is included as the second major site of the day. After the Taj Mahal visit and lunch, you visit the massive **16th-century red sandstone fort** (UNESCO World Heritage Site) that served as the main residence of the Mughal emperors until 1638. The fort's highlights include the Diwan-i-Am (Hall of Public Audience), Diwan-i-Khas (Hall of Private Audience), Sheesh Mahal (Mirror Palace), and the poignant Musamman Burj — the octagonal tower where the aged Shah Jahan was imprisoned by his son and spent his final years gazing at the Taj Mahal across the river. Your guide connects the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort narratives into a complete Mughal Empire story." },
      { question: "Is lunch included in the Taj Mahal superfast tour?", answer: "Yes — a **sit-down lunch** at a quality Agra restaurant is included, typically served between the Taj Mahal visit and the Agra Fort visit (around **1:00–2:00 PM**). The restaurant offers North Indian and Mughlai cuisine — butter chicken, biryani, kebabs, dal makhani, fresh naan — with comprehensive vegetarian, vegan, and dietary-restriction options. The lunch venue is a proper restaurant (not a tourist-trap buffet) selected for food quality and hygiene standards. Inform your guide of dietary requirements when you meet at Agra station. Water and soft drinks are included with the meal." },
      { question: "What station does the Gatimaan Express depart from in Delhi?", answer: "The Gatimaan Express departs from **Hazrat Nizamuddin Railway Station** — located in south Delhi, approximately **10 km from Connaught Place** and **15 km from Delhi airport**. This is NOT New Delhi Railway Station (which is in central Delhi near Paharganj). Your tour includes a **hotel pickup transfer** to the station, departing your hotel at approximately **6:30–7:00 AM** depending on hotel location and Delhi morning traffic. The station has a clean waiting lounge and platform amenities. Arrive at the station at least **20 minutes before departure** (8:10 AM). For hotels in south Delhi (Saket, Hauz Khas, Defence Colony), the station is very conveniently located." },
      { question: "What time do I return to Delhi on the Taj Mahal train tour?", answer: "The return Gatimaan Express (Train 12049) departs Agra Cantt at **5:50 PM** and arrives at Hazrat Nizamuddin Station, Delhi at **7:30 PM**. Your driver then transfers you from the station to your Delhi hotel, arriving at approximately **8:00–8:30 PM** depending on hotel location and evening traffic. This gives you a full **8 hours in Agra** (arrival 9:50 AM, departure 5:50 PM) — more than enough for a complete Taj Mahal visit, lunch, and Agra Fort. If you have an evening flight from Delhi airport (DEL), the driver can take you directly to the airport instead of your hotel — confirm this at booking." },
      { question: "Can I visit other Agra sites besides the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort?", answer: "With **8 hours** in Agra, you can comfortably add one or two additional sites beyond the Taj Mahal and Agra Fort. Popular additions: **Mehtab Bagh** (₹300 entry — garden across the Yamuna River with a spectacular Taj Mahal backdrop, excellent for photography), **Itmad-ud-Daula** (₹110/₹210 — the 'Baby Taj,' an exquisite marble tomb predating the Taj Mahal), or **Fatehpur Sikri** (₹50/₹550 — Emperor Akbar's abandoned city, 37 km outside Agra, adds ~2 hours). Discuss your priorities with your guide at the start of the day. For a separate comprehensive Agra experience, see the [Taj Mahal entry ticket tour](/india/agra/taj-mahal-entry-ticket)." },
      { question: "Is the Taj Mahal train tour better than driving from Delhi to Agra?", answer: "The Gatimaan Express train tour offers several advantages over driving: **Speed** — 1 hour 40 minutes by train versus 3–3.5 hours by car (each way), saving **3+ hours** of total travel time. **Comfort** — airline-style reclining seats with onboard meals versus sitting in a car through highway traffic. **Reliability** — trains run on schedule regardless of Delhi's unpredictable traffic jams, road construction, or accidents on the Yamuna Expressway. **Experience** — the Gatimaan Express itself is a uniquely Indian travel experience. The only advantage of driving is door-to-door convenience and flexibility for stops (such as Mathura or Sikandra en route). For driving options, consider the [Delhi to Agra private tour](/india/delhi/delhi-agra-private-tour)." },
      { question: "Is the Taj Mahal superfast tour suitable for families with children?", answer: "Yes — the train tour is excellent for families. Children enjoy the **Gatimaan Express experience** (India's fastest train), and the total walking at the Taj Mahal is approximately **1.5 km on flat ground** — manageable for children aged 5+. **Children under 5** travel free on Indian Railways (without a separate seat). Children aged **5–11** receive a **50% discount** on train tickets. Entry to the Taj Mahal is free for children under 15. The guide adjusts commentary for families, highlighting stories and details that engage younger visitors. The private vehicle in Agra can accommodate car seats if brought along. The day is long (12+ hours door to door) but punctuated by varied activities that keep children engaged." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'delhi-to-jaipur-same-day-tour-by-car') {
    return [
      { question: "How long is the drive from Delhi to Jaipur by car?", answer: "The drive from Delhi to Jaipur is approximately **270 km via NH48** (Delhi-Jaipur Expressway) and takes **4.5–5 hours** each way under normal conditions. The route is entirely on a well-maintained national highway and expressway, with smooth divided carriageway for most of the distance. Departure from your Delhi hotel is at **5:30–6:00 AM** to arrive in Jaipur by **10:30–11:00 AM**, allowing a full day of sightseeing before the return drive departing Jaipur at approximately **5:00–5:30 PM**, reaching Delhi by **10:00–10:30 PM**. A brief stop for tea/coffee and breakfast is made en route at a highway restaurant (approximately 30 minutes)." },
      { question: "What monuments and attractions are included in the Jaipur same-day tour?", answer: "The day covers Jaipur's top highlights: **Amber Fort** (the massive 16th-century hilltop fortress — the crown jewel of Jaipur, featuring Sheesh Mahal mirror palace, Diwan-i-Khas, and panoramic views; ~1.5 hours), **City Palace** (the Maharaja's residence with museums, courtyards, and the famous oversized silver urns; ~1 hour), **Jantar Mantar** (UNESCO-listed 18th-century astronomical observatory with the world's largest stone sundial; ~30 minutes), and **Hawa Mahal** (Palace of Winds — a photo stop at the iconic pink sandstone facade; ~15 minutes). Time permitting, Jal Mahal (Water Palace, photo stop) and the vibrant **Johari Bazaar** for shopping are also included. For a deeper Jaipur experience, consider our [Amber Fort guided tour](/india/jaipur/amber-fort-official-guided-tour)." },
      { question: "What type of AC car is provided for the Delhi to Jaipur tour?", answer: "A **private air-conditioned sedan** (Toyota Etios, Swift Dzire, or Honda Amaze) is provided for couples and solo travellers. For groups of 3–5, a **Toyota Innova Crysta** (6-seat SUV) is used. For groups of 6–12, a **tempo traveller** (12–15 seats) is arranged. All vehicles have functioning air conditioning (essential for the Rajasthan climate), comfortable seating, adequate luggage space, and USB charging ports. The same vehicle and driver are with you for the entire day — approximately **16–17 hours** from morning pickup to evening drop-off. Bottled water is provided in the vehicle. The vehicle is well-maintained and highway-rated for the high-speed expressway driving." },
      { question: "Does the driver speak English on the Delhi to Jaipur tour?", answer: "The driver speaks **basic conversational English** — sufficient for pickup coordination, route questions, and restaurant recommendations. For detailed monument commentary and historical narration, a **separate licensed guide in Jaipur** is included in the tour package. The Jaipur guide is a Rajasthan Tourism-certified professional who meets you at the first monument (typically Amber Fort) and accompanies you through all sites, providing in-depth English commentary on the Rajput history, architecture, and cultural significance of each location. Guides speaking **French, German, Spanish, Japanese, and other languages** are available on request at booking." },
      { question: "Where is the pickup and drop-off for the Jaipur same-day tour?", answer: "Pickup and drop-off are at **your Delhi hotel, guesthouse, or Airbnb** — anywhere within Delhi NCR (National Capital Region), including Gurgaon and Noida. Airport pickup from **Indira Gandhi International Airport (DEL)** is also available if you're arriving on an early morning flight. The driver arrives at your location at **5:30–6:00 AM** with a name board. On return, you're dropped at the same location (or a different Delhi address if needed) at approximately **10:00–10:30 PM**. If you have a late-night flight, the driver can drop you directly at Delhi airport instead of your hotel — confirm this arrangement at booking." },
      { question: "What time does the Jaipur same-day tour start and end?", answer: "The tour follows this timeline: **5:30–6:00 AM** — pickup from your Delhi hotel. **7:30 AM** — highway breakfast stop (~30 minutes). **10:30–11:00 AM** — arrival in Jaipur, begin sightseeing. **11:00 AM–4:30 PM** — Jaipur sightseeing with guided visits to Amber Fort, City Palace, Jantar Mantar, Hawa Mahal, and lunch. **5:00–5:30 PM** — depart Jaipur for Delhi. **10:00–10:30 PM** — arrive back at your Delhi hotel. Total tour duration is approximately **16–17 hours**, with **5.5–6 hours of active sightseeing** in Jaipur. The early start is essential to maximize time in Jaipur given the 5-hour drive each way." },
      { question: "Is a guide included in the Delhi to Jaipur same-day tour?", answer: "Yes — a **Rajasthan Tourism-certified licensed guide** is included for all Jaipur monuments. The guide meets you at the first site (typically Amber Fort around 10:30–11:00 AM) and accompanies you through the entire Jaipur sightseeing portion — approximately **5–6 hours** of guided touring. The guide provides expert commentary on Rajput history, the Kachwaha dynasty, Amber Fort's construction and design, the astronomical instruments at Jantar Mantar, and the significance of the Pink City designation. Without a guide, the historical depth and architectural details of Jaipur's monuments are largely inaccessible. The guide also assists with entry tickets and navigating crowded areas." },
      { question: "Are monument entry tickets included in the Jaipur day tour price?", answer: "Yes — **all entry tickets** are included: Amber Fort (**₹100 Indian / ₹500 foreign nationals**), City Palace (**₹200/₹500**), Jantar Mantar (**₹50/₹200**), and Hawa Mahal (**₹50/₹200**). A composite ticket covering Amber Fort, Jantar Mantar, Hawa Mahal, Nahargarh Fort, and Albert Hall Museum is available for **₹100/₹1,000** — your guide arranges whichever option provides the best value for your itinerary. Camera fees at all monuments are also included. The total ticket value for foreign nationals is approximately **₹1,400–₹2,000**, all pre-purchased so you skip the ticket queues." },
      { question: "Is one day enough to see Jaipur properly?", answer: "One day covers Jaipur's **essential highlights** comprehensively — Amber Fort, City Palace, Jantar Mantar, and Hawa Mahal are all within a compact area of the old city and can be visited thoroughly in **5–6 hours**. However, Jaipur has much more to offer beyond the core sites: Nahargarh Fort (sunset views), Albert Hall Museum, Jaigarh Fort (home to the world's largest cannon on wheels), the bazaars of Johari Bazaar and Bapu Bazaar, and the step wells of Chand Baori (95 km outside Jaipur). For travellers with more time, an overnight stay in Jaipur is recommended. For a multi-day experience, consider the [Golden Triangle tour from Delhi](/india/delhi/delhi-private-4-day-golden-triangle-luxury-tour)." },
      { question: "Are toll charges and parking fees included in the Delhi to Jaipur tour?", answer: "Yes — **all toll charges, parking fees, and fuel costs** are included in the tour price. The Delhi-Jaipur Expressway has multiple toll plazas totalling approximately **₹800–₹1,000** in toll charges (round trip). Parking fees at Amber Fort, City Palace, and other Jaipur monuments are approximately **₹100–₹200** per site. Driver meals, overnight allowance, and state permits (required for vehicles crossing state borders from Delhi to Rajasthan) are all included. There are **no hidden costs** — the quoted price is fully inclusive of vehicle, driver, fuel, tolls, parking, guide, entry tickets, and all applicable taxes. Lunch is the only item typically paid separately." },
      { question: "Can I combine the Jaipur day trip with other Delhi tours?", answer: "Absolutely — the Jaipur same-day tour pairs perfectly with Delhi sightseeing on adjacent days. Many travellers do the [Delhi full-day guided tour](/india/delhi/delhi-full-day-guided-tour) on Day 1 (covering Old Delhi and New Delhi) and the Jaipur same-day trip on Day 2. Another popular combination is this Jaipur tour followed by the [Taj Mahal superfast train tour](/india/delhi/taj-mahal-superfast-guided-tour) on the next day — covering all three Golden Triangle cities as day trips from Delhi without needing to change hotels. For a guided Delhi overview with shopping, see our [Delhi guided shopping tour](/india/delhi/delhi-guided-shopping-tour-female-expert)." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'delhi-same-day-sightseeing-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "What monuments are covered on the Delhi same-day sightseeing tour?", answer: "The full-day Delhi sightseeing tour covers **8–10 major monuments** across both Old Delhi and New Delhi: **Old Delhi** — Red Fort (UNESCO, Mughal fortress), Jama Masjid (India's largest mosque, built 1656), Chandni Chowk (17th-century bazaar with cycle-rickshaw ride), and Raj Ghat (Mahatma Gandhi memorial). **New Delhi** — India Gate (war memorial), Rashtrapati Bhavan/Parliament House (drive-past), Humayun's Tomb (UNESCO, 1570 precursor to the Taj Mahal), Qutub Minar (UNESCO, 73-metre 12th-century minaret), and Lotus Temple (Bahá'í House of Worship). The tour provides a comprehensive sweep of Delhi's **3,000+ year history** from the medieval Delhi Sultanate through the Mughal Empire to British-era New Delhi and modern India." },
      { question: "Is the Delhi same-day sightseeing tour a full-day or half-day tour?", answer: "This is a **full-day tour** running approximately **9–10 hours** from hotel pickup to hotel drop-off. Typical timings are **8:30–9:00 AM pickup** and **6:00–7:00 PM return**. The full day is necessary to properly cover both Old Delhi and New Delhi, which are geographically separated and each contain multiple major sites. A sit-down lunch break (approximately 1 hour) is included midday. If you have limited time, we also offer a [Delhi half-day sightseeing tour](/india/delhi/delhi-sightseeing-half-day-tour) covering 4–5 highlights in approximately **4–5 hours**. The full-day tour is strongly recommended for first-time visitors who want a comprehensive Delhi experience." },
      { question: "What type of transport is used for the Delhi sightseeing tour?", answer: "A **private air-conditioned vehicle** is provided for the entire day — typically a Toyota Innova Crysta (6-seat SUV) for groups of 3–5, or a sedan (Swift Dzire/Honda Amaze) for couples and solo travellers. The vehicle remains exclusively with your group throughout the day, serving as a cool, comfortable base between monument visits. Delhi's distances between major sites are significant — **Qutub Minar to Red Fort is 18 km**, and navigating Delhi's traffic independently is challenging. The driver knows all monument parking areas, one-way restrictions, and traffic patterns. For a luxury vehicle upgrade (Mercedes, BMW, or Audi), see the [Explore Delhi luxury car tour](/india/delhi/explore-old-new-delhi-city-luxury-car-tour)." },
      { question: "Is a licensed guide included in the Delhi sightseeing tour?", answer: "Yes — a **Ministry of Tourism-licensed professional guide** accompanies you throughout the entire day. Delhi's complex layered history — 8 successive cities built on the same site, ruled by Turko-Afghan sultans, Mughals, the British Empire, and the Indian republic — requires expert narration to fully appreciate. Your guide provides the chronological thread connecting each site: how Humayun's Tomb (1570) directly inspired the Taj Mahal (1632), why the British moved the capital from Calcutta to Delhi in 1911, and how Shah Jahan's Red Fort became the symbol of Indian independence. Guides are available in **English, Hindi, French, German, Spanish, Japanese**, and other languages on request." },
      { question: "Are monument entry tickets included in the Delhi sightseeing tour?", answer: "Yes — **all monument entry tickets** are included in the tour price: Red Fort (₹35 Indian / ₹500 foreign), Humayun's Tomb (₹35/₹550), Qutub Minar (₹35/₹550), Jama Masjid (free entry, ₹300 camera fee included), and Lotus Temple (free entry). The total ticket value for foreign nationals is approximately **₹1,900–₹2,100**. All tickets are pre-purchased by your guide, so you **skip the ticket queues** at every monument — a significant time-saver, especially at popular sites like Humayun's Tomb and Qutub Minar where queues can exceed 20–30 minutes during peak season. India Gate and Raj Ghat are free to visit." },
      { question: "Does the tour cover both Old Delhi and New Delhi?", answer: "Yes — the tour comprehensively covers **both Old Delhi and New Delhi**, which are historically and geographically distinct parts of the city. **Old Delhi (Shahjahanabad)** — founded in 1638 by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan — is a dense, vibrant, sensory-rich experience of narrow lanes, bazaars, mosques, and the Red Fort. **New Delhi** — designed by British architects Edwin Lutyens and Herbert Baker in the 1910s–1930s — is a spacious, tree-lined city of grand colonial boulevards, government buildings, and pre-Mughal monuments (Humayun's Tomb, Qutub Minar). The contrast between the two Delhis is extraordinary and forms one of the most fascinating aspects of the tour. Most tours begin in Old Delhi (morning energy) and move to New Delhi in the afternoon." },
      { question: "Is the Delhi sightseeing tour recommended for first-time visitors to India?", answer: "The Delhi same-day sightseeing tour is **specifically designed for first-time India visitors** and is the most popular Delhi tour for international travellers. Delhi can be overwhelming to navigate independently — the traffic, the distances between sites, the complexity of monument ticketing, and the intensity of Old Delhi's bazaars. A private guide and vehicle create a comfortable, managed framework that allows you to absorb and enjoy the city. Your guide provides cultural context, photography tips, and practical advice throughout the day. By evening, first-time visitors typically feel significantly more comfortable and confident about their India journey. For a detailed planning guide, see our [Delhi travel guide 2026](/india/delhi/delhi-travel-guide-2026)." },
      { question: "Does the Delhi sightseeing tour include hotel pickup?", answer: "Yes — **complimentary pickup and drop-off** at your Delhi hotel, guesthouse, or Airbnb is included. The driver arrives at your accommodation at **8:30–9:00 AM** with a name board displaying your name. Pickup is available from anywhere within Delhi NCR, including central Delhi (Connaught Place, Paharganj, Karol Bagh), south Delhi (Hauz Khas, Saket, Greater Kailash), and the airport area (Aerocity, Mahipalpur). Pickup from **Gurgaon and Noida** is also available with a small surcharge (₹300–₹500). If you're arriving at Delhi airport on a morning flight, airport pickup can be arranged — confirm your flight details at booking." },
      { question: "Is lunch included in the Delhi same-day sightseeing tour?", answer: "Yes — a **sit-down lunch** at a quality Delhi restaurant is included, typically served between the Old Delhi and New Delhi portions of the tour (around **1:00–2:00 PM**). The restaurant serves authentic North Indian and Mughlai cuisine — butter chicken, dal makhani, biryani, kebabs, fresh tandoori naan — with comprehensive vegetarian, vegan, Jain, halal, and allergen-aware options. Delhi is one of India's great food cities, and the lunch is a culinary highlight rather than a generic tourist meal. For travellers with specific food interests, your guide can recommend Old Delhi street food stops (Karim's, Paranthe Wali Gali) as additions to the standard lunch." },
      { question: "Is the Delhi same-day sightseeing tour suitable for families with children?", answer: "Yes — the tour is **excellent for families** and suitable for children aged **5 and above**. Highlights that particularly engage children include the **cycle-rickshaw ride** through Chandni Chowk (exciting and fun), the grand scale of the **Red Fort** (kids love exploring the ramparts), **India Gate** (open lawns for a brief run-around), and the futuristic **Lotus Temple** (the petal-shaped architecture fascinates children). The private vehicle allows for flexible breaks — ice cream stops, restroom breaks, and energy recharges as needed. **Children under 15** receive free entry at most Indian monuments. The guide adjusts commentary for families, using stories and legends that captivate younger visitors. For other family-friendly Delhi options, see [things to do in Delhi](/india/delhi/things-to-do-in-delhi)." },
      { question: "What is the best time of year to take the Delhi sightseeing tour?", answer: "**October to March** is the ideal season for Delhi sightseeing: cool, clear days with temperatures of **15–28°C**, comfortable for extensive outdoor walking at monuments. **November and February** are particularly pleasant. December–January can bring morning fog, which creates atmospheric photography conditions at Humayun's Tomb and Qutub Minar. **April–June** is hot (**35–46°C**) but manageable with early starts (7:00 AM pickup) and the air-conditioned vehicle providing relief between sites. **July–September** (monsoon) brings rain and humidity but also dramatic skies and lush green gardens — monuments are less crowded. The tour operates year-round; guides adjust the itinerary sequence to manage heat and weather conditions." }
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'delhi-sightseeing-half-day-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "Is the Delhi half-day sightseeing tour available in the morning or afternoon?", answer: "The half-day tour is available in **both morning and afternoon** slots. The **morning slot** (8:00–8:30 AM pickup, return by 1:00–1:30 PM) is the most popular and recommended — cooler temperatures, better light for photography, and more energetic bazaar scenes in Old Delhi. The **afternoon slot** (1:30–2:00 PM pickup, return by 6:30–7:00 PM) is ideal for travellers arriving on morning flights or those who want a relaxed morning before sightseeing. Both slots cover the same core monuments and run approximately **4.5–5 hours**. The morning slot is particularly recommended during the hotter months (April–June) to avoid peak afternoon heat." },
      { question: "Which monuments are included in the Delhi half-day tour?", answer: "The half-day tour covers **4–5 essential Delhi highlights**, strategically selected for maximum impact in limited time. **Option A (Old Delhi focus):** Jama Masjid, Red Fort (exterior and ramparts), Chandni Chowk cycle-rickshaw ride, Raj Ghat (Gandhi memorial), and a drive past India Gate. **Option B (New Delhi focus):** Humayun's Tomb (UNESCO), Qutub Minar (UNESCO), Lotus Temple, India Gate, and a drive past Parliament House and Rashtrapati Bhavan. You choose your preferred focus at booking, or your guide recommends based on your interests. Most first-time visitors choose **Option A** for its immersive, sensory-rich Old Delhi experience. For comprehensive coverage of both, upgrade to the [full-day Delhi sightseeing tour](/india/delhi/delhi-same-day-sightseeing-tour)." },
      { question: "How long is the Delhi half-day sightseeing tour?", answer: "The half-day tour runs approximately **4.5–5 hours** from hotel pickup to hotel drop-off. This allows **30–60 minutes** at each of the 4–5 included monuments, plus transit time between sites in your private air-conditioned vehicle. The pace is efficient but not rushed — your guide ensures you see the essential highlights, hear the key historical narratives, and have time for photography at each location. The half-day format is specifically designed for travellers with limited time — those on a layover, business travellers with a free half-day, or visitors who want to combine the tour with other activities (shopping, food tours, or a day trip to Agra or Jaipur)." },
      { question: "Is the Delhi half-day tour private or shared with other tourists?", answer: "This is a **fully private tour** — you travel exclusively with your own guide and driver, with no other tourists in your vehicle or group. The private format allows complete flexibility: if you want to spend extra time at Humayun's Tomb for photography, or skip a site to explore Chandni Chowk's lanes in more depth, the itinerary adjusts to your preferences. Private touring is particularly valuable in Delhi, where navigating the city, managing touts outside monuments, and finding optimal photography positions all benefit from a dedicated guide's attention. The private vehicle (air-conditioned sedan or SUV) is your mobile comfort base between sites." },
      { question: "What is the difference between the half-day and full-day Delhi tours?", answer: "The **half-day tour** (4.5–5 hours) covers **4–5 monuments** in either Old Delhi or New Delhi, while the [full-day tour](/india/delhi/delhi-same-day-sightseeing-tour) (9–10 hours) covers **8–10 monuments** across both Old and New Delhi plus includes lunch. Specifically, the full-day tour adds: the Chandni Chowk cycle-rickshaw ride AND the New Delhi UNESCO sites (or vice versa), Raj Ghat, a sit-down lunch, and more time at each monument. The full-day tour provides the complete Delhi narrative — the historical arc from the 12th-century Sultanate (Qutub Minar) through the Mughal Empire (Red Fort, Humayun's Tomb) to the British Raj (India Gate, Lutyens' Delhi) and modern India (Lotus Temple). The half-day is a highlight reel; the full day is the complete story." },
      { question: "Is the Delhi half-day tour suitable for airport layovers?", answer: "Yes — the half-day tour is **ideal for airport layovers** of **8 hours or more** (international-to-international or international-to-domestic connections). With a 4.5–5 hour tour duration plus approximately **1.5–2 hours** for airport transfers (Indira Gandhi International Airport is 15–25 km from central Delhi), you need a minimum of **7–8 hours** between flights. The driver picks you up at the airport arrivals terminal and returns you to the departures terminal. For layovers of 5–6 hours, a condensed 3-hour version covering 2–3 sites is available. Carry your passport, boarding pass, and checked luggage receipt — your guide assists with all logistics. For a detailed layover planning guide, see [Delhi 1-day itinerary](/india/delhi/delhi-1-day-itinerary)." },
      { question: "Can the Delhi half-day tour include airport pickup?", answer: "Yes — **airport pickup from Indira Gandhi International Airport (DEL)** is included at no extra charge. The driver meets you at the arrivals terminal with a name board after you clear immigration and customs. For the morning slot, pickup is typically at **8:00–8:30 AM** (suitable for travellers who arrived on an early morning or overnight flight). For afternoon tours, airport pickup at **1:30–2:00 PM** works for late-morning arrivals. The tour can also **end at the airport** rather than your hotel if you have an evening departure. One-way airport transfers (pickup at airport, drop at hotel, or vice versa) are seamlessly integrated into the tour routing." },
      { question: "What languages do the guides speak on the Delhi half-day tour?", answer: "All guides are **Ministry of Tourism-licensed professionals** with fluency in **English** as the default language. Guides speaking **French, German, Spanish, Italian, Portuguese, Japanese, Mandarin, Korean, Russian, and Arabic** are available on advance request (typically 48–72 hours notice for non-English languages). The English-speaking guides have extensive experience with international visitors and speak clearly and articulately — accustomed to adjusting pace and vocabulary for non-native English speakers. Guides provide not just monument narration but also cultural context — explaining local customs, religious practices, and daily life in Delhi, which is invaluable for short-stay visitors." },
      { question: "Is the vehicle air-conditioned on the Delhi half-day tour?", answer: "Yes — a **fully air-conditioned private vehicle** is provided for the entire tour. Vehicle types: **sedan** (Toyota Etios, Swift Dzire, or Honda Amaze) for 1–2 passengers, **SUV** (Toyota Innova Crysta, 6 seats) for groups of 3–5, or **tempo traveller** (12–15 seats) for larger groups. Delhi temperatures range from **5–15°C in winter** (December–January) to **40–46°C in summer** (May–June), making air conditioning essential for most of the year. The vehicle has tinted windows for privacy, USB charging ports, and bottled water. Between monument visits, the air-conditioned car provides a refreshing break, especially during the warmer months." },
      { question: "What are the must-see highlights if I only have half a day in Delhi?", answer: "If you have only half a day, prioritize these **4 unmissable Delhi highlights**: (1) **Humayun's Tomb** — the most architecturally significant monument in Delhi, a UNESCO World Heritage Site that directly inspired the Taj Mahal; (2) **Qutub Minar** — the 73-metre, 12th-century minaret, India's earliest Islamic monument; (3) **Chandni Chowk + Jama Masjid** — the sensory heart of Old Delhi, combining the 17th-century bazaar with India's largest mosque; and (4) **India Gate** — the iconic 1931 war memorial on Rajpath. These four sites provide a concentrated narrative of Delhi's major historical periods. Your guide recommends the optimal sequence based on your pickup location and traffic conditions. For a full exploration, book the [Old & New Delhi guided tour](/india/delhi/old-new-delhi-guided-tour)." },
      { question: "What should I wear on the Delhi half-day sightseeing tour?", answer: "Dress comfortably with these considerations: **Footwear** — comfortable walking shoes are essential (you walk approximately **2–3 km total** across monument visits, on stone and marble surfaces). **Clothing** — modest dress is recommended for religious sites: at Jama Masjid, women should cover shoulders and knees (scarves are available to borrow at the entrance). At Sikh gurudwaras (if included), both men and women must cover their heads (head coverings provided). **Weather** — light, breathable layers for October–March; sun hat, sunscreen, and loose-fitting clothes for April–September. **Sun protection** — sunglasses and SPF 50+ sunscreen are recommended year-round, as Delhi gets intense sun even in winter. Your guide carries a first-aid kit and extra water." }
    ];
  }

  // --- END ADDITIONAL DELHI TOUR FAQS (6 TOURS) ---

  // --- BANGKOK TOURS ---

  if (slug === 'bangkok-grand-palace-wat-pho-wat-arun-guided-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "How long is the Grand Palace, Wat Pho and Wat Arun tour?", answer: "The tour runs approximately **4 to 5 hours**, covering all three of Bangkok's most iconic temples in a single guided walk. You will spend about 90 minutes at the Grand Palace and Wat Phra Kaew, 75 minutes at Wat Pho (Reclining Buddha), and about 70 minutes at Wat Arun. The pace is comfortable and allows plenty of time for photos, questions and exploring each site thoroughly. Most tours begin at 9:00 AM, which helps you beat the worst of the midday heat." },
      { question: "Are the entrance fees included in the tour price?", answer: "Yes, **all entrance fees are included** in the tour price. This covers entry to the Grand Palace and Wat Phra Kaew (normally **500 baht** per person), Wat Pho (normally **300 baht**), and Wat Arun (normally **100 baht**). The traditional boat ride across the Chao Phraya River is also included. Having everything prepaid means you skip the ticket queues at each temple and walk straight in with your guide." },
      { question: "What is the dress code for visiting the Grand Palace?", answer: "All three temples require **modest dress**. Shoulders and knees must be covered for both men and women. No tank tops, shorts, miniskirts, see-through clothing or open-toed sandals. If you arrive underdressed, sarongs and cover-ups are available to borrow at the Grand Palace entrance, but they can be uncomfortable in the heat. We recommend wearing lightweight, breathable clothing that covers your shoulders and knees. Long cotton pants or a maxi skirt with a t-shirt works perfectly. Comfortable closed-toe shoes are also recommended since you will be walking on stone and marble surfaces for several hours." },
      { question: "Is hotel pickup included in this tour?", answer: "No, this tour does not include hotel pickup. You meet the guide at the **Grand Palace main entrance**, near the Tha Chang Pier. The meeting point is easy to reach by taxi, Grab, tuk-tuk, or the Chao Phraya Express Boat. If you are staying near the river or in the Khaosan Road area, you can walk there in about 15 minutes. The guide will send you a WhatsApp message with exact meeting instructions the day before the tour." },
      { question: "What is the best time to visit the Grand Palace in Bangkok?", answer: "The best time is **early morning**, between 8:30 and 9:30 AM. The Grand Palace opens at 8:30 AM and the first hour is the least crowded. By 10:30 AM large tour bus groups start arriving and it gets significantly busier. Our tour is designed to start at 9:00 AM so you experience the Grand Palace during the cooler, quieter morning hours. If you are visiting between November and February (cool season), any morning time is pleasant. Between March and May (hot season), starting early is essential since temperatures can reach 35 to 38 degrees by midday." },
      { question: "Can children join this tour?", answer: "Yes, children of all ages are welcome. Children under **120 cm tall** get free entry to the Grand Palace. The walking distance is approximately 3 to 4 km total across all three temples, so children should be comfortable walking for a few hours with breaks in between. The boat ride across the river to Wat Arun is usually a highlight for younger visitors. Strollers are not practical at the temples due to steps and uneven surfaces. The guide adjusts the pace and commentary for families with children." },
      { question: "What is the difference between the Grand Palace and Wat Phra Kaew?", answer: "They are part of the same complex but serve different purposes. The **Grand Palace** is the former royal residence, a sprawling compound of throne halls, pavilions and government buildings built in 1782. **Wat Phra Kaew** (Temple of the Emerald Buddha) sits within the Grand Palace grounds and is Thailand's most sacred Buddhist temple. It houses the Emerald Buddha, a 66 cm jade statue dressed in gold seasonal robes that only the King of Thailand is permitted to change. You visit both with the same entrance ticket. The Grand Palace showcases royal and political history, while Wat Phra Kaew is the spiritual heart of the nation." },
      { question: "How do you get from Wat Pho to Wat Arun?", answer: "You cross the **Chao Phraya River** by traditional wooden boat. The crossing takes about 5 to 10 minutes and departs from the pier near Wat Pho (Tha Tien Pier). The boat ride is included in the tour price. It is a scenic crossing with views of the river, the Bangkok skyline and riverside temples. The boats run frequently so there is usually no waiting. Wat Arun sits on the opposite (west) bank of the river. After visiting Wat Arun, you can take the same boat back or continue exploring the Thonburi side independently." },
      { question: "Is the climb to the top of Wat Arun steep?", answer: "Yes, the steps at Wat Arun are **quite steep** and narrow. The main prang (spire) has steps at a roughly 45 degree angle leading to the upper terrace at about 30 metres high. There are handrails on both sides. The climb is optional and takes about 5 minutes each way. The reward is a panoramic 360 degree view over the Chao Phraya River, the Grand Palace across the water, and the Bangkok skyline. If you are uncomfortable with heights or steep stairs, you can skip the climb and still enjoy the beautiful mosaic work and grounds at the base level. Your guide will wait for you either way." },
      { question: "Is this tour suitable for first-time visitors to Bangkok?", answer: "This tour is **ideal for first-time visitors** and is the most popular guided tour in Bangkok. The Grand Palace, Wat Pho and Wat Arun are the three most important historical and cultural landmarks in the city. Visiting them with a knowledgeable local guide gives you essential context about Thai Buddhism, royal history and temple architecture that would be impossible to get on your own. Most visitors say it completely changed their understanding and appreciation of Bangkok. We recommend doing this tour on your first or second day to set the cultural foundation for the rest of your trip." },
      { question: "How big is the group on this tour?", answer: "This is a **small group tour** with a maximum of **10 people**. Most departures have between 4 and 8 guests. The small group size means you can actually hear the guide, ask questions freely, and move through the temples at a comfortable pace without getting lost in a crowd. It is a very different experience from the large bus tour groups of 30 to 40 people that you will see at the Grand Palace. The guide gives personalized attention and can adjust the pace and focus based on the group's interests." },
      { question: "What should I bring on the temple tour?", answer: "We recommend bringing: **comfortable walking shoes** (you will walk 3 to 4 km on stone and marble surfaces), **sunscreen and a hat** (most of the Grand Palace grounds have no shade), **a small bottle of water** (bottled water is provided but extra is helpful in the heat), **a camera or phone** (photography is allowed everywhere except inside the Emerald Buddha hall), and **a small amount of cash** for any personal purchases. Leave large bags at your hotel if possible. Lockers are available at the Grand Palace entrance for a small fee if needed." },
    ];
  }

  if (slug === 'bangkok-maeklong-railway-damnoen-saduak-dragon-temple-tour') {
    return [
      { question: "How long is the Maeklong Railway Market, Floating Market and Dragon Temple tour?", answer: "The full day tour runs approximately **8 to 9 hours** from hotel pickup to hotel drop-off. Pickup starts between 7:00 and 8:50 AM depending on your hotel location, and you return to Bangkok by approximately 4:00 to 4:30 PM. The tour includes about 60 minutes at Maeklong Railway Market, 75 minutes at Damnoen Saduak Floating Market, and 60 minutes at the Dragon Temple, with driving time between stops." },
      { question: "What time does the train pass through Maeklong Market?", answer: "The train passes through Maeklong Railway Market **8 times per day**, roughly every 2 to 3 hours. The most common morning times are around **8:30 AM** and **11:10 AM**. Your guide times the visit to coincide with one of these train arrivals so you see the full spectacle of vendors folding up their stalls. The train horn sounds about 2 minutes before arrival, giving vendors time to pull back their awnings and goods. The whole process takes about 3 to 4 minutes and then everything goes back to normal within seconds. It is one of the most unique things you will see in Thailand." },
      { question: "Is the floating market at Damnoen Saduak touristy?", answer: "Damnoen Saduak is **Thailand's most famous floating market** and yes, it attracts tourists. That said, it is still a genuine, operating market where locals sell real produce, fresh food and handmade goods from their boats. The atmosphere is lively and colourful. The longtail boat ride through the narrow canals is the best way to experience it. Prices at the market are slightly higher than in Bangkok but you can bargain. Bring **Thai baht in small bills** (20, 50 and 100 baht notes) as vendors often cannot make change for large notes. The best food buys are fresh coconut ice cream, mango sticky rice, pad thai and grilled seafood." },
      { question: "What is the Dragon Temple and where is it?", answer: "Wat Samphran, commonly called the **Dragon Temple**, is located in Nakhon Pathom province about 40 km west of Bangkok. It features a striking **17-storey pink cylindrical tower** wrapped by a massive green and gold dragon sculpture that spirals from the base to the top. You can walk through a tunnel inside the dragon and climb the tower for panoramic countryside views. The temple was built in the 1980s and is one of the most unique and photogenic temples in Thailand. Unlike Bangkok's famous temples, the Dragon Temple is still relatively unknown to international tourists, so it is usually quiet and uncrowded." },
      { question: "Is hotel pickup included in this tour?", answer: "Yes, **complimentary hotel pickup and drop-off** is included for hotels within 8 km driving distance of Khaosan Road and the Rambuttri area. If your hotel is outside this zone, you can meet the group at one of five central Bangkok pickup points: **Pratunam Market** (07:10 AM), **Chinatown Yaowarat** (07:30 AM), **MRT Sam Yot Station Exit 3** (08:00 AM), **Khaosan Road** at Lampoo Ocean Travel (08:30 AM), or **Central Pinklao** (08:50 AM). Your exact pickup time is confirmed via WhatsApp the day before the tour." },
      { question: "What type of vehicle is used for transportation?", answer: "The tour uses a **comfortable air-conditioned van** for all transportation. The drive from Bangkok to the first stop (Maeklong) takes approximately 60 to 90 minutes depending on morning traffic. The van has reclining seats, tinted windows and USB charging ports. Since this is a shared group tour with a maximum of 12 guests, the van makes several hotel pickup stops before leaving Bangkok. The total pickup process can take 60 to 90 minutes, so bring something to read or listen to for the morning drive." },
      { question: "Is the longtail boat ride at Damnoen Saduak included?", answer: "Yes, the **longtail boat ride** through the canals of Damnoen Saduak Floating Market is included in the tour price. The boat cruise lasts about 20 to 30 minutes and takes you through the narrow waterways lined with wooden houses and market stalls. Vendors paddle up alongside your boat selling fruits, drinks and souvenirs. The boat has a canopy for shade. This is the traditional and best way to experience the floating market, rather than walking the concrete paths along the canal edges." },
      { question: "Can you climb inside the Dragon Temple tower?", answer: "Yes, you can **walk through the dragon tunnel** inside the tower and climb the stairs toward the upper levels. The dragon's body forms a tunnel that wraps around the outside of the cylindrical tower. Some sections are steep and narrow, so wear comfortable shoes with good grip. The climb rewards you with **panoramic views** of the Nakhon Pathom countryside and surrounding temples. The climb is optional and suitable for anyone with reasonable fitness. There are rest points along the way. The interior also contains Buddha statues and small shrines at various levels." },
      { question: "Is lunch included in the tour?", answer: "Lunch is **not included** in the tour price, but both markets offer excellent and affordable food options. At Damnoen Saduak Floating Market you can buy fresh pad thai, grilled seafood, coconut ice cream, mango sticky rice and tropical fruit smoothies directly from the boat vendors, with most items costing **30 to 80 baht** (about $1 to $2.50). At Maeklong Railway Market there are also food stalls selling grilled meats, fresh fruit and Thai snacks. Your guide can recommend the best food vendors at each market. Bring at least **300 to 500 baht** in small bills for food and purchases." },
      { question: "Is this tour suitable for children?", answer: "Yes, children aged **5 and above** will enjoy this tour. The train passing through Maeklong Market is exciting and memorable for kids. The longtail boat ride is fun and safe (life jackets available). The Dragon Temple's dragon tunnel feels like an adventure. That said, the tour involves an early morning start (7:00 to 8:50 AM pickup) and a long day with several hours of driving. Very young children or toddlers may find the day tiring. The van has air conditioning and there are restroom stops between each attraction. Children under 120 cm typically get free or reduced entry at the Dragon Temple." },
      { question: "What should I wear and bring on this tour?", answer: "Wear **comfortable walking shoes** and lightweight clothing. At the Dragon Temple, shoulders and knees should be covered (standard Thai temple dress code). Bring **sunscreen, a hat and sunglasses** as much of the tour is outdoors. Pack **Thai baht in small bills** (500 baht minimum recommended) for food and market purchases. A **light rain jacket** is advisable during rainy season (June to October). Bring your camera or phone as all three stops are extremely photogenic. A small backpack is more practical than a handbag since you will be getting in and out of boats and vans throughout the day." },
      { question: "What is the best time of year for this tour?", answer: "This tour operates year-round but the best months are **November to February** (cool season) when temperatures are comfortable at 25 to 32 degrees with low humidity and clear skies. **March to May** (hot season) is very hot, reaching 35 to 38 degrees, so bring extra water and sun protection. **June to October** (rainy season) can bring afternoon showers but mornings are usually dry and the markets are less crowded. The floating market and railway market are covered or have shade, so rain rarely cancels the tour. The Dragon Temple is best photographed in morning light regardless of season." },
    ];
  }

  // --- END BANGKOK TOUR FAQS ---

  return null;
